<HEADLINE>Teachers' vain bid to save pupil</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By LYNNE ROBERTSON
A 17-year-old schoolboy collapsed and later died while watching a rugby match
at Loretto School in Musselburgh, East Lothian, yesterday.
Pupils watched as staff and a doctor tried in vain to resuscitate John Kelsey,
a boarder at the school, before paramedics arrived. He was taken by ambulance
to Edinburgh Royal Infirmary, where he later died.
Headmaster Keith Budge said the boy's parents, who live near Aberdeen, had been
informed and were travelling to Edinburgh. He said John had been studying for
A-Levels, and that pupils and staff were ``in a state of shock''.
``Parents are being contacted to ask them to take their children home early for
the weekend,'' he added.
The public school's old boys include the late MP for Perth and Kinross, Sir
Nicholas Fairbairn, and retired judge, Lord Allanbridge.
</TEXT>
