<HEADLINE>Palace turn-off for BBC?</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUCKINGHAM Palace officials, concerned over the BBC's handling of the Panorama
interview with the Princess of Wales, may consider switching the filming of the
Queen's Christmas broadcast to another channel.
Royal aides were shocked when the princess gave the Panorama interview without
informing her palace advisers.
Senior palace officials are now expressing scepticism about the BBC's
explanation of how it scooped the hour-long interview.
A palace spokesman said in a veiled threat to the BBC: ``No institution can
take for granted its relationship with the media, just as the media - and in
this case the BBC - cannot take its relationship for granted with us.''
Meanwhile, National Grid engineers have put the Dinorwic plant in Snowdonia,
north Wales, on stand-by to cope with extra demand when viewers switch on
kettles at the end of the programme on Monday.
