<HEADLINE>Fayed offer as Today closes Murdoch closes Today</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339524</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TODAY newspaper is to close after its final issue today, News International
said yesterday.
The announcement was followed by the news last night that the owner of Harrods,
Mr Mohamed Al Fayed, wants to buy the paper.
Earlier, announcing the closure, News International executive chairman Les
Hinton said: ``We deeply regret the decision to cease publication but, with a
modest circulation, insufficient growth, and rapidly rising costs, we have no
alternative.''
Mr Hinton said NI had been unable to find a ``credible'' purchaser and had
poured ``scores of millions of pounds'' into the paper ``without the necessary
result''.
A great many staff would be found jobs elsewhere in the group and the rest
would receive their full redundancy entitlements, he added.
Last night, in a remarkable open letter to News International's owner, Mr
Rupert Murdoch, Mr Al Fayed - who two months ago was in negotiations to buy the
ailing title from NI - said he was ``dismayed'' by the closure and revealed
that he renewed his offer to buy in a fax at 2pm yesterday.
He described Mr Hinton's claim that no ``credible'' owner for the title could
be found as
Continued on Page 2
Continued from Page 1
``untrue and dishonourable'' and claimed he had been treated with
``discourtesy''.
Mr Al Fayed wrote: ``I think Today can still be a national asset. It is bad for
democracy when a newspaper is killed off.
``Given the opportunity, I would have made a substantial investment to create a
great newspaper in which the whole country could have taken pride.''
Today revolutionised the British newspaper industry when it was launched in
March 1986 by Eddy Shah. It was the first national paper to use computer
technology, full-colour printing, and to dispense with the traditional printing
unions. However, although it blazed a trail for others, its own sales never
reached the level its editors hoped for.
As recently as May, Mr Murdoch appeared determined to keep the paper going.
``We see a gaping opportunity in the young, middle-class market, and we plan a
multi-million pound promotional and editorial expenditure that will add
substantial extra value and circulation,'' he said at the time.
Labour leader Tony Blair expressed his dismay at the news from Wapping. ``Under
Richard Stott's editorship, the paper ran some great campaigns, consistently
told the truth about the Tories, and became an excellent newspaper,'' he said.
A United Newspapers spokesman denied rumours that it was closing the Daily Star
and that Mr Murdoch had bought a stake in the company, which also owns the
Daily and Sunday Express.
</TEXT>
