<HEADLINE>A look in the big picture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Nina Noone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEBORAH Campbell decided when she left school that she wanted to study art; if
that proved to be impossible, her second choice was geology. Now, 12 years out
of Glasgow School of Art, she is launching her Munro Collection: a group of
Scotland's Munro mountains, painted by her and offered as fine limited edition
prints.
What Deborah Campbell has captured superbly well, is the summits of these
mountains, their uniqueness, their cliffs and corries, and eagle's-eye glimpses
of the panoramas far below. Her rocks are living and vital, capturing the
characters and complexities of the stones.
Her paintings have been sold in shops and galleries throughout Scotland.
However, as a one-woman business, she has pragmatically decided that offering
mail-order limited edition prints - to which she will add a new collection
annually - makes a lot more sense than sorties around her diverse range of
customers.
Ms Campbell started hillwalking and climbing with her father, as a child. ``I
thought I'd done about 65 Munros,'' she laughed. ``People kept asking me how
many, and when I started counting I found it was only about 50. Because I have
my favourites, I tend to go up and down these all the time.''
Ben Nevis, she thinks, is probably her favourite. ``It's a spectacular walk. It
is probably the most-climbed Munro in Scotland, but everybody tends to go up
the tourist path.''
As a Glaswegian, Ben Lomond has always been her local Munro, and therefore
amongst her favourites. ``It's probably the first Munro I ever did - like a lot
of other people. It took me three visits to get the view that I've painted,
which is from the rear of the summit, showing the cliffs towards Loch Lomond.''
Deborah Campbell's limited edition print collection numbers nine. ``Next year I
hope to produce another six, larger and smaller sizes. My panoramic print of
Ben Nevis is a limited edition of 600, for example, while Ben Lomond is 850.''
Who buys the prints? ``Climbers and hillwalkers, generally older men, and I've
sold to people for their boardrooms.''
Her eye is on the American market for her Munro collection. She is regularly
commissioned to paint murals for a firm of architects, and her work features in
such establishments as Yes and the Big Blue. She also paints naive-style
Mexican-inspired theatrical set pictures . . . entrepreneurial, talented and
diverse. Deborah Campbell's is a name to watch.
</TEXT>
