<HEADLINE>Towards Biotech Glen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCIS SHENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS APPOINTMENTS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975339526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE formal launch last week of a trust aimed at attracting #50m of extra
research funds to Scotland in only five years highlights the phenomenal growth
already taking place in the biomedical sector.
Worldwide, the market for the products of bio-technology is expected to grow
more than 25-fold to #76bn by the year 2000 from a base of only #3bn in 1990.
An estimated two million new jobs could be created in Europe in the next five
years through the introduction of bio-technology products. Last year alone
biotech companies raised more than #150m on the London Stock Exchange.
Yet Europe has only 25% of the global market, although still ahead of Japan's
20%. The clear world leader is the United States with 40%.
However, the world's pharmaceutical companies are increasingly looking for
strategic alliances and outside research laboratories as their costs spiral.
The latest estimate of the average cost of bringing a new drug to market is
#250m.
In the US 80 state-funded centres have already been established to develop the
biotech industry, including ``Genetown'' in Worcester, Massachusetts, ``Biotech
Beach'' in San Diego, and ``Biotech Bay'' in San Francisco.
Scotland, which already produces 4000 university graduates in the biomedical
sciences every year, is now setting out to establish ``Biotech Glen''.
The Scottish Biomedical Research Trust - founded by the universities of
Aberdeen, Edinburgh, Glasgow, St Andrews, Strathclyde and Paisley - will offer
a single-door approach to research and technology in the sector.
It will search for new pharmaceuticals, immunotherapies, gene therapies,
diagnostic procedures, and biomedical devices.
Among the areas of expertise already identified are research into
cardiovascular conditions, neurosciences, cancer, inflammatory diseases,
respiratory diseases, immunology, infectious diseases, bone disease, diabetes
and gene therapy.
Examples include Glasgow University's Clinical Research Initiative in Heart
Failure and the Cardiovascular Research Unit in Edinburgh which is a national
centre for coronary artery disease.
Edinburgh researchers discovered how cells orchestrate their own death and were
the first to realise that the failure of damaged cells to do so allows certain
cancers to arise and grow.
Aberdeen University's Department of Physics Applied to Medicine is applying a
range of technologies to medical imaging; Strathclyde's National Centre of
Proesthetics and  Orthotics designs and manufac- turers replacement limbs; and
Paisley has a well-developed expertise in biosensor technology.
The pharmaceutical industry is already collaborating with Scottish
universities. Glaxo-Wellcome has established a diabetes research lab within the
institute of Medical Sciences in Aberdeen and endowed a chair of respiratory
medicine at Edinburgh.
And the Fujisawa Institute of Neuroscience is a #5m collaboration between
Edinburgh University and Japan's Fujisawa pharmaceutical company.
``One of the key markets is Japan, whose companies are globalising and putting
research labs into Europe,'' says the trust's chief executive, Dr Stephen
Hammond, who has held senior positions in large pharmaceutical companies such
as Astra, Smithkline Beecham and Glaxo.
``The UK as a whole has a poor record of spin-out companies. There is still a
divide between academia and industry.''
The trust, which is based in Clydebank, is being funded by the Healthcare
Liaison Office (HLO) of Dunbartonshire Enterprise. Any jobs created will tend
to be high-value ones.
``It takes an estimated #67,000 to create one research job,'' says HLO director
David Macauley.
Trust chairman Dr Jim Stewart, who in 1987 became managing director of
Ciba-Ceigy Pharmaceuticals in the UK and is responsible for 1000 staff and
sales of #120m, says: ``World pharmaceutical markets continue to show strong
growth potential.
``Companies in Europe, Japan and the USA are looking increasingly for external
research to help them bring new products to market. The trust will be working
hard to attract a greater share of the spend.
``The more research work we can bring to Scotland, the more jobs we create and
the greater the opportunity for long-term commercial spin-off.''
An example of the potential for commercial spin-off is the Fluosam system,
which combines opto-electronics and immunochemistry to produce a test which
could deliver the results of cervical cancer smear tests within an hour,
eliminating the need to transport the specimens to a distant lab.
This would mean tests could be carried out at local clinics, by GPs or even by
nurses, saving time and resources, and it could eliminate the need for
exhausting visual inspections, so reducing errors.
It was developed by Bio-Medical Instrumentation Ltd, headed by Dr John
Scholefield, based initially at Strathclyde University but now in new premises
provided with the help of Dunbartonshire Enterprise.
When the system underwent trials alongside conventional testing methods, it
performed well. Its potential is enormous: 80 million smear tests are carried
out in Europe and the US every year.
</TEXT>
