<HEADLINE>Collins the top earner on #27,900 but . . . Pride name of the game for players</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND began their preparations for the European Championship finals in
earnest yesterday. The threat of a play-off had gone, though manager Craig
Brown had never seen that as a real worry, and the plans were being laid for
the cross-Border invasion next summer. Yesterday, the SFA had men in England
looking at hotels where the team may stay once they know the section they will
be in.
Bonuses for players have already been decided. John Collins has already earned
#27,900 as the one player who appeared in all 10 qualifying matches. His match
fees were worth #3000; points bonuses gave him another #6900, and then there is
a share of the #300,000 lump sum which is split among the players on a pro-rata
nature. His share of that came to #18,000.
Now, in the finals themselves, the players will be paid #1500 per game with an
additional #1000 per game for players who did not take part in the matches.
There will also be a share of a #152,000 lump sum.
Similarly, a semi-final situation would involve #168,000 divided among the
players. In the event of them winning the competition, #332,000 would be split
among the squad.
Brown maintained yesterday: ``The money doesn't matter to these players. I
think the SFA have done remarkably well to offer this kind of bonus system for
the players, but you have to remember they are all earning massive amounts of
cash with their clubs. Playing for their country is still a matter of pride.''
However, the increase in match fees alone is a significant move by the men at
Park Gardens, who clearly realise that their payments must be comparable to
those the players receive at club level.
Brown believes his squad's view of the bonuses was summed up when captain Gary
McAllister was still asking after the San Marino victory what the players had
earned.
``He honestly didn't know,'' said Brown, ``and that shows the commitment of
this group. They are not motivated by money. You can see that when you hand
them their caps after a game. You can sense their pride in receiving that
honour from their country.''
The most worrying feature now for Brown is eventually having to tell some of
these men that they will not have that honour in England.
``It will be one of the worst things about this job,'' he said, and added:
``There will be no flannel from me, because professional players see through
that. They will be told, and they will know that it will be done with honesty
and fairness. I have to look at the squad and decide which players will be most
appropriate for the games. I am sure there will be emotion involved, but I will
not shirk anything. I can't do that.''
Aberdeen striker Scott Booth has emerged as the main man up front and Brown was
at pains to point out his scoring record of five goals in nine games. Brown
said: ``That is amazing. If he continues that scoring rate then he will be up
there with Gary Lineker.
``But, remember, we could have Duncan Ferguson back, we can play Eoin Jess
either up front or in midfield, and you can never discount Ally McCoist. He is
such an enthusiast. He came on and scored again and between now and the summer
I'll be watching him. I am sure he'll continue to get sharper and sharper.''
Brown has both a full international and a B international against Denmark in
April. He wants another game, at home, in March and then he will look for a
short tour to hone the players to fitness before they go to England early in
June.
His main concern is the gap between the end of the season in both England and
Scotland and the start of the championships. The season ends on May 4 - the
tournament begins on June 8.
Brown said: ``The only players who will be in training after May 4 are those
involved in the cup finals, which are scheduled for May 18. What we will do is
have everyone together in February, when fitness levels will be checked by the
doctor.
``Then, those who are not playing in the cup finals will be given a special,
individual fitness programme to follow until the squad gets together for the
tour games around May 22.
``We hope to have two matches, one in the United States and the other in
Canada.''
</TEXT>
