<HEADLINE>Pointing the way to market The Glasgow Development Agency has introduced a number of initiatives to help software and information technology companies become more competitive. Joan Grady reports</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joan Grady</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Appointments</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975339528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE proliferation of software and information technology companies in Scotland
makes them an important part of the country's economic regeneration. Glasgow
alone is home to 240 firms, about a third of the Scottish total.
A well-trained workforce and good technical ability means many countries are
already aware of Scotland's reputation in technology manufacturing. Keeping up
that workforce and enhancing that reputation will ensure Scotland's success
continues.
However, Scottish firms are not developing as fast as they might. Glasgow
Development Agency has introduced a number of initiatives to help these firms
become more competitive. It aims to teach companies the importance of marketing
to help them reach their full potential.
``GDA believes that while companies' technical competence is outstanding, the
high-calibre workforce and better use of commercial considerations and
marketing techniques could result in significant growth and development,'' says
GDA spokesman Denny Macgee.
The Software Marketing Scheme provides grants of up to 50% of the full cost of
implementing marketing initiatives designed to help improve overall performance.
Services to Software Ltd is another GDA venture, this time enlisting the help
of Glasgow University, Glasgow Caledonian University, and the National
Engineering Laboratory. Its remit is to help software firms overcome technical
problems.
January of this year saw the opening of the Glasgow Software Centre by the GDA
and BAeSEMA. The centre, at Atlantic Quay, provides premises for growing
software companies almost ready to go on the market. Five firms are currently
developing there.
``This is another important element in our strategy to help software companies
be-come more com-petitive,'' says Jim Johnstone of BAeSEMA, facilities manager
of the Software Centre.
``Marketing is the fundamental missing link in many companies' ability to
develop and grow. This scheme aims to harvest the technical expertise of
Glasgow's software companies, while allowing them to focus on customers and
their needs.''
Scotland is already known for the quality of its workforce. Universities and
colleges provide excellent training in a wide variety of information technology
subjects and qualifications. Strangely, however, the only place in Britain
which offers an SVQ in Software Production - an essential part of the industry
- is based in the West Midlands.
Computeach International Ltd runs a unique training centre providing City &amp;
Guilds, NVQs and SVQs in all aspects of information technology. The difference
is that all courses are run by distance or open learning, which company
chairman George Parkinson believes offers more to people in training than many
Government schemes.
``The Government devotes huge sums of our taxes to the problem of career
development for the unemployed, and incarcerates great numbers of them on a
variety of training schemes and program-mes,'' he says.
``Trainees on such courses are listed as full-time students and so are not
included in the unemployment statistics. If people are available for work while
learning they cannot be used to reduce the unemployment figures, and that's the
very reason open learning is in a political wilderness.''
Parkinson in fact pioneered the open learning concept in the UK. In 1964, when
information technology was just beginning to show its importance, he wanted to
provide training across the country for those who wanted to learn more about
this developing field.
He founded Computeach International Ltd (CIL) at University House in the West
Midlands. Since then it has grown in size, with students not only all over the
country, but all over the world.
The company has re-cently been awarded SVQ assessment centre status by SCOTVEC
and is a recognised examination centre for the City &amp; Guilds of London
Institute, where C&amp;G examinations are held on a monthly basis.
``By awarding us SVQ status, SCOTVEC has given us a vote of confidence,'' says
CIL managing director Paul Harrison. ``It has shown that distance is no object
for people throughout Scotland who want to train for a career in the booming IT
industry.''
CIL helps students find work through its JobSearch initiative. It provides
assistance in compiling CVs, in letter-writing and coaching in interview
techniques. It also provides a free service for employers which matches their
specifications with student qualifications.
Parkinson hopes to show the Government the value of distance learning as an IT
training option. ``With successful students now working in all areas of
industry and commerce, we have shown the Government the way,'' he says.
``Distance learning gets results.''
</TEXT>
