<HEADLINE>Hearts in the right place</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEARTS chairman Chris Robinson won the night when the club's shareholders met
for the annual meeting at Ingliston last night.
He took on former owner Wallace Mercer and shareholder Dr Gavin Kennedy, and
received the backing of the majority of the 1000-strong audience.
Afterwards, Robinson said: ``I hope that this lays the ghost of Wallace Mercer.
Now we must go forward.''
Manager Jim Jefferies, who was on the platform with the directors, announced
also that the signings of Italian Pasquale Bruno and Swede Hans Eskilsson are
``ninety-nine per cent certain to be completed tomorrow.''
Two new directors from the new shareholders, John Frame and Ian McCallum, were
voted on to the board.
Mercer had leapt to his feet after the meeting had been going for more than an
hour and demanded to know why he had not been given the opportunity to meet
Robinson since the takeover.
Robinson responded angrily: ``I have met you. I had breakfast with you in the
Balmoral Hotel, and I had to ask you not to interfere with transfer dealings of
this club. ``You ignored me and you spoke to David Murray about Alan McLaren's
transfer to Rangers.''
Mercer then asked: ``Is Colin Wilson, my nominee director, happy with the
business affairs?'' Wilson answered by saying: ``I have had to go to law to get
details. I have been marginalised. I have not had access to the accounts and
this has been wrong.''
Robinson stressed that his fellow director had never once minuted these claims
and, indeed, had been given quarterly access to the accounts which was the
agreement.
Robinson also gave a strong rebuttal to the much-publicised claims made by Dr
Kennedy, who had suggested that the club was facing severe financial problems.
Robinson said: ``We have the support of the bank until May 1996. They are
allowing us the same overdraft facility as we have now.'' The club is almost
#5m in debt.
There was criticism from the floor over the accounts and even a suggestion that
Hearts were ``trading insolvent,'' but the chairman referred to what he termed
a ``hole in the accounts'' when he took over - which meant the Tynecastle side
was more than #1.37m worse off than he and his partner Deans had believed.
</TEXT>
