<HEADLINE>More and bigger herds could be the key to Aberdeen-Angus dominating quality end of market Macphie aims to beef up business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339530</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND needs another 50 Aberdeen-Angus herds of up to 300 head if the breed
is to realise its potential to dominate the quality end of the beef market at
home and overseas.
That is the view of Stewart Macphie of Glenbervie, near Stonehaven, whose
family business is the largest privately owned supplier of sauces and mixes to
the bakery industry in Britain.
He has followed his own advice on the home farm at Glenbervie where he has,
over the last three years, created a pedigree Aberdeen-Angus herd based on two
outstanding bulls and 200 breeding cows dedicated to commercial purposes.
One of the bulls, Castle of Mey Quartz, bought from the Queen Mother, will be
seen at this year's Smithfield Farm Tech show at Earls Court where Macphie will
be exhibiting for the first time.
The aim will be to show other farmers how the company set out to get added
value for its product. For the Macphie family that means an investment of about
#1.4m which includes the establishment of the herd and the creation of a
butchery unit.
The output from that unit will be aimed at the quality end of the market such
as the Savoy Hotel Group, certain chefs nominated by Egon Ronay, and leading
outlets in the capitals of Europe.
The intention is not to corner a market for Macphie, however. The company
anticipates buying in beasts from other producers provided the quality is
right. It will start off next summer with about 10 carcasses a week but hopes
to build up quickly to 50.
The new butchery unit will create about 10 jobs and will satisfy the most
stringent hygiene regulations. At the same time there will be a return to some
traditional standards such as allowing meat to hang for 14-21 days.
An important part of the strategy will be to get a premium price for
forequarters beef. Here Macphie's food enterprise and farming interests will
combine. Much of the forequarter output will be cooked on site into oven-ready
meals such as lasagne and stroganoff which will be marketed through
delicatessens and private High Street retailers.
Stewart Macphie also promises a pie of chopped beef covered with lattice pastry
of a standard which could be served in a five-star hotel.
Quality is of vital importance to the future of beef, he insists, and he is
scathing about Scottish butchers who ``want to destroy 40% of an animal by
putting it through a mincing machine''. His own aim is to get a premium price
wherever possible.
If he does achieve that target he is prepared to share his success. One of his
declared ambitions is to pay the highest prices in Scotland to farmers for any
stock bought in.
``We will push the price up and cut out the middle man,'' he said. ``After two
years we hope to show farmers a balance sheet which will make the profits of
the North-east co-operatives look skinny.''
John Lohoar, farm manager at Glenbervie, said that the pedigree herd had begun
to be established in October 1992. ``We can trace our animals back for three
generations,'' he said. ``Our idea is to control everything from conception to
consumption.''
Stewart Macphie is resigned to the fact that in order to meet the demand for
``Continental'' cuts he may have to look to Holland for a butcher. ``There are
not too many butchers in Scotland with that kind of experience,'' he said. ``I
would like the job to go to a Scot but it has to go to the best applicant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
