<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Facing up to winter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Kate Rafferty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WINTER is fast taking a grip, but there are a few, almost reflex, actions we
take to protect ourselves from the driving rain and icy-cold winds.
Warm coats, boots, gloves, scarves and even hats shield areas of exposed skin -
but what about the face? - probably the area of skin we worry most about
keeping in top condition.
As we wrap our bodies, so there are treatments designed to ``wrap up'' our
skin, keeping it smooth yet strong during the ravages of a Scottish winter.
At Yours Faithfully in Hope Street, beauty therapist Sandra McCafferty works
towards this on the floor above the popular hair salon. This is Yours
Faithfully's first venture into the beauty world, but already Sandra has a list
of faithful clients.
With the comprehensive range of E'spa products, Sandra can help you take the
natural road to relaxation and healthy skin. E'spa is a British company which
uses only plant extracts in its treatments. The versatility of each means that
Sandra can mix and blend to achieve the right balance for each skin type.
``E'spa are also very competitively priced,'' Sandra said. ``They keep the
packaging to a bare minimum and don't use widespread advertising, but
word-of-mouth has already made them a popular choice.''
One of the most relaxing treatments that Sandra recommends is the back, scalp
and face package.
``After a back massage with E'spa oils, we give the client a facial. As this is
left to work, we massage deep into the scalp with clay which nourishes the hair
and scalp,'' Sandra added.
With coughs and colds tearing through the workplace at the moment, E'spa also
have a range of anti-infection treatments. While they can't promise to stop
colds coming, they have helped to keep them at bay, staving off the worst
effects.
Yours Faithfully offers the full range of beauty procedures from electrolysis
to manicures, pedicures, waxing and colour analysis, a computer-generated guide
to the perfect palette of colours to complement your skin.
And, with taking the stress out of Christmas in mind, there are gift boxes and
vouchers available to boost the spirits of a woman or man who may be prone to
the January blues.
``It's a relaxing way of approaching the Christmas rush,'' said Sandra. ``The
treatments have cosmetic and therapeutic benefits, but some clients find just
the process of getting away from it all and chatting on a one-to-one basis a
great therapy in itself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TENNIS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JUDY MURRAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339532</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAMANTHA Smith maintained a British presence in the Texaco Women's Challenger
event in Edinburgh when she upset top-seed Sandra Kleinova to book her place in
today's semi-final, writes Judy Murray.
Smith trailed the Czech 4-1 in the first set but after having broken back in
the seventh game, Smith dropped her own delivery in the tenth and Kleinova
clinched the set 6-4.
The Czech looked to have the match under control when she broke in the second
game of the second set, but when the British No.9 reeled off the next three
games to take the lead for the first time, Kleinova's suspect temperament
presented itself, and she received code violation for firing a ball into the
viewing gallery.
Smith's winning run continued as she produced some spectacular forehands to
break Kleinova after six deuces in the vital seventh game and went on to pocket
the set 6-2 when the favourite netted a forehand return.
The 17-year-old, prone to verbal outbursts, dissolved into tears when her first
serve was called out on the second point of the final set, and although she
went on to win the opening game, Smith regained control and won the next six
for a 4-6, 6-2, 6-1 victory.
She now meets Seda Noorlander, from Holland, who beat Paula Hermida 7-6, 1-6,
6-2, while Russian teenager Julia Lutrova, a 4-6, 6-2, 6-2 victor over
Australian Nicole Pratt, takes on third-seed Marion Maruska who recovered from
4-1 down to beat German qualifier Sabine Gerke 6-4, 6-1.
</TEXT>
