<HEADLINE>The info-tech way to train</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOAN GRADY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Appointments</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975339534</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q WHILE training in information technology will keep Scotland at the forefront
of an expanding industry, training by information technology gets results of
its own, writes JOAN GRADY.
The Scottish Interactive Technology Centre (SiTC) is an independent body, based
in Edinburgh, committed to promoting and supporting the use of information
technology in Scotland. It helps companies with the design, development and
production of interactive multimedia products for use in the commercial and
public sectors.
Among the many products available are interactive training videos. Information
is stored on a videodisk, which can be played back through specialised
equipment linked to a PC. It is accessed by trainees via an on-screen ``icon''
or ``hot area''. Users need simply ``click'' a mouse or touch the screen to
activate the video clip they want to see.
SiTC advises on the equipment needed and program design, and it teaches
companies how to use interactive video as a training tool. The most immediate
advantage is that employers can tailor a program to suit their needs.
As with open learning, interactive video gives the trainee control over his or
her own progress. The disks can fast-forward or freeze-frame just like a
conventional video cassette, so he or she can pick out necessary information or
bypass any which has already been covered.
Disks can be programmed to offer several sets of circumstances for any
particular problem, allowing a more thorough examination of the situation.
As a method of training, interactive video appears to catch the imagination of
trainees. The US army found that training using interactive video increased
retention by up to 40%. It is also suitable for group use, or for tutor-led
sessions.
And it doesn't need a mountain of gadgets or vast knowledge of computer
systems, expensive textbooks or costly training sessions.
q GDA can be reached on 0141 2041111, Computeach International on 01384 458515,
and Scottish Interactive Technology Centre on 0131 5586039.
</TEXT>
