<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why the bank that likes to say No to ageism also said No to Arnold, 59</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Appointments</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975339535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Appointments reporters helped Arnold Markson get an answer to why he
lost out on work in a call centre, the fast-growing sector featured last week.
it was our report last month on combating age discrimination which first led
him to contact us. It had quoted TSB Bank as saying: ``We welcome all
candidates, whatever their age.''
In September Mr Markson, 59, had telephoned the TSB in response to an
advertisement in The Herald for telemarketing supervisors at its Glasgow
PhoneBank Centre.
He had been made redundant six months earlier and although his degree is in
chemistry and his experience in the food industry, he is computer literate,
having taught himself desk-top publishing.
Applicants were telephoned to assess their telephone voice after which a phone
interview would be arranged. Mr Markson was telephoned on September 29. ``When
I told her my age, the girl said I wasn't eligible for the job because anyone
over 59 was too old.
``I was told I had been on the interview list but that I couldn't be any
longer.''
An upset Mr Markson wrote to TSB for an explanation, without success, and to
Employment Minister Cheryl Gillian, who publicly supports anti-ageism policies,
before contacting The Herald.
We contacted TSB's Scottish head office in Edinburgh. ``We don't talk about
individuals - it's our policy not to,'' said a spokesman. ``If this person
writes to us we'll certainly write back.''
Last week TSB did write to Mr Markson, explaining that although it encourages
applications from people over 50, it requires all staff to retire at 60 so ``a
business decision has been taken not to accept applications from people aged 59
and over''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chairmen vote to view TV evidence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Football League, concerned by the disciplinary lapses in the game,
yesterday made a bold decision to push for acceptance of television evidence
and pressure will now be put on the SFA, who continue to claim video pictures
should not be used, even though that view is obviously out of step with modern
times, writes James Traynor.
The majority of chairmen of the country's premier division clubs said in The
Herald on Wednesday the time had come to use television evidence, which can be
employed to prove innocence and not only guilt. The chairmen also believe that
by making it clear football will use every reasonable method to improve
on-field discipline, the police might be able to resist the temptation to
enforce the genuine law of the land.
Already some clubs have altered their views. They have come to accept the folly
of turning a blind eye to incidents which are shown on television and realise
now that football's failure to act on such evidence left them open to criticism.
The SFA's council recently rejected overwhelmingly the use of film, but they
are to be pressed again after yesterday Scottish League Management Committee
meeting, at which SFL president Yule Craig, who is a member of the SFA's
disciplinary committee, was instructed to present their views on Monday.
The disciplinary meeting now has a busy schedule, because the members are also
to consider various matters of alleged indiscipline involving Rangers' Paul
Gascoigne, John Brown, and Alan McLaren, and Billy Dodds, of Aberdeen. All four
were involved in scenes, one or more of which prompted intervention from the
procurator-fiscal.
The committee will also be investigating incidents involving Alan Lawrence, of
Hearts, when his side last played Rangers, Sean Sweeney's alleged kick at
Dundee's Morten Weighorst, and the double sending off last week of the
Dumbarton keeper, Ian McFarlane, in a match against Airdrie.
The premier division representatives at yesterday's meeting were Rangers
secretary-director Campbell Ogilvie, Douglas Cromb, of Hibs, Jim Oliver, of
Partick Thistle, and Kilmarnock's Bob Fleeting.
In addition, the Falkirk chairman, George Fulston, was present as
vice-president of the League, but he is not in favour of television evidence.
While the representatives of the first, second, and third divisions did not
take any direct line, it is known that Airdrie's George Peat gave his backing
even though one of his own players, Sweeney, could be punished perhaps because
his alleged kick was seen on television.
The indications are that, when the issue is raised at the SFA's disciplinary
committee, it will be remitted to the executive committee, which is the body
able to recommend changes of policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000016</DOCNO>
