<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>match for the occasion Kate Rafferty finds a venue which offers an appealing wedding-day package</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KATE RAFFERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVERY engaged couple looks forward to their wedding day as something to
remember - a day which is geared to be unique to them and the start of their
lives together.
There are few venues which can guarantee a wedding in the most beautiful of
settings - but Gleddoch House is one. Walking up the gravel driveway toward the
hotel entrance gives you a feeling of being truly ``away from it all'' when in
reality, the hotel is just half-a-mile from the Langbank/Houston exit off the
M8 to Greenock.
In true country house tradition, the grounds at Gleddoch are immaculately kept,
and perfect for stunning wedding photographs.
Although each wedding is tailor made, there is a basic wedding package, which
for 1996 costs #450. This includes private use of the garden restaurant for the
day (depending on guest numbers), personalised Gleddoch scroll menus and
in-house table plans and place cards, table flowers, a changing room for the
bride and groom, the use of a silver cake stand and knife and use of the
hotel's luxurious honeymoon suite, complete with four-poster bed.
Those couples who have already booked their wedding venue may care to consider
Gleddoch's honeymoon night package, which can be tailored to include champagne
and flowers on your arrival. As most newly-weds arrive later in the evening,
accommodation and breakfast are included in this package, which can be expanded
to a longer stay. There is a courtesy car to Glasgow Airport.
Next Sunday is the ideal opportunity to see what Gleddoch House can offer.
There will be a Wedding Fayre at the hotel from 1pm to 5pm on November 26.
Macbee Bridal are the bridal wear specialists at the fayre, who promote the
individuality of the bride. Evidence of their work will be on the catwalk when
they stage a bridal fashion show at 3pm.
For the groom, Houston Menswear will be there to give advice on dress hire,
with everything from morning suits to full Highland outfits. And, for the
mother of the bride, Catherine's of Partick will have some suggestions.
Lightbody's of Hamilton will have advice on wedding cakes, Style Video are
there to explain how best to capture the day on film and Graeme Wilson
photography will have examples of his comprehensive wedding work.
Frasers of Glasgow will explain how their wedding registry operates, and the
store will also have Elizabeth Arden make up experts on hand.
An individual approach to wedding stationery comes from Something Original who
use celtic influences and designs inspired by Charles Rennie Mackintosh for
their range.
Gleddoch have chosen Flower Vogue as an example of inventive but dependable
floristry, and Little Chauffeur Drive for car hire to get you to your venue on
time.
Entertainment is also represented by the Neil Drover Agency, who can provide
bands which will please a whole spectrum of guests.
Gleddoch have made their own extremely special contribution to the day, with a
competition for brides-to-be. There will be a prize draw on the day in which
one bride will win the #450 wedding package explained in detail earlier.
The other two prizes are wedding stationery vouchers from Something Original,
and Elizabeth Arden will give both a trial and wedding day make-over to a lucky
bride along with True Love and Cerruti fragrances.
The memorable surroundings of Gleddoch stem from the fact that it was once a
private house, owned by shipping baron Sir James Lithgow. It is now in its
twenty-first year as a hotel, the tenth under its current owners.
It can also provide corporate golf packages, clay pigeon shooting, off-road
driving and an equestrian centre.
Conferences and meetings are also catered for. The choice of mouth watering
meals on the restaurant menu, the majority of which use local produce, is
enough to make business a pleasure. And, for an outstanding treat this
Christmas or New Year, Gleddoch is the last word in getting away from it all. A
taste of aristocratic living is closer than you would ever think.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Festive shopping in a comfort zone</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Lucy Lockhart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIRTY-seven shopping days to Christmas. Can you bear it? Fighting to find a
parking place - which could well add considerably to your shopping bill - the
hassle of pushing your way through crowded pavements, braving whatever the
elements choose to throw at you . . . lots of legwork getting between streets
and shops.
But The Forge Shopping Centre believes it can offer shoppers all the answers
this festive season. Its glittering glass pyramids cover a mighty 450,000 sq.ft
of retailing space which includes no fewer than 75 High Street names, one of
the largest Asda superstores in Scotland - which has just completed a #4m refit
- a drive-thru McDonald's and a seven-screen cinema.
Before you even venture inside the immaculately kept mall where lavish
Christmas decorations can't help but put you in the festive mood, you'll find
free car parking for 1800 cars, with special places reserved for the disabled,
close to the entrances. Should the weather be inclement, covered walkways will
see you arrive at the Centre dry and unharassed. Once there, you can enjoy the
comfortable temperatures of the bright, airy mall which are well-maintained,
and relax as you browse among the huge range of shops. When you feel like a cup
of coffee or a meal, you'll find a choice of five menus at the Food Fair.
Among the newest names at The Forge, are the Early Learning Centre; Adams
childrenswear; All Sports - a company just moving into Scotland - which carries
a large range of sports equipment and clothing; Holland and Barrett the health
food specialist; travel agents Going Places, and Bodycare. Despite The Forge
being only seven years old, a number of shops - in addition to Asda's major
revamp - have been refitted. Index, for example, has invested #100,000 in such
an exercise, while Stead and Simpson shoes has also updated its store.
What The Forge is aiming to do, is provide a shopping experience which embraces
each member of the family. Christmas epitomises this. November 25 sees the
opening of Santa's Grotto, located on the central concourse's sunken area,
outside Asda.
Here, the younger members of the family can receive a gift (valued at up to
twice the Grotto charge of #1.50 according to the Centre), and have a
photograph taken. There will be animations and lots of fun. Each child visiting
Santa's Grotto will be entered into a competition. The prize? A family holiday
to Lapland, to meet Santa.
All visitors to The Forge will enjoy the traditional carol singing which is
laid on over the festive lead-up, along with street theatre, puppet shows and
clowns to keep everyone entertained. Look out too, for Santa's postbox, where
children can pop in their Christmas lists - those who supply their address,
will get a reply.
From November 27, a free gift-wrapping service for goods bought at The Forge,
will operate in the run-up to Christmas, although it may be impractical to
maintain this during peak periods. All the more reason then, to get there at
the beginning of the week or in the mornings, before business becomes really
brisk.
These more tranquil periods, are the times favoured by the many disabled
customers whose patronage The Forge enjoys, who appreciate the thoughtful
gestures of real support which are offered to them along with consultation on
their needs. Facilities include: easy parking, covered walkways, level access
to malls, wheelchair loan for use in the centre, roomy lifts, drop kerbs,
ramps, automatic doors and toilets on both evels, and low-level direction
boards.
The Forge is open seven days a week, with Thursday late opening night. The week
before Christmas, it is planned that all shops will be open until 8pm daily,
with Asda open certain nights until 10pm. On Boxing Day and on January 2, the
Centre will open from 11am-5pm and there will be plenty of entertainment laid
on, as well as the enticing prospect of sale bargains.
Vincent Lochrie is the Centre's manager. He said: ``It is my aim to ensure that
everyone who comes to shop here has a trouble-free and pleasant visit. We pride
ourselves on the cleanliness of the mall, staff courtesy, and the pleasant
shopping atmosphere that we have strived to create.``Parking in all our 1800
spaces is absolutely free, and uniformed security officers and hi-tech CCTV
cameras cover our carparks to help ensure the safety and security of your
vehicle.''
Compared with many areas, The Forge is a cinch to get to. Simply follow the M8
to Junction 12, then follow the signs for Parkhead. Situated next door to
Celtic Football Stadium, its glass pyramid construction provides a distinctive,
easy-to-spot landmark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Customer service is priority</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME members of the family are no doubt, more enthusiastic about shopping than
others, but Christmas at The Forge means that everyone can find something to
please. The youngsters may prefer to watch a movie - there's a very popular
Saturday morning film club - while their parents shop, and dad may like to
sidle off to watch some of the entertainment . . . then the whole family can
join up for a meal at the Food Fair or McDonald's. Then on the way home, you
can even fill the car with petrol at the Centre's 24-hour filling station.
Altogether, a total experience.
Services such as banking and building society facilities, cash machines, dry
cleaning and photograph processing are also excellent at The Forge. And
promises of customer care at the Centre are not hollow. Every couple of months
or so, meetings are held with customers who are asked a range of questions, to
give feedback on what they think about The Forge, and what they'd like to see
provided. These customer panels as they are called, have proved to be fertile
forums for positive ideas, and the management has not been slow to implement
them. An excellent example, is the latest, free, customer service offered in
the car parks: changing a car tyre for instance, if you return to your vehicle
to find it flat; or jump starting cars which refuse to start.
Trained personnel have been provided to look after this aspect, and Lex
Vauxhall has laid on a car which tours the car parks on a regular basis, driven
by a Forge employee looking out for anyone who has such a problem. The Centre
will also call motoring organisations for members whose vehicles require their
specialist services.
Mark Stangroom, marketing co-ordinator of The Forge considers: ``These days, of
great importance, is the service you provide. The Forge is very clean and
bright, a nice place to be. Bins are emptied every 15 minutes, loos inspected
half hourly - it all combines to make a very pleasant Centre.
``Sometimes, we get customers who can't remember where they left their cars in
the parks. With our CCTV we can locate them quickly, much to their owner's
relief.''
Summing up, Mr Stangroom says: ``Christmas at The Forge Shopping Centre really
will be something special this year - for all the family. Over the past 12
months, The Forge has undergone a great many improvements which are now being
supplemented by some fantastic Christmas promotions.
``Shops; cinema; foodcourt; Asda and McDonald's; free parking; no city-centre
hassle; everything under cover; and all our entertainments, carol singing and
fun mean we believe visitors to The Forge will be delighted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Meat wholesalers and auctioneers remain divided over BSE levy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339540</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE pre-Christmas period is the season when beef producers can usually
anticipate high prices for their prime cattle. At present those expectations
are being realised as a result of fewer cattle coming forward and a buoyant
export trade.
However, two recent television programmes, Watchdog and World in Action, have
aroused widespread alarm in both the farming industry and the meat trade with
claims that BSE-infected cattle are being sold in markets and then entering the
food chain.
Meanwhile, livestock auctioneers and the meat trade are at loggerheads over the
imposition of a #3.50 per head levy on all cattle going for slaughter. The meat
trade claims that this should be deducted by auctioneers but they in turn say
that they have no authority to act in this fashion.
The NFU takes a similar line as was clearly stated at the council meeting in
Ingliston earlier this month. The union's view is that any extra costs incurred
in removing spinal tissue should be reflected in the price paid for cattle.
On Monday two English auction marts, Gloucester and Rugby, broke ranks from
their professional organisation and deducted the levy. It now seems certain
that those firms will be expelled from their association. So far Scottish
auction marts remain 100% solid behind the policy of the Institute of
Auctioneers in resisting the levy.
Yesterday a meeting was held in Dunblane between the Scottish Association of
Meat Wholesalers and the auctioneers. No statement was made afterwards but it
is understood that the auctioneers remain totally opposed to any levy.
However, John Scott, the president of the SAMW, remains convinced that farmers
have more to gain than lose by agreeing to pay the levy which is half the #7
the trade believe it costs to comply with the appropriate health regulations.
Mr Scott said: ``We feel that the whole issue has been pushed below the carpet.
If the industry comes clean and accepts that there is a problem and shows a
willingness to pay then there could be a chance of attracting funds from
Brussels to eradicate BSE.''
Earlier this week it emerged that in the Irish Republic a slaughter policy has
been implemented to cope with Ireland's reported cases of no more than 15 per
year. The Irish Government compensates farmers on a herd basis where BSE occurs.
Mr Scott is both a farmer and butcher, running a herd of 200 beef cows, taking
the progeny through to slaughter. He commented: ``I do feel there are many
farmers willing to pay the levy. Some who sell deadweight are already doing so
and this cost is shown specifically on their advice notes. There is a problem,
and there is an enormous amount of disinformation which we have to fight
against.''
Consumer reaction on the high streets of Scotland varied enormously yesterday
with the younger element of shoppers being the most concerned. Outside a major
supermarket a student said: ``I never eat beef, in fact everyone in our flat is
vegetarian.''
A housewife, however, took a different view, ``I still eat beef and I've every
intention of continuing. In fact I had an excellent steak last night.'' A male
shopper, though, was more circumspect saying: ``I'm still eating beef but I'm
more aware about BSE.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
