<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surgeon felt risk of operation too great</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONSULTANT surgeon yesterday claimed he had refused to refer patients to an
experimental research project for hip operations because he thought it was too
risky.
Orthopaedic specialist Thomas Scotland told a fatal accident inquiry into the
death of Mrs Phyllis Moffitt, 70, that he felt the benefits to elderly patients
were outweighed by the risks it posed to their health.
Mr Scotland claimed he and a colleague had both declined to take part in the
Aberdeen University-led project, although the university's ethics committee had
approved it.
The inquiry, at Aberdeen Sheriff Court, was earlier told that Mrs Moffitt
became ill and died at the city's Woodend Hospital while undergoing an
experimental operation as part of the project.
A post-mortem examination revealed she had died of a heart attack after being
given a sedative to ease discomfort during the operation.
The project was designed to see if the incidence of elderly women suffering a
second hip fracture could be reduced by means of a revolutionary injection
process.
Mr Scotland said: ``I was concerned that the perceived benefits of the project
were out-weighed, in my mind, by the potential disadvantages.''
He said he was concerned that the injections would strengthen only the top part
of the hip bone, leaving the lower hip more prone to snapping.
He added: ``I was also concerned that the operative procedure may have serious
consequences for the group of patients involved.''
Most patients over 70 were likely to suffer from other serious diseases,
including coronary heart disease, and an unnecessary operation could put them
in a ``precarious'' state, he said.
Mr Scotland also disputed information contained in a letter sent to potential
volunteers, which claimed the operation would be of great benefit.
``They should have included, somewhere, something about the potential
disadvantages.''
Earlier, pathologist James Grieve said an autopsy report revealed Mrs Moffitt
had severe and significant coronary artery disease, which had caused her death.
Even a very slight drop in blood pressure caused by administering a sedative
may have led Mrs Moffitt's heart to stop, he said.
The inquiry, before Sheriff Peter Hamilton, was adjourned until December 27.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Isles welcome BCCI ruling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339543</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LUXEMBOURG court ruling which appears to have cleared the way for
compensation payouts to creditors of the crashed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International (BCCI) was welcomed cautiously in the Western Isles last night.
The Western Isles Council lost #23m in the BCCI crash.
There are 15,000 creditors in the UK who could now receive #433m.Liquidator
Touche Ross is to make an initial payment of 30% of the total owed, under a
compensation scheme agreed by the bank's leading shareholder, the Sheikh of Abu
Dhabi.
Yesterday Mr Brian Stewart the council's chief executive, who was not with the
council when BCCI crashed in 1991, said: ``I have not seen the details of the
proposed settlement and, therefore, cannot comment fully on it. However, if
reports of a 30% immediate payout to creditors are accurate then this would be
welcome news to the council.
``Any payments would, of course, be used to partially offset the council's
increased borrowing requirement, so that the council's capital spending
capability would not be affected. It would, however, have the effect of
reducing our loan repayments which, in turn, would have a beneficial effect on
the council's revenue finances.
``We will be pressing the liquidators for full details of the settlement and
the likely timing of the first payments to the council.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BP awards long-term contract</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BP Exploration has awarded a long-term contract for the provision of a new
purpose-built stand-by and support vessel to cope with the severe weather
conditions in the Foinaven Field, to the west of Shetland.
The MV Grampian Frontier will be owned and operated by North Star Shipping, a
member of the George Craig Group Ltd, and a construction contract will be
awarded shortly.
The vessel will provide the most up-to-date equipment for the rescue and
recovery of personnel including an advanced fast rescue craft with a fully
enclosed wheelhouse for the crew to enable it to operate on its own for several
hours.
The craft will be able to be launched and recovered in poor weather conditions.
The stand-by vessel will also have a scoop-net system for recovering personnel
and lifeboats directly from the sea on to its deck and will have accommodation
for 400 passengers in an emergency.
The multi-million pound vessel is designed to be multi-role and will assist in
the shuttle tanker operations, has a dynamic positioning system to keep her on
station and will be able to deploy a remotely operated vehicle for inspection.
It will also carry oil dispersant chemicals and spray equipment.
Production from the field is expected to start in the spring and a vessel of
similar specification will work in the field until the Grampian Frontier is
commissioned a year later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for dockyard work to stop Trident refit costs soaring</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339545</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE overall cost of refitting Trident submarines could escalate further unless
more Royal Navy work is soon given to Devonport dockyard, unions claimed
yesterday.
They already have asked for an independent inquiry into claims that the true
cost of building the Trident refit complex at Devonport would be double the
successful #236m bid which won the operators, Devonport Management Ltd, the
refit work two years ago.
Ministers should be called to account because there was a ``sorry history'' in
the Ministry of Defence of ``grotesque mismanagement'', said Transport and
General Workers' Union national secretary Jack Dromey at Plymouth yesterday.
However, a current ``serious shortfall'' of work in the dockyard threatened
further major job losses there, which could in turn lead to the Trident work
costing still more, said Mr Dromey.
Major redundancies were threatened unless there was a decision on further work
by the end of January, he said.
Because of delays at Devonport more nuclear submarine refits were expected to
be diverted to Rosyth, and to prevent threatened job losses at Devoport, Mr
Dromey called for the Ministry of Defence to ``load'' the Plymouth dockyard
with unallocated Royal Navy surface fleet work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dounreay `would be left with foreign waste'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A REPORT published by Greenpeace yesterday claimed that Dounreay would be left
with up to two million litres of foreign radioactive waste.
The Government and Dounreay have continually insisted that        such waste
would be returned to the country of origin.
The report claims that the size of the foreign contracts sought by Dounreay
would mean up to 28,000 litres of waste, but because of the cementation process
employed there would be an 85-fold increase in the volume of waste left at the
Caithness plant.
The authors of the report, Dr Frank Barnaby, a nuclear physicist and former
director of the Stockholm Peace Institute, and Mr Shaun Birnie, Greenpeace
International's nuclear spokesman, were in Inverness yesterday to launch their
report.
Mr Birnie explained their concerns over Dounreay's declared intention to seek
contracts to reprocess at least 6000 of the near 15,000 spent fuel rods of US
origin which are currently lying at research reactors around the world.
Mr Birnie read from Dounreay's own literature which stated that any foreign
waste would be returned to country of origin ``or an equivalent in
radioactivity terms''.
He said most of the countries looking to use Dounreay did not have facilities
to store any waste and the US had made it clear that they might take the waste
back from reprocessing. However, the US would not take waste that resulted from
Dounreay's cementation          process.
``The waste will remain at Dounreay because not only is the US unable to take
the cemented waste in, none of the client states with the exception of Germany,
have facilities and they won't get repositories in the 25 years that Dounreay
puts as the maximum for keeping the waste.''
The UK Atomic Energy Authority's spokesman at Dounreay, Mr Ian Shepherd,
insisted last night that the Greenpeace report contained misinformation.
``We are quite clear that the waste will be returned to the country of origin
and that means returned from Dounreay. As regards the volumes produced, the
report doesn't include any information or figures on the alternatives to
reprocessing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boy, 15, drove at 90mph in 60-mile police chase</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339547</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 15-YEAR-OLD schoolboy who led police on a 60-mile chase along single-track
Highland roads at speeds up to 90mph in his mother's car, was yesterday
sentenced to a year in residential care and banned from the road for five years.
Officers, who feared he might crash, injuring himself and others, eventually
had to use a metal spiked stinger to halt the car, Dingwall Sheriff Court was
told. Procurator-fiscal David Hingston said the teenager tricked his mother
into handing over the keys of her Ford Fiesta by claiming he wanted to get
something out of the car.
He then took off at high speed and the alarm was raised. Police chased him as
he headed from Dingwall to Lairg and Ullapool. In Ullapool, he drove at 70mph
in the 30mph limit, and up to 90mph on the wet, greasy, and twisting
single-track roads through the hills and glens.
Other drivers had to take emergency action to avoid the car, which swerved from
side to side as police followed it.
The car was finally stopped at Bonar Bridge in Sutherland, when the stinger was
placed across the road by police to puncture its tyres.
Mr Hingston said the boy, who had been home on review from Rossie School secure
unit, Montrose, appears to have a fascination for cars and seems to be
completely beyond control.
The teenager admitted driving dangerously and without a licence or insurance.
He also pleaded guilty to more than a dozen charges, earlier in October, of
taking or attempting to take away cars without the owners' consent in various
Easter Ross towns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Identity card will help carers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A UNIQUE co-operative venture which will identify dependants should their carer
be involved in an accident was launched yesterday.
For the first time in Scotland, a carers' emergency card has been launched. The
Princess Royal Trust Carers' Centre in Aberdeen, Grampian Health Board, and the
emergency services are all involved in the project.
The card, which is the size of a credit card, is carried by the carer to alert
the police, ambulance, and fire services that they look after someone who is
dependent on them and provides contact numbers of people who will know what to
do. Initially 10,000 cards will be printed for free distribution.
There has been concern for some time that carers find the prospect of accidents
and sudden illness an extra source of worry when the person they care for may
be left alone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major `letting peace slip away'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINN Fein's Gerry Adams yesterday accused John Major of letting a historic
opportunity for peace slip away in Northern Ireland.
Speaking in Washington, Mr Adams said: ``We're now facing the prospect that
this could be the end of the beginning of this new opportunity.''
But Mr Adams said he had high hopes a visit by President Clinton to Britain and
Ireland, from November 27 to Decemebr 3, would help to put the stalled peace
process back on track.
Britain is insisting the IRA give up some of its arms before Sinn Fein can take
a seat at peace talks. Dublin says any weapons handover should be part of the
talks, not a precondition.
Mr Adams said that the prospects for talks had dimmed since the IRA and
loyalists declared ceasefires 15 months ago.
``At the moment, we don't have a peace process,'' added Mr Adams, ``We need to
re-establish the peace process.''
Meanwhile Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble played down the prospects of an
early breakthrough in the stalemate yesterday.
After a 75-minute meeting with Mr Major at Downing Street he was ``not
optimistic''.
He added the Prime Minister had categorically denied reports in the Irish press
that the British Government had put forward proposals that could see an end to
the current deadlock by the weekend.
``Obviously things are a bit sombre, because it does appear, with the threats
Sinn Fein-IRA are making about the breakdown of the situation, it is not
optimistic,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>At ease in an age of reality Pauline Collins takes time out from filming to tell Allan Laing about her latest villainous role and her insouciant attitude to growing old</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975339550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAULINE Collins was once asked how she felt about growing older. She replied:
``I've always liked the age I am when I get there.'' Which, when you think
about it, is sound advice for anyone mindful of the passage of time. Right now
Collins is more than happy to admit that she has just turned 55. And liking it.
She is sitting in a caravan, parked in a gap site off Glasgow's Woodlands Road.
Autumn rain - and a dozen film-crew vans - have ensured that the ground outside
is a quagmire. A friendly production assistant offers the actress a pair of
gumboots - which she is more than happy to accept. It is refreshing to note
that sartorial elegance takes second place to keeping her feet dry and warm.
Collins, who will forever be identified by a generation of women of a certain
age as their role model, Shirley Valentine, is on a rare visit to Scotland to
play a major role in Flowers of the Forest, a disturbing and powerful drama by
Michael Eaton about ritual child abuse in a fictional Highland village.
Her role is a challenging one, more so because it takes her into unfamiliar
territory. She is, I suppose, a villain of sorts. She plays Aileen Matthews, a
self-styled expert in satanic child abuse who is a member of the New Morning
Trust, a fundamentalist evangelical group. The kind of religious busy-bodies
who go poking their pious noses into other people's business.
With no real evidence to back up her claim, she convinces local social workers
that the village is riddled with devil-inspired child abusers. The result is an
unwarranted witch-hunt which devastates the local community.
``She is a member of this fundamentalist group which runs seminars. I perceive
the character as someone who is true to herself but probably misguided.
``The thing is that, as an actress, I can't consider her misguided; I must
believe in what I am doing. The film, I suppose, is the story of what leads up
to children being taken away from their families and how a large group of
people can be influenced by a small group - in this case social workers being
influenced by this evangelical group which believes in the concept of satanic
abuse. Here the signals which could be taken for another type of abuse are
interpreted as being satanic in nature,'' she explains.
Though she was aware of the recent spate of unfounded child abuse cases, not
only in Scotland, but also in England, she admits that she knew very little
about them. ``But when I read Michael Eaton's script I thought it was
absolutely fascinating. I had seen another thing he did for television, Signs
and Wonders, and I thought it was great.
``Increasingly people are becoming more and more interested in real life
stories and drama seems to be moving in that direction. Personally, I like
things which are reality-based though not necessarily true stories.''
Collins in reality, as opposed to being fully made-up for the screen, possesses
a delicate beauty. She really could pass for someone half her years. But 55 she
is (and still liking it). It is, however, a dangerous age for an actress.
She says: ``It is easier for men, of course, but women in their mid-50s, in
life as in this profession, are invisible. Now, whether you accept that or
fight it, is another question. My inclination is to accept it and do other
things with my life. Until, perhaps, I become fluffy and 60 and white-haired.
``It would be wonderful to have great parts coming my way but I look around and
they're not there.'' Her role in Flowers is a notable exception.
Despite these remarks, Collins is clearly not an actress who is ever (or, for
that matter, has ever been) short of work. Born on Merseyside, she caught the
acting bug at the age of eight in a school play. Her first big break came in
1962 when she broke into television with a part in Emergency Ward Ten where she
met her future husband, John Alderton.
Upstairs, Downstairs followed (so did Alderton) and she went on to some
distinguished work in the theatre.
But mention Pauline Collins and it is Willy Russell's Shirley Valentine which
surely springs to mind. Funny to think that the Hollywood producers first
wanted Cher to take the role. Successful though it was, Collins must be fed up
talking about the part by now.
``No, not at all,'' she remarks, eagerly. ``I loved the character, I loved the
play, and I loved the film. I think that two or three times in your life you
find a playwright with whom you have a creative marriage and that is true with
me and Willy Russell. And it's the same with him and Julie Walters.
After Shirley, Collins had many offers from Hollywood - but most of them were,
well, Valentine cards; clone roles. She was offered some television parts -
which were tempting - but she decided against them because they would have
involved five-year contracts.
She believes that one of her professional strengths is the fact that, in life,
she is a normal person.
``I'm not glamorous, I don't play glamorous parts. I play people who are
reality-based,'' she adds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Fears growing
over violinist
FEARS were growing last night for the safety of concert violinist Miles Baster,
60, leader of Edinburgh String Quartet, who lives in Edinburgh's Gracemount
area and was last seen by friends nine days ago.
Administrator Mr Kenneth Main said: ``We are worried for his safety. He's left
us in the dark over where he's gone and what he's doing.''
Tractor thief
A MAN who stole and crashed a tractor down a 50ft drop while on a day out to
Arran was jailed for six months and fined #900 at Kilmarnock yesterday. Henry
Currie, of Doon Place, Saltcoats, was also banned from driving for 10 years.
Conman jailed
CONMAN Douglas Darling, 45, was jailed for three years at Edinburgh yesterday.
He admitted four fraud offences which netted him #1670.
Robber in court
STIRLING man James Taylor, 18, of Calder Court, Braehead, who admitted robbing
and assaulting a 14-year-old boy in Bannockburn in March, had sentence deferred
until December 14 at Stirling.
Catering axed
CALEDONIAN MacBrayne is closing catering services on the Clyde ferries Juno,
Saturn, and Jupiter, because of mounting losses. The vessels primarily serve
the Wemyss Bay-Rothesay and Dunoon-Gourock routes.
Street search
ARMED police were called out yesterday in a search for a man believed to be in
possession of a firearm in Hillhouse Road, Hamilton. Police said later that a
young man was in custody.
Allan Glen Place
ALLAN Glen, the benefactor whose estate established the famous Glasgow school,
is to have a street named after him, councillors decided yesterday. The
northern part of Montrose Street will be renamed Allan Glen Place.
Woman stabbed
POLICE in Edinburgh are hunting two men in their early 20s who attacked two
women in broad daylight on Wednesday morning. One woman was stabbed in the
thigh in the attack in Redgauntlet Terrace, in The Inch. The assailants,
driving a red Metro or Ford Fiesta, were both about 6ft 3in tall.
Appeal lost
AN APPEAL by Ross Lumsden and Co against Borders Regional Council's refusal of
planning permission for the erection of seven houses at Leithen Lodge,
Innerleithen, has been dismissed by the Scottish Secretary.
Euro boost
MORE than #9.5m in grants    for small and medium firms    in Scotland have
been approved by the Brussels Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ban on abuse</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEIJING: Authorities in a middle school in eastern Jiangsu province banned 20
abusive phrases often used by teachers to criticise pupils, the China Daily
said yesterday.
The ban includes phrases such as ``Get out'', ``You're retarded'', ``You'll
never amount to anything'', and ``I'm ashamed of having a student like you''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jury told husband lied about ambush</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETECTIVES investigating the killing of a building society manageress became
suspicious when medical experts found a flaw in her husband's story of an
ambush by robbers, a court heard yesterday.
Oxford Crown Court heard that Mr Gordon Wardell, 42, could not have remained
gagged for 16 hours, after being knocked out by anaesthetic, without choking on
his tongue.
Mr Wardell told police he returned home from a public house to find his wife
being held hostage by a gang.
Mr Wardell, of Bonneville Close, Meriden, Warwickshire, denies murdering his
wife Carol, 39, at the couple's home on September 11 last year.
The prosecution claims Mr Wardell suffocated his wife before dumping her body
in a local lay-by and going to her building society branch, where he faked a
raid.
Mr Richard Wakerley QC, prosecuting, said detectives identified Mrs Wardell's
body and visited the couple's home, where they found Mr Wardell bound, gagged,
and beaten on the lounge floor.
Mr Wakerley said it was incredible that Mr Wardell had not wet himself during
the 16 hours in which he claimed he had been unconscious.
The court was told that a demonstration would show that Wardell could have tied
and gagged himself.
Referring to the claims he had been unconscious from 10pm on the Sunday until
around 9am next day, Mr Wakerley said it was almost impossible.
He said: ``There is no question that any of the blows he received had knocked
him out. If you eliminate the blows, could it have been an anaesthetic?
``It is impossible to maintain somebody unconscious for more than a few
minutes. Their tongue will go to the back of their throat and they will die if
an airway is not maintained.''
Further forensic evidence showed the defendant's claim that Mrs Wardell was
alive when he last saw her being held by the raiders was little more than a
lie, said counsel.
Mr Wardell claimed they had eaten a supper of ham and tomato salad at 7.30pm on
the Sunday but examination of her stomach contents revealed there was no ham or
tomato.
There were still obvious traces of their Sunday lunch, which Mr Wardell said
they had shared before 2pm.
``The stomach completely empties within three to four hours of taking food.
``She could not have been with the robbers at the building society at 5.22am on
Monday. She was already dead and had been for several hours.''
The jury were told that a gang of raiders would not have chosen the small
Woolwich branch where Mrs Wardell worked. Only #14,000 was taken from the safe
and the alleged raiders ignored the cardcash machine. None of the cash was
recovered.
Mrs Wardell had not used her ``duress code'' when allegedly forced to open the
security shutters. Staff issued with this code can alert headquarters to any
possible danger without setting off the alarm systems.
Mr Wardell knew his wife's security code but was unlikely to have known about
the duress code.
Mr Wakerley said: ``In the privacy of marriage, there may be many, many
motives. Motives which may require planning. That he stood to gain financially
from her death is very plain. On her death, he would receive a handsome lump
sum of thousands of pounds and a pension.
``The prosection do not, and do not need to, set out to provide a motive.''
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
