<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Countryside offensive against animal rights brigade Elizabeth Buie examines the new coalition which aims to counter the campaigns against hunting, animal transport and rambling restrictions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Buie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE fight-back has begun. Beset by activists - many of them from the
middle-class suburbs of Middle England - about everything from live animal
transport to fox-hunting, the ``country'' interests have decided to take the
offensive.
It is likely to be a highly professional campaign - public relations by
Lowe-Bell Communications, one of London's top firms, and a #3.5m advertising
campaign devised by another market leader, Bartle Bogle Hegarty.
All this to promote a better understanding of countryside issues? To explain
the rural facts of life to children who apparently believe that eggs come from
pigs, and bacon from chickens? Not likely, say the sceptics.
It seems, according to environmental sources, that a wide-ranging market
research exercise has told the country's landowners, farmers and food producers
exactly what they did not want to hear: that the vast majority of members of
the public care very much about farming practices and animal welfare issues and
are critical of both intensive and factory farming techniques.
The Countryside Movement, launched yesterday with Sir David Steel, former
Liberal leader, as its executive chairman, may well be saying that its aim is
to increase understanding of rural issues, and to help solve problems of
unemployment, poor housing, inadequate transport, and misdirected farming
policies. But a number of conservationists believe that the agenda goes much
further, and they point to the board of directors featuring leading hunt
proponents such as Lord Peel and the Duke of Westminster as evidence.
One of the Countryside Movement's main sponsors and financial backers is the
Countryside Business Group, whose spokesman, Eric Bettelheim, wrote recently in
The Field magazine: ``It took British guts and American money to win the last
war and it will take the courage of country people and the wealth of
landowners, sporting tenants and businessmen to win the current one against our
contemporary enemy, the animal rights brigade.
``Irresponsible, sanctimonious, contemptuous of others and full of hatred for
the essential elements of civilised democratic life, they will not be defeated
by reason or compromise.''
Mr Bettelheim draws comparisons with a country sports campaign mounted in
France in the 1980s backed by 50 million francs (more than #6m) with
accompanying media propaganda.
The CBG plans to spend #3m-#4m a year on its campaign, much of it raised by a
levy on landowners, farmers, sporting tenants and countryside businesses.
What has mystified many environmental commentators is Sir David Steel's
involvement. He has said he does not hunt and does not particularly approve of
it. But he is a keen angler, and at the launch defended the right of minority
sports to exist in the face of opposition.
Some anglers are concerned that if hunting is banned, angling will be the next
blood sport targeted by the anti-blood sports lobby.
Indeed, earlier this year, Sir David wrote in the London Evening Standard:
``The various worthy animal lobbies spent about #750,000 on press advertising
before the debate on hunting, and, perhaps as a result, a great many
sympathetic members of the public got swept along by this new hysteria......
And behind these armies of little old ladies come the platoons of new fascists
fuelled by the moral certainty that they are correct and the law should enforce
their view.''
He went on to describe hunting as a source of enjoyment which added to ``the
general gaiety of the countryside and to some rural employment''.
One of the Countryside Movement's first advertisements features a picture of a
hen and an egg, asking which came first, to focus people's interest on the
subject of where our food comes from. But it is understood that a later
advertisement planned for the organisation's national press campaign has a
swipe at the Ramblers' Association, the main proponent of public access.
If so, then the Ramblers in Scotland will be asking some tough questions of the
Scottish Landowners' Federation, which supports the new Countryside Movement,
about its commitment to the public access concordat that the two sides have
been working on for the past two years.
Simon Fraser, the SLF's director, said yesterday the organisation supported the
concept, but added he hoped it would take account of the differences that
marked out Scottish rural life from English.
``We like people generally to understand the countryside, to understand that
farming does involve managing animals and transporting them, and that if you
want to eat them they have to be killed,'' he said.
However, he added: ``Up here we have spent two years on this concordat and we
are right behind it, absolutely. We do not want it spoilt by noises south of
the Border where there is a different problem. ``We believe that the best way
to progress in the countryside is by consensus and agreement rather than
fighting each other from opposite trenches.''
But there does seem to be a feeling among landowning and farming interests that
they have been victimised by activists.
The Countryside Movement's launch literature states: ``It is depressing, in
Britain of all countries, to see the growth of a profoundly unsympathetic
faction which seems to have no understanding of country people and the things
for which they stand. Their vision is apparently a sanitised countryside,
devoid of life as well as death - a theme park for which the urban dweller
takes no responsibility, financial or otherwise, but through which he expects
to wander freely at the weekend.''
</TEXT>
