<DOCNO>GH951117-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A word . . .</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
. . . in your ear, Michael. Answer this, if you will. What is it about trees,
forests, and general arboreal matters which makes grown politicians ignore
their basic political instincts? Dear Ian Lang suffered from it badly. How
could he, as a Member of Parliament for a seat which is about as solid as a
quaking bog, sanction the sale of enormous tracts of Forestry Commission land
in his own area for no good reason other than political ideology? Now you will
say that there is nothing wrong with political ideology, particularly your own
sort, but the sensible politician, the politician who likes a seat in
Parliament and who wishes to retain it, leavens ideology with common sense. The
Scottish public, you see, likes to imagine itself to be trampers and hikers in
the wilds. Some of them actually do it, but what they all approve of is the
right of access to wooded paths strewn with fragrant pine needles. Access,
Michael, is what they have not got. As The Herald reported, of 801 forests in
Scotland sold by the Forestry Commission through privatisation only one is
covered by a public-access agreement. Frankly, there are plenty of people
shocked to the soles of their thick wooly socks by the news that 801 forests
have been sold, far less that there is no access to 800 of them. Selling off
forests leads to big five-barred gates, all of them shut; it means problems for
wild animals and birds and it does not lead to more jobs. Now that is not good
politics.
People admire the Forestry Commission. It has green vans, builds paths and
tracks, lets people use them and smiles a lot. At this rate there will be no
Forestry Commission left, no access to woodland, and an awful lot of trouble
for the politicians who promoted such a lousy policy. Now might be the time for
a policy review. It wouldn't do for you to be named after the Forestry
Commission's house magazine. What's it called, now? Ah yes, The Slasher.
</TEXT>
