<TEXT>
IT was 10 cold Christmases ago that oor ain Beat Poets first followed the
advice of an age-old firm of instrumentalists - Diddley, Dale, and Jones - and
began dropping the hammer on Silent Night.
``Dear uncles Bo, Dick and Booker T insisted that playing loud was the best way
to fend off Yuletide chills,'' reminisces head Beat Poet Tom Rafferty. While
their contemporaries have all lost their sparkle, the Beat Poets still gleam
with tinselled brilliance - and this year they're doing their bit for a
year-round good cause by recording their rambunctious version of Silent Night
for the nation's homeless.
Available on CD from a Big Issue vendor near you, Silent Night is intended to
provide fundraising cheer for those to whom Christmas Day is, like every other
day, a bleak one. ``Silent Night grew out of a chance meeting with journalist
Andrew O'Hagan, following the Glasgow launch of his book, The Missing, which
considers Fred West's brutal culling of the lost and the displaced. He put us
in touch with the Big Issue after we'd talked about the resonances of Silent
Night for folk who don't have homes and end up dossing on noisy city streets.''
Naturally, the Beat Poets will be adding their own joyous racket to Scottish
streets in the next few weeks. Tomorrow at 1pm they'll be performing Silent
Night in Glasgow's George Square.
In addition, the band will be appearing al fresco during Shine On, Glasgow's
city-centre festive entertainments season. On December 3, they'll be rocking a
Christmas tree in Buchanan Street. On December 10, Shine On's giant cuckoo
clock at the junction of Sauchiehall Street and Cambridge Street will feature
the Beat Poets as rock'n'roll roosters.
Regular gig-goers will be able to enjoy the Beat Poets, plus the Kaisers, on a
mini-tour which visits Glasgow (Archaos, December 7), Aberdeen (Lemon Tree,
December 8), Edinburgh (Music Box, December 9) and Newcastle (Riverside,
December 10).
For Christmas Tom Rafferty would like a box of jellied fruits; warm dry homes
for all; Silent Night in the top 10; and world peace. Buy the Beat Poets'
Silent Night and you'll help at least one of his dreams come true.
n.Silent Night is also on sale from Monday in branches of FOPP, HMV, Tower,
Virgin, Avalanche, Ripping, 1Up and Impulse in Glasgow, Edinburgh, Aberdeen,
Motherwell and Hamilton, priced #3.99.
DAVID BELCHER
</TEXT>
