<HEADLINE>Recognising today's political void</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WELCOMED Arthur Scargill's courageous and honest attempt to instigate a
debate within the labour movement over the future position of socialists within
a Labour Party that has unashamedly shifted to the centre of British politics.
The level of condemnation from some sections of the Labour Party, however,
reflects just how bereft the party has become of ideological discussion.
Indeed, Labour has shifted so far to the right of politics that its activists
comfortably adopt the rhetoric of the Conservatives (Letters, November 14).
Mr Scargill did not destroy the NUM: lest the passage of 11 years has dimmed
some memories, the 1984 strike was the culmination of a struggle between the
free-market economic policies of the Conservative Government, and the
preservation of jobs and working-class community.
The reason the Labour Party finds it difficult to refrain from the vitriolic
personal denigration of Mr Scargill is because it still cannot face up to its
shameful part in failing to support the NUM in its struggle.
To liken Scargill to Field Marshal Haig and condemn him for seeking to split
Labour is hopelessly inaccurate. There are large numbers of people whose
socialist views are no longer represented by a mainstream British political
party, and there are too many younger people who are unable to identify with
any of the mainstream political parties.
Mr Scargill should be congratulated for recognising the political void that
exists today, and ought to be applauded for addressing these very real
challenges.
Bruce R Shields,
106 Barleyknowe Road,
Gorebridge, Midlothian.
</TEXT>
