<HEADLINE>Karadzic and Mladic charged with further crimes against humanity Bosnian Serb duo indicted a second time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>The Hague, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Yugoslav war crimes tribunal today indicted Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic and his army commander, General Ratko Mladic, for crimes against
humanity and genocide for the massacre of Muslims in the UN safe area of
Srebrenica last July.
It was the second time the two leaders had been indicted. In July they were
charged with crimes against Bosnia's Muslim and Croat population, including
attacks on the capital, Sarajevo.
The UN tribunal sitting in The Hague said today's indictment related to ``one
of the bloodiest acts of the war in the former Yugoslavia . . . involving
crimes of an unprecedented cruelty against the Bosnian Muslim population''.
Meanwhile, an American reporter says he found evidence of two suspected
massacre sites in Serb-held Bosnia before he was arrested and held prisoner for
10 days.
He followed a trail of witness descriptions and information from US
intelligence sources.
Near a school in the small town of Sahanici, where three survivors said they
were held before being blindfolded and driven to a field to be executed,
journalist David Rohde said he found evidence of two graves large enough to
hold a total of at least 1000 men.
``I found two areas of fresh digging on either side of a railroad track,'' he
said. Rohde's report on his findings appears in today's editions of The
Christian Science Monitor.
The 28-year-old journalist was captured at gunpoint on October 29. He was
released November 8 and returned to Boston, Massachusetts, two days later.
In a pile of more than 100 garments near the largest grave, Rohde said he found
three canes and a crutch, personal photographs and Muslim identification cards
- one from the United Nations-declared ``safe haven'' of Srebrenica, which fell
to Bosnian Serb forces in July.
Rohde said he believes the crutch and canes belonged to a group of elderly men
who asked for sanctuary at an enclave of Dutch UN peacekeepers near Srebrenica.
But the Dutch soldiers also were forced to flee, and except for a handful of
survivors who spoke with Rohde, the old men were rounded up and executed, he
said.
The International Red Cross has reported that of 40,000 Muslims who fled
Srebrenica, some 8500 men are still unaccounted for.
Nine men who survived by playing dead told Rohde that thousands of Muslim
prisoners were executed on July 14, 15, and 16 at several different sites.
Bosnian Serbs have said no civilians were massacred; rather, the graves contain
the bodies of Muslim soldiers who were killed during the fighting.-AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
