<HEADLINE>Charting the  rocking waters David Belcher finds timeless collections of inspiration for today's bands in the vaults of Ace records, while a home-grown band aims to brighten Christmas for the homeless</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>boss grooves</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975339561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOSTALGIA isn't what it was. Learning from history is preferable to
regurgitating it, surely. What am I on about? Oasis's much-hyped Christmas
cracker, Wonderwall, the single: it's twisting me melons, man. Oasis, as you'll
know, have been hailed as leading contenders in the ongoing revival of Britpop
plc. Their main rivals, Blur? Too calculated, some might say. Soft southerners:
their problem is they think too much. But oh, them bluff northern Oasis lads.
They must be better because they're evidently more natural, untutored,
instinctive. Oasis? Natural? Instinctive? So's athlete's foot.
But why am I increasingly irked by Oasis? Because it's easy to picture Noel
Gallagher listening to his old Beatles albums, and simply opting to invest the
Fab Four with a bit of post-industrial Mancunian sarky. Getting down to the
nittimost of the grittimost, Wonderwall is a duff George Harrison album.
At least when Blur nick a sixties song title - The Universal was initiated by
the Small Faces - they come up with a gutsy song that's better than the
original.
The fact is that there's tons of stuff better than the Beatles. Fittingly, I am
pondering such matters as I sit inside a small cupboard in an unprepossessing
industrial unit on a tatty west London business park next to a greasy canal.
For this small windowless room is the heart of the Ace reissue empire. In here
Ace musicologists assemble timeless collections of yon Afro-American primal
rock'n'roll gumbo; undying compilations of vintage funk, jazz, and soul.
It was about 20 years ago today, to coin a phrase, that the Ace organisation
began charting the fertile old breeding grounds of rock'n'roll. But it all
began much, much earlier, as Ace co-founder Roger Armstrong reveals.
Armstrong's Belfast childhood was shaped by Buddy Holly and a clued-up elder
brother. ``Thanks to him, when the Beatles appeared, I'd heard the original,
more immediate versions of some of the songs they covered.''
As a teenager, Armstrong made two vital discoveries. ``You could buy three
deleted singles for the price of one new one, and some labels could mean
something, could guarantee quality. Stuff on the red Atlantic label was bound
to be good, whereas in addition to the Beatles, Parlophone meant Ken Dodd,
too.''
Armstrong's philosophy studies at Queen's University, Belfast, led to him and
his student chums in the Esoteric Music Society staging gigs which regularly
drew between 700 and 1500 entertainment-starved people.
Armstrong's first big-name gig featured Arthur ``Big Boy'' Crudup, touring
mainland Britain to 30-strong audiences. That's Alright Now Mama was Arthur's
song. Yon Elvis boy had his first hit with it ..... what would have happened to
him if he'd confined himself to listening to Bing Crosby?
Having left uni, Armstrong went to London and became involved in managing Irish
bands. He secured one bunch a #20,000 recording deal. When he went to tell them
the good news, they looked pained, explaining they'd just broken up. ``I asked
them to reform, if only for one album. For #20,000. They wouldn't. Bloody
musicians. They'd broken up; I was flat broke.''
But if you can't trust bands, you can depend on records.
Ted Carroll was another Irish exile in London. Having managed Thin Lizzy, he'd
retreated to a three-day-a-week record stall at a Soho street-market. Selling
records was fine; making them was more exciting, however. The Chiswick label
was born.
``Our sole capital was the old vinyl we had. Another single at the time had a
line: `It's easy. It's cheap. Go and do it.' We did.''
Chiswick grew to encompass two market stalls selling vintage vinyl and US
cut-outs by cults like the Stooges and the MC5, plus one shop housing the
label's office in a back room. Chiswick's talent-spotting reputation grew
faster. Hopefuls besieged Ted and Roger with tapes - and one such tape altered
the course of Scottish rock history.
BACK in 1977 wee Jim Kerr posted a track, Saints And Sinners, by his band,
Johnny and the Self Abusers. Chiswick liked it. It reminded them of the Sweet.
``But then we lost the tape. They sent us another. By the time we were ready to
release it, the band had changed their name. They wrote asking if it was too
late to reprint everything with the new name. It wasn't, but we told them it
was. Why? Because we'd done wonderful pre-sales figures on the strength of
Johnny and the Self Abusers ..... Simple Minds didn't have the same ring.''
Despite good sales for big Chiswick hits the label was failing financially.
Gradually, as Chiswick withered, the Ace reissue label thrived. It now
encompasses everything from fifties jazz to seventies retro-funk by way of
post-punk quiffabilly and sixties northern soul. Little Richard; Bobby Bland;
Eddie Cochran; boxed sets of Stax singles. The Everly Brothers; Creedence
Clearwater Revival; Isaac Hayes; Link Wray; John Lee Hooker; Ofra Haza.
``We carry 1500 album-titles, much more than any big label. For that reason and
many others, I don't see us as part of the record industry at all. We're
repertoire driven. We make sure our stuff sounds good by working direct from
the original master-tapes, not reprocessed-from-mono rubbish.
``But we're basically a nickel-and-dime organisation with no marketing muscle.
And the mainstream business is principally marketing-driven.''
But what of the big reissue question: if tracks weren't good enough to come out
at the time they were recorded, surely they can't be good enough now.
``On take one of The Wanderer, a piece of history which has sold 50 million
copies, you hear Dion say: `I can't handle these lyrics.' He manages it on
second take, after which he says: `OK, next ..... Kansas City.' Bang. How can
it be bad to have greater insights into the way records were made?''
Are you listening to the Ace credo, Mr Gallagher?
n.FIVE lucky Boss Groovers can each win the fabulous new Chiswick Story double
CD - featuring a host of top tunesmiths plus erstwhile self-abuser Jimmy Kerr -
and an Ace T-shirt. Simply tell me, on a postcard, the title of the first
Chiswick release. Mail your entry before next Friday, November 24, to: David
Belcher Is Ace, The Herald, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow, G1 1QP.
n.AND five lucky Erasure fans can each win an Erasure T-shirt by simply telling
me the names of the Erasure duo. As a bonus, the first correct entrant drawn
from my boater will receive a special Erasure wrist-watch. Postcard entries to
David Belcher Is Not In Erasure at the same address by next Friday.
</TEXT>
