<HEADLINE>#500m to tackle crumbling schools</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE bill for tackling long-term disrepair in Scotland's crumbling schools
amounts to nearly #500m, the Liberal Democrats said yesterday in a devastating
attack on the Government's spending priorities.
The leader of the party in Scotland, Mr Jim Wallace, said the cost of tackling
the backlog of repairs had risen by 10% since local authorities last returned
figures, 18 months ago, for the funds they needed to bring schools up to
standard.
He said: ``It is an outrage that, time after time, the Government has refused
to give the green light for essential repairs or for new buildings.
``In Central region, for instance, the council estimates it would require about
#9.2m a year over the next 10 years to bring building stock up to a
satisfactory condition.''
The result was teachers and pupils enduring decaying classrooms, he said. Apart
from the nursery vouchers scheme - which Liberal Democrats were sceptical about
- the Scottish education measures outlined in the Queen's speech merely
tinkered with administrative matters.
``Overall, just #70m has been given to all of Scotland's school buildings. The
Government appears to be continuing to squeeze public life to pay for the
inevitable pre-election tax cuts,'' Mr Wallace said.
Several local authorities gave estimates of the funding needed to tackle major
school building repairs and maintenance. They included: Strathclyde (#142m);
Grampian (#72m); Lothian (#69m); Fife (#36m); and Highland (#34m).
Strathclyde region's deputy director of education responsible for school
buildings, Mr David Dunbar, said: ``In some cases, the position is quite
serious and there is no doubt that teachers and young people are working in
conditions that are far from ideal.''
The new unitary authorities, which will operate under severe financing
constraints, will be under increased pressure to make more efficient use of
their resources.
Scottish Education Minister Raymond Robertson, said: ``Regional councils have
substantial resources at their disposal, and it is for them to decide on their
spending priorities.''
</TEXT>
