<HEADLINE>Nothing sells like a dame Beauty is only skin deep, and no-one knows that better than Dame Barbara Cartland. JANE SCOTT considers her ability to spot a marketing opportunity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975339566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEING on the receiving end of a full-scale campaign launched by Dame Barbara
Cartland must be, one gains the impression, an exhausting business. It is with
an air of bemusement at a force stronger than nature that Robert Smith,
marketing director of a health supplements company favoured by Dame Barbara,
tells the story of how she persuaded his firm to create a new skin-care product
which Scottish women are now clamouring to buy.
Ayesha's Flame, Dame Barbara claimed in a recent interview with The Herald,
smoothes wrinkles, crows' feet, blemishes and even scars. Soon after taking the
vitamin and mineral mix pills for the first time, she told interviewer Phil
Penfold: ``I looked in a mirror and everything had gone. Positively everything.
Even my appendix scar.''
At a stroke, she created a new market for the product in Scotland, a feat she
replicated nationwide on Sunday when she told South Bank Show presenter Melvyn
Bragg about the benefits of Flame.
Since then, the company's three phone lines have been jammed solid with orders;
Dame Barbara can spot a marketing opportunity, even on someone else's behalf,
when she sees one.
``The product actually started with Dame Barbara herself,'' says Smith,
marketing director of Cheshire firm Cedar Health.
``We have another product, basically a calcium supplement called Porosis D
intended to help prevent osteoporosis in later life, and Dame Barbara had been
taking this for some time at the suggestion of her naturopath. After some time
he commented that her nails and hair and skin were looking better, and the only
thing he could put it down to was the supplement.''
Most other supplements, he says, use inexpensive calcium carbonate, whereas
Porosis D uses calcium citrate, the most easily absorbed form.
``Dame Barbara contacted us and said, look, you're selling this product wrong.
Women aren't interested in their bones, women can't see their bones; what
they're interested in is their skin, their hair and how they look, and you
should be selling this product as a beauty product.
``We said no, we really don't want to change three years of marketing on this
one. But she wouldn't go away. She was so insistent, she really believed in the
product.''
There is a pause, as he reflects on the number of calls this belief engendered.
Cedar Health, of course, gave in; further development with the Danish
biochemist who created the original product, the addition of vitamins with
antioxidant properties (the subject of current medical debate; some claim high
antioxidant doses are beneficial in heart disease and some cancers) and
Ayesha's Flame was born in tablet and face cream form. (Ayesha is the name of
an Egyptian goddess who remained eternally young by entering a blue flame of
youth to preserve her beauty.)
The product contains calcium citrate (for soft, supple skin) vitamin A (for
healthy skin cell tissue), magnesium (activates the vitamins and keeps the skin
toned), vitamin C (helps create collagen, the connective tissue); vitamin D
(stimulates the body's calcium use) and vitamin E (strengthens the blood
vessels).
But before you get too excited: ``I can't see any reason why any of these
should have the effects (that Dame Barbara claimed),'' said Dr Wilfred
Turnbull, senior lecturer in human nutrition at Queen Margaret's College
dietetics department in Edinburgh.
``Judging by the composition, basically it is more like a multi-vitamin and
mineral preparation.
``There could be a benefit in taking mineral supplements if you are deficient,
but deficiencies are very, very rare in the UK.''
None the less, sales of Flame have done well over the past three years, Smith
says, although they are now about to go through the roof.
``It was all really down to Dame Barbara, her insistence, and persistence. She
certainly is quite singleminded.'' The company, whose major interest has
previously been in licensed natural medicines, is extremely gratified by the
public interest. ``We have been quite overwhelmed.'' Indeed.
n.A month's course of 120 tablets costs #7.98, as does a 50g jar of cream.
Available from Cedar Health (Pepper Road, Bramhall Moor Lane, Hazel Grove,
Cheshire SK7 5BW, 0161-483 1235, postage free for orders over #10), or from
health food shops, including Forrest &amp; Niven, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
