<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Facing reality of drugs culture Thom Dibdin examines demands for the Bill in response to drug deaths at `raves' to include harm-reduction measures as well as making club owners carry more responsibility</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Thom Dibdin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL Forsyth's decision to introduce a Bill implementing new controls on the
licensing of dance events has received support from all sections of the
clubbing and dance community. However, many believe it does not go far enough
and that testing of drugs for purity should also be introduced.
The Bill will be based on guidelines, due to be published next month, which are
being drawn up by the Scottish Drugs Forum (SDF) following recommendations made
by the Scottish Drugs Task Force report of 1994. In this, concerns were
expressed about the increasing incidence of recreational drug use in Scotland
and the number of drug-related fatalities in Scottish nightclubs.
``It is widely believed and acknowledged that the environment in which drugs
like ecstasy are taken can have a tremendous bearing on the effects of the
drug,'' according to Lee Fawcett who is preparing the guidelines for SDF.
Unlike the tragic case of Leah Bett, who appears to have died after an allergic
reaction to ecstasy, most fatalities have occurred through chronic over-heating.
``The major cause of death associated with ecstasy poisoning is a syndrome
likened to heatstroke, if not from heatstroke itself,'' says Fawcett. ``The
body becomes so dehydrated - through the effects of the drug, through incessant
dancing, through the hot environment and through lack of fluid intake - that it
is no longer able to cool itself down.''
Although Forsyth's statement on Wednesday specifically mentioned ``raves'',
Fawcett points out that the guidelines should apply equally to all kinds of
dance events held on licensed premises.
``The problem with using the word `rave' is that it has become a word which
promoters have become used to dodging,'' she says.
Fawcett claims that unscrupulous club owners turn off water supplies and charge
extortionate prices for water from the bar. They overfill clubs and also give
inappropriate treatment to people who are experiencing an adverse reaction to
drugs.
``These are the things that the guidelines are aiming to address,'' she
says,``plus providing information which will inform people of the risks of
taking drugs, and for those who insist on using drugs, despite the risks, ways
of reducing those risks. Harm associated with drug use can be reduced
significantly by safer clubs and more responsible drug use.''
This emphasis on harm reduction and education diverges widely from the
increasingly rejected ``just say no'' campaigns of the past.
It tacitly accepts that drug use is here to stay. ``We are looking at a youth
culture which has embraced the recreational use of drugs more than any previous
generation,'' says Fawcett. ``I don't think there is any way that anyone can
stop people taking drugs.''
This admission is borne out both by the existence of a Scottish Office funded
project, Enhance, and the attitudes of its volunteers. The Glasgow-based
project uses young people who take ecstasy on a recreational basis to educate
others about the risks.
``The guidelines take the onus off the drug user and put it back on the
clubs,'' according to Justine, who is an Enhance volunteer. ``They are making
money out of our drug use and it is about time they started putting something
back. It has always been seen as the drug user's fault for taking it in the
first place, which should not be the case.''
Caroline, another volunteer, believes the guidelines should be taken one step
further and provide a testing service for ecstasy users. ``People should not be
so elitist and moralistic about drug use,'' she says. ``They must realise that
we can stop a lot of deaths by testing what people are using so they are not
getting dog-worming tablets or whatever. All the worst drugs are imported into
Britain because dealers know that we don't test.''
The volunteers do not believe that the guidelines promote drug use. ``It is
more a case of pro-drug user than pro-drug,'' says Nellie Smith.
Clubs where incessant dancing and drug use take place are rarely run by the
people who own the venues. Young club runners, desperate to promote their
favourite DJs and style of music, are at the mercy of the owners.
Alan Gray, who helps promote clubs in Paisley and Glasgow, welcomes the support
which the Bill will give him in ensuring that his patrons have a safe night
out. ``To make people pay for water is wrong,'' he says. ``We won't let the
Government privatise water so why should we allow venues to do the same and
make a vast profit?''
Fawcett points out that many clubs are already operating in accordance with the
guidelines. In Edinburgh, the regular Rezerection events attract up to 5000
young people to dance all night. The promoters have a close relationship with
the Edinburgh District Council who ensure that health and safety issues are
kept to the fore.
Councillor Dickie Alexander, chair of the licensing board, says it is good to
be able to exercise a form of protection. ``Not to control young people,
because I don't believe in that, but to give them some boundaries that they can
operate within.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
