<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dundee's political parties unite over #18m crisis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN ALL-PARTY appeal was made yesterday for the Government to bail Dundee out of
an #18m cash shortage which could force school closures, job losses and a 50%
increase in council tax.
The situation is so serious that a leading right-wing Tory is supporting the
Labour council's plea for more money.
Mr Neil Powrie, leader of the Tory group on Dundee District Council and
chairman of the Scottish Conservative local government advisory committee,
joined Labour and the SNP in criticising the Government's funding plans for the
new unitary authority.
He is alarmed at the scale of cuts needed to balance the books and the huge
rise in council tax required.
Last night, Councillor Powrie explained his decision for joining an all-party
delegation to lobby Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth: ``Dundee is in a unique
position. The city has a very low tax base and for years services have been
funded by council tax payers in Angus and Perth.
``Only 38,000 out of Dundee's 115,000 voters pay any council tax and, with the
loss of tax revenue from the surrounding areas, a shortfall is inevitable.''
He added: ``The Government needs to review local government funding on a
Scottish-wide basis. Some new councils have been given too much money, while
Dundee has a shortfall.''
The leader of the Labour administration, Councillor Kate Maclean, said: ``The
Scottish Office grant aid is based on a formula which was designed for the old
councils, not the new unitary authorities.
``The fact is that the Scottish Office capping limit of #177 for providing
services in the new Dundee City Council is likely to be considerably less than
is currently being spent on essential services in the city by the existing
regional and district councils.
``So, through no fault of its own, Dundee is looking at a huge budget deficit
and the likelihood of large council tax increases next year.''
Ms Maclean added: ``All the political groups on Dundee City Council, council
employees, the trade unions and the people of Dundee now need to work together
to fight for the city and send a powerful message to the Scottish Secretary.''
A Scottish Office spokesman said: ``Next year's settlements have not yet been
finalised but Ministers are aware of the problem. The Secretary of State has
asked Cosla for their recommendations on how to solve the problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
