<HEADLINE>The Fiesta's facelift It's all change for Ford's favourite. Ross Finlay approves. Traditionalists might need a little time</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS USUAL, Ford has been teasing out the launch programme for the new Fiesta.
The autumn season has seen the first details being published, then the car's
appearance at motor shows, and finally the chance to buy it from a showroom.
As the best-selling small car in Britain, the Fiesta has gone through several
model generations since it was introduced in 1977. More than two million
examples have been sold in this country alone. Even in its final year, the
run-out version has held its place as number two in the overall national sales
charts, behind the Escort.
Ford is sometimes criticised for making headline changes to cars which are
essentially the same as their immediate predecessors.
Although the basic structure remains the same, as anybody prowling around the
cars on show at the SECC will have seen, that is certainly not the case with
the latest Fiesta. It has all-new exterior panels, a more attractive interior,
new suspension, and a range of brand-new engines in addition to revised
versions of the familiar units.
Ford has been tinkering around, not always successfully, with the front-end
treatment of its various model ranges. The Fiesta has a much stronger identity
here than some other cars with the blue oval badge, even if traditionalists
will probably take some time to accept it.
There is no doubt, however, that the new fascia is one of the most stylish in
the small-car class, although some of the practical stowage space in the older
model, which continues for the time being as the Fiesta Classic, has gone. In
both materials and design, the once familiar Ford bias towards being
utilitarian has disappeared.
Heart of the car, of course, is the engine, and here Ford offers some brand-new
designs plus some modified versions of the existing types. The latest 16-valve
twin-cam Zetec-SE engine, designed by Ford with input from Yamaha, is a
lightweight all-alloy affair to be seen first in the 1.2-litre size which peaks
at just under 75bhp. Next year, a 1.4-litre 90bhp type will be added.
Two of the present engines survive, though in modified form. The familiar 60bhp
1.3-litre, and the similarly powered 1.8-litre diesel are now tagged the
Endura-E and the Endura-D.
At launch, there are four trim and equipment levels from Encore through LX and
Si to Ghia. Each comes as a three-door or five-door, and you can have any
engine you like with any trim level or body style.
Despite the various body changes, the whole new Fiesta programme is really
engineering-led. The new Zetec-E engines are livelier and smoother, the whole
power-train is quieter and better balanced, and there are features in the
specification which Ford has never offered on its small cars before.
For example, an option on all new Fiestas (except the Encore) is a combination
of anti-lock brakes, traction control and electronic brake force distribution,
which nips into action before the ABS comes into play.
The difference most people will notice, comparing the new Fiesta with the old,
is how much quieter the latest version is. Richard Parry-Jones's team, which
was so heavily involved with noise path analysis on the latest Escort, played
the same part in the development of the Fiesta.
Together with an enhanced ride quality, the suppression of noise is one of the
features which shows that Ford has really taken its new-generation small car
seriously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Winter at Ford Unreasonable union behaviour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORD workers who have rejected a very acceptable wage settlement and watched
their colleagues at two factories go on unofficial strike are behaving like a
dairy herd released into the field after a long winter. They sniff the spring
air, kick their heels, and generally do daft things. The problem with the
actions of the Ford unions is that industrial spring is not here, indeed may be
delayed for the foreseeable future. In single-handedly attempting to recreate
the feel-good factor in a corner of British industry Ford workers may believe
that they are in the vanguard of a resurrection of traditional union values and
practices. There is nothing wrong with the traditions and aspirations which
have motivated the union movement in this country for many years. At their best
they lifted workers from conditions in which they have been used and abused for
scant recompense and they may have to perform this service again.
Other sorts of trade union practice, the sort that resulted in bullying and
unreasonable behaviour, have had quite the opposite effect on an honourable
tradition. Unfortunately it is the car workers, who have not historically been
the most downtrodden workers in British industry, who are among those best
remembered for unreasonable behaviour. Certainly, there is a good deal of
cheering at the news of the rejection of a 9.25% increase in wages over two
years, but most of it comes from back bench Tory MPs who sense a golden
opportunity to attack the Labour movement and New Labour.
Just as with traditional union values, there is nothing wrong with a fair wage
rise. British workers have watched a high tide of money flow into the
boardrooms of too many companies to feel that a decent reticence has much place
in modern industry. Nevertheless there has to be a sense of the context in
which these events take place at present, particularly the growth of the Labour
Party into a position from which it can win the next General Election. This
should be the concern of unionists but those in Ford have either not grasped
the point or do not care. New Labour will have to handle its reaction to this
event with caution, but it is not alone. The Chancellor of the Exchequer will
have been pleased by the fall in inflation figures but at a time when evidence
is mounting of a distinct hiccup in the economic recovery he will not want to
see inflationary wage rises. Perhaps Mr Clarke and Mr Blair could work in
sensible concert. The Chancellor could have a word with Ford management and Mr
Blair could speak to the unions; that would herald spring indeed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
