<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ex-chairman of Hibs admits to #80,000 fraud</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KENNY WAUGH, the former chairman of Hibs Football Club, yesterday admitted
defrauding the Inland Revenue of #80,000 in his bookmaking business, by giving
tax-free bonuses to employees.
Waugh, 58, pleaded guilty that at his Edinburgh premises between August 1987
and August 1992, he pretended that receipts of wages paid to his employees were
accurate, when he knew they showed lower wages than were actually paid,
resulting in him paying lower income tax and national insurance contributions,
and so defrauding the Inland Revenue of a total of #80,000.
Miss Vicky Roger, depute fiscal, said at Edinburgh Sheriff Court, that Waugh,
of Glenlockhart Bank, Edinburgh, had instituted and continued a system of an
untaxed supplement or bonus given to employees in addition to their normal
wages, but no deductions were made from it.
The matter came to light after Inland Revenue inspectors suspected that the
scheme was in operation and made inquiries.
Mr Gordon Jackson, QC, for the defence, said Waugh became a bookie in 1963 and
had built up a successful business. During the time of the offence, he had
between 11 and 17 betting shops and employed a large number of people.
He got into the way of giving his employees a bonus. If a betting shop had a
good week, the manager could take a bonus and give a bonus to other staff.
It was not a regular thing when it started but became more regular and began to
feel like an entitlement.
In 1988, Waugh became seriously ill and was off work for 18 months. During that
time, his managers continued to pay the bonus, and this went on until 1992.
Mr Jackson said: ``The irony of the situation is that he got nothing out of it
- not one penny piece of advantage has come to him.''
Mr Jackson produced a letter to show Waugh had repaid the #80,000 to the Inland
Revenue.
Waugh had retired because he had a serious heart problem and his son ran the
business. Part of the price for ``this sorry mess'' had been the worsening of
his medical condition.
There had been a two-year delay in the case until November last year, and Waugh
had suffered from massive stress.
Sheriff Iain Macphail, QC, said he had a duty to consider a jail sentence in a
case such as Waugh's.
He deferred sentence until December 7 and called for social inquiry and
community service reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kenya `not to blame' for death of Ward</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nairobi, Thursday
KENYA has rejected a claim by British hotelier John Ward for reimbursement of
the costs of his private investigation into the murder of his daughter.
Attorney-General Amos Wako filed papers with the High Court in Nairobi, saying
``Kenya was not to blame'' for the death of Julie Ward ``and does not accept
any liability''.
The partially dismembered body of Miss Ward, 28, was found in the Masai Mara
game reserve in September, 1988.
Her father launched his own investigation after the state initially termed her
death a suicide. It later conceded she was murdered, but no-one has ever been
convicted of the crime.
Mr Ward filed a lawsuit seeking compensation from the Kenyan Government for
#300,000 he has spent on his own seven-year investigation.-AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Liaison officer `challenged his neighbours to a fight'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COMMUNITY policeman woke up his neighbours and challenged them to a fight in
the early hours of the morning, a court heard yesterday.
Constable Stephen Boag, 37, shouted and swore outside the house of his startled
neighbours and demanded: ``Get outside and I'll give you a square go, you
bastards!''
Yesterday, Boag pleaded guilty to a breach of the peace charge.
The court has heard that Boag, with 15 years' service, had already been
suspended from duty at the time of the offence.
Boag, of Baluniefield Road, Dundee, admitted that, on August 12 this year, he
conducted himself in a disorderly manner, shouted and swore, and committed a
breach of the peace.
Dundee Sheriff Court heard that there had been ``bad feeling'' between Boag and
his neighbours, the McHardy family, for days before the incident.
At 2.15am on August 12, Mr and Mrs McHardy were woken by someone opening their
gate and when they looked out they saw Boag standing on the pavement and
shouting.
He came back five minutes later and started shouting at them again and
continued to do so even after police were called to the scene.
Depute-fiscal Vivien Kennedy told the court that Boag was a community liaison
officer who is currently suspended from duty because of an investigation into
another matter.
Solicitor-advocate Peter Watson, defending, said there had not been a ``one-way
traffic of abuse'' and added that Boag had served for 15 years in the police
without a ``blemish on his character''. However, Mr Watson admitted that Boag
had a ``problem'' which had now been acknowledged and that he was to receive
counselling from occupational health officials with Tayside Police.
A plea of not guilty to another breach of the peace charge was accepted by the
depute-fiscal.
Sheriff Anella Cowan deferred sentence for three months for Boag to be of good
behaviour. The sheriff called for an updated psychiatric report and a report
from Tayside Police's occupational health department.
Last night, Inspector Jim O'Donnell of Tayside Police complaints and discipline
branch, said: ``Disciplinary proceedings will be considered when the matter has
been finalised by the court.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Loach set to start filming in Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEN Loach, whose film Land and Freedom, about the Spanish civil war, won the
Felix, the European Oscar, is to start work this week in Glasgow on his next
film provisionally entitled Carla's Song.
Written by Mr Paul Laverty, a Glasgow lawyer, it is about a love affair between
a bus driver, George, played by Robert Carlyle, who starred in Loach's film,
Riff-Raff, also a European film of the year, and Carla, a Nicaraguan refugee.
The film will be shot in Glasgow until Christmas and then the cast and crew
move to Nicaragua in January for five weeks. Produced by Sally Hibbin, Carla's
Song has been backed by the Glasgow Film Fund and the Scottish Film Production
Fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The public is deserting the high streets for the comparative safety of the modern shopping centre - an oasis which has bred a new phenomenon among the young: the mall mice. Stephen McGinty gives chase Mall mice find bolt hole</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGinty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM the St Enoch Centre, Glasgow, to the Aventura Mall, Miami, is 8000 miles
and one exhausted crow. Yet the posture of kids remains the same. Propped up
against a wall, slouching with baseball cap tipped over his eyes, Carlos was
``hookie'' from school among the potted trees and fountains of one of Miami's
slickest shopping centres.
Maurice was simply suspended till his hair grew in, or his black biker's jacket
was replaced, allowing re-entry to his school in East Kilbride. Until then the
polished walkways, glinting glass of the big city shopping citadels were, for
both, a cool enough hangout.
In America such kids are christened Mall Rats, now celebrated by Hollywood in a
new movie starring Shannon Docherty of Beverly Hills 90210 fame. Yet Scotland's
shopping malls are the home of a smaller, milder breed, the mall mice.
While their American counterparts deal drugs, indulge in gang fights and
vandalism under the temperature-controlled roofs of the malls, young Scots say
these buildings are a safe sanctuary from such anti-social behaviour.
Even 14-year-old Carlos admitted playing look-out for friends on a shoplifting
spree. ``Nobody misses it and we haven't been caught.'' Yet across the ocean it
was the St Enoch's calmness which Maurice admired.
It is a new idea to those who believe the words ``young'' and ``hoodlum'' are
inseparable. But it is backed by research from Sheffield University which has
revealed that only 5% of 11 to 14-year-olds said they would allow their own
kids into a town centre alone. More than 40% said they would only take their
children to malls. Young people felt threatened by the town centre ``yobbos''.
Almost the exact same words were used by Maurice and his mates as they hung
around across from Bargain Books in the centre's ground floor. ``It's safe here
compared with home. You don't get hassled by yobbos. It's really nice and
clean. In the High Street in East Kilbride it's rough. Guys beat you up, but
not here, 'cause they would just get lifted,'' said Sean Clark, 19.
Fear of city-centre crime, beggars, drunks, and vagrants were also cited this
week by researchers at Leicester University as the reasons why shoppers are
deserting high streets for shopping malls. Statistics showed that six times as
much crime was suffered by city centre shoppers as their counterparts in malls.
In their report, ``Crime and Security: Managing the Risk to Safe Shopping'',
the authors wrote: ``The bobby on the beat may still patrol town centres but he
or she has been superseded by the private security guard in the shopping mall .
. . both offer the presence of officers in uniforms which the public finds
reassuring.''
They suggest it will take more than the decision by John Gummer, the
environment minister, to place a moratorium on building out-of-town malls to
regenerate a safe shopping environment in many British cities. However, all of
Scotland's cities have major malls in the city centre as well as in outlying
towns.
A number of reasons have led to a drop in juvenile delinquency at the St Enoch
Centre. The ice rink, which was a magnet for high jinks, has shut down. ``Why
was it shut down?'' said deputy centre manager David MacGregor. ``Have you ever
tried to keep an ice rink in a greenhouse? It cost a fortune.'' The centre's
security have also been working with local police and the education department
who regularly sweep through for truants.
It is ironic that their presence is most appreciated by those the public would
expect to occupy them most. But everyone likes security, and the covered floors
of Glasgow's St Enoch Centre and Edinburgh's Waverly Centre, for example, are
an oasis of calm safety. The French anthropologist Marc Auge views shopping
malls as ``non-places'' rooted not in soil but publicity, marketing, and
recycled images.
It is true. In a mall you could be anywhere from Tokyo to Toledo.
Miami's Aventura mall has the same bright lighting, potted plants, and rock
fountains as those the length of Britain. It's big - more than 200 shops,
restaurants, and services - but not as big as The Mall of America in
Minneapolis. Spread out across 78 acres it is the biggest in the world: for
once, no idle American boast. It was here two years ago that school lessons
were first introduced to a series of US malls.
A trial scheme involved teaching children how to be retailers and included work
experience. Mall life across the Atlantic has reached the stage where you can
marry in the ``chapel of love'' and a few years later receive counselling if
your husband gets heavy-handed. Mall culture has never exploded in Britain in a
similar manner; even less so in Scotland.
Yet it is the variety for which MacGregor at St Enoch's enjoys his job. The
centre is like an iceberg, with two-thirds its bulk remaining hidden. As we
stroll the miles of red concrete corridors which run under the ground, off from
the giant loading bay, the size of the centre but below it, he explains that
occasionally the public wander.
``We've found people in back corridors, near the boilers even, claiming to have
been looking for the toilets, but they're casing the joint looking to see if
they can find a store room to swipe from.'' In the data room a panel of five TV
screens films the entire centre, offering the facility to zoom in hundreds of
yards. ``It also works for the bad guys.''
He said last year the centre was contacted by a lawyer defending a man charged
with stealing cars in a city-centre car park. Police officers said he was
arrested at 3pm, yet the man insisted he was arrested at 3pm shoplifting in the
centre. He was proved correct by the tapes. The police case collapsed.
On the subject of wandering teenagers MacGregor is adament that if they are
well behaved they are most welcome. ``I keep telling the security men, these
are tomorrow's shoppers, if you don't treat them properly they won't come back.
``But if they're on bikes, blades, or skateboards, they're out!''
As Christmas approaches, sprinkling fairy lights and late-night shopping along
with it, malls across the country will heat up and begin to hum the tune of
jingling cash registers.
Their sales, however, will not be swollen by any contributions from Maurice or
Sean as they stay between 11am and 4pm ``looking at stuff'' they cannot afford
to buy. Eight thousand miles away Carlos will remain on his stakeout.
``Mall rats never sleep,'' he said.
</TEXT>
