<HEADLINE>Still the hottest property around William Russell looks at the enduring success of the board game which has launched a million millionaires</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GO Directly to Jail, Do Not Pass Go! The familiar commands from one of the
world's favourite board games will be issued tonight at London's Park Lane
Hotel where a #250-a-head black-tie party is being thrown by Waddingtons to
celebrate Monopoly's 60th birthday. To help you go to jail, assuming you try to
steal it, a specially created $2m Monopoly set, consisting of a 24-carat gold
board, will be on show. It is a glittering concoction which has a ruby or a
sapphire set on top of the chimney of each of the 18-carat gold houses and
hotels used as counters, and a dice studded with 42 diamonds.
A total of 168 stones have been implanted in this made-for-Midas objet d'art,
ranging from diamonds to sapphires, rubies to citrines, amethysts to garnets,
and blue topaz to catseye tourmalines and peridots, while to sustain the
capitalist theme the Monopoly money has been specially printed on metallic
gold-coloured paper. Steal that little lot and you could, if caught, very well
end up in jail, from which no amount of double sixes would get you out. Not
that it will be easy to purloin. The board weighs 32lbs, and Sidney Mobell, the
San Francisco jeweller who designed it, will spend the evening handcuffed to it.
Over 480 million people are estimated to have played the real-estate,
beggar-thy-neighbour game since it was created in 1934 in Philadelphia during
the Depression by an unemployed heating engineer called Charles Darrow.
Within months the board game, made from bits and pieces found in his kitchen,
was the rage of the city. Darrow sold some sets through a local department
store, but realising he needed to do things in a big way, or not at all, took
it to Parker Brothers, the world's largest games manufacturers. They did not
spot its potential. Too long to play, too complicated, and far too circular in
conception, they complained. What was more, there was no goal on the board for
the players to reach.
Darrow, therefore, decided to go ahead on his own and the game proved to be all
the rage that Christmas in Philadelphia. The following year the Parker Brothers
bought the rights and by mid-February were producing 20,000 games a week.
Monopoly is now licensed in 45 countries and printed in 25 languages, including
Catalan, Hindi, Arabic, Afrikaans, and Croatian. Darrow was able to retire a
millionaire at the age of 46 and spent the rest of his life travelling the
world and collecting exotic orchids while others carried on selling the licence
to make money he had invented.
At tonight's party the usual suspects from the celebrity A list, or possibly,
given some of the names, the B list - who on earth are Sian Lloyd, David
Jensen, Carol Smillie, and Jeremy Beadle? - will be on board, so to speak, to
play the game for the Children with Leukemia charity. Hugh Grant, Joan Collins,
Jerry Hall, Mick Jagger, and Paula Yates have also been invited, as have six
people who are 60 today.
The 150 celebrities and the 250 paying guests, the ones expected to spend the
money when the set is auctioned because celebrities only put their hands in
other people's pockets, are unlikely to break the record for the longest ever
game. That lasted for 1416 hours (59 days of continuous play), or perhaps it
was 1680 hours (70 straight days' play). Waddingtons, who acquired the British
rights in 1935, are somewhat confused as to which is right and have given both
sets of figures, but either way it went on a bit.
On acquiring the rights they decided to change the names of the properties on
the board, originally places in Atlantic City, to ones British people would be
more familiar with, hence the London place names.
It is said that the head of Waddingtons, Victor Watson, asked his secretary,
Marjory Phillips, to make the selection and on the day she made her choice she
happened to lunch at the Angel pub in Islington, the only pub on the board. The
rest of the names are of streets like Oxford Street or Piccadilly, London
railway stations like Waterloo, districts like Mayfair and, this being a
speculators' game, streets which house police stations, like Vine Street,
Marlborough Street, and Bow Street.
The reigning European Monopoly champion is the teddy-bear collector and games
freak Gyles Brandreth, Tory MP for Chester. He is in good company. Other famous
players include the Queen, Frank Bruno, and Sir Edward Heath.
Monopoly has stood up well to the competition from computer games - Waddingtons
sell some 500,000 sets in the United Kingdom each year - possibly because
Monopoly has not stood still. There is Magnetic Monopoly, Junior Monopoly,
European Monopoly, and on a computer near you, Internet Monopoly. They even
play it in Russia with place names like Red Square and the Kremlin on the board.
Go Directly to the Lubyanka. Forget Glasnost. Pay 1,000,000 roubles.
</TEXT>
