<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q Saturday: Border Ecosse Car Club's Early Winter Rally has an evening start
from Coldstream, and finishes back there after a 90-mile route. As well as
being a round of the East of Scotland rally championship, it has attracted
entries from members of Tyneside Motor Sport Group clubs in north-east England.
q Monday: Also in the Borders, but on a grander scale, the Network Q RAC Rally
brings the final round of the World Rally Championship to Scotland at Wauchope
and Kershope forests.
Wauchope is the more convenient spectator area for people approaching from the
north. It is off the B6357 south of Bonchester Bridge, where the spectator
signposting starts. Scheduled time of the first rally car at Wauchope is 12.54,
but do not expect the full entry to come through, because the long, gruelling
miles in Kielder Forest, just across the border, will undoubtedly have taken
their toll.
The spectator car parks, on roads within the forest, are a short walk from the
stage itself. Parking charge is #5 per car, and on no account try to abandon
your car on the B6357 verges instead. Lothian and Borders Police will make sure
the public road is kept clear for rally and everyday local traffic.
</TEXT>
