<DOCNO>GH951117-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Net sales</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE the source of little more than tacky crystal ornaments and dubious acrylic
clothing, home shopping is being revolutionised by the computer age; TV
shopping, stores and services on the Internet, and now the launch of a 3-D
virtual reality computer shopping experience.
Edinburgh University's announcement this week that it is embarking on a
European project to bring an interactive shopping system to your PC screen, is
just the latest in a long line of retail initiatives pulling customers off the
streets and into their own homes. It's estimated that by the year 2000, 10% of
all retailing and 20% of all grocery shopping will take place via the Internet.
Retail analysts say new-age shopping will make big changes to the way we make
our purchases, but is unlikely to kill off the malls and high streets.
Shopping, they say, is an interactive experience and there will always be those
who prefer dealing with humans to dealing with pixels.
``It is right to say that it is never going to replace shopping,'' says Dr Paul
Freathy of Stirling University's Institute of Retail Studies. ``Some people
will always enjoy shopping, meeting people, walking around, interacting. But
there will always be a certain element who won't have time, even people who
enjoy shopping but find that home shopping suits them better.''
Dr Freathy says if the experience of America was anything to go by, then the
Internet offered vast amounts of room for expansion of shopping initiatives.
``If you look at America, there is a host of different products and services.
The other day I was flicking through and I came across a florist's in Florida
which had different types of flowers displayed, you pay with credit card and
have them despatched there and then. We've got a little bit of a way to go
before we get to that level but it's catching on here,'' he says.
Meanwhile, some retail analysts say that changing demographics and populations
are leading to a much older society which suggests that in 10 to 15 years' time
there will be much more locally based shopping - leading possibly to a revival
in high-street fortunes.
Professor Mervyn Jack is involved in Edinburgh University's latest initiative -
a collaboration between a number of British and European companies. The project
is for a virtual reality on-screen shopping experience with a 3-D assistant who
will talk customers through sizes and colours. The scheme, which will take
three years to develop, is, according to Professor Jack, designed more ``for
the lay person rather than the Nintendo generation''.
He says computers offered an attractive and efficient proposal for stores
because they could operate without the heavy overheads of shops and outlets.
However, he adds that Internet shopping would most likely operate ultimately as
an addition to existing means of shopping. ``It will never supersede shopping
but it will be a valid alternative channel.''
</TEXT>
