<HEADLINE>Army's stray parachutist strains usual hospitality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Highlands may be in the frontline for hospitality but an armed and
camouflaged soldier who arrived in the middle of the night at a remote cottage
just went over the top.
The soldier dropped in - literally from 18,000ft - to Ian and Liz Bishop's
cottage at Slochd, by the A9, near Aviemore, and rang the bell to ask if he
could use their telephone after stormy weather blew him off course during a
night-time parachute jump. He also asked if he could borrow a map.
At first the couple refused to open the door to the armed and menacing figure
dressed in full camouflage gear.
Mr Bishop said: ``We have a rottweiler which was going mad because of the noise
the soldier had been making. We are always particularly careful about answering
the door because we live in such an isolated location.
``I thought he was a complete nutter to start with. I noticed his Army issue
SA80 lightweight rapid-fire rifle with night sights, which made me very worried.
``I thought he had gone AWOL or something and was very scared. But after
speaking to him for a while, I came to the conclusion that he was probably in
the SAS because he would not tell me which regiment he was in, which is usually
a clear sign.''
Mr Bishop eventually relented and opened the door to the lost soldier who even
refused to confirm that he was in the British Army despite his somewhat unusual
appearance and specialised rifle.
The soldier told him he needed to telephone in his grid reference to Army HQ
and let them know he was safe. He also said he was several hours late for a
rendezvous six miles away, at the Eil bothy on Strathspey Estate, near Dulnain
Bridge, and everyone would be worried about him.
Mr Bishop heard the soldier telling Army HQ what had happened to him. He added:
``I then gave him directions on how to get back to the Eil bothy using the
river Dulnain as a guide. He seemed very intelligent and I never saw him again
so I take it he made it alright.''
After the incident, Mr Bishop telephoned his only neighbours, Mr John Redwood
and his wife Judy, three miles away on Seafield Estate. They told him that
another Army parachutist had landed in their garden but had disappeared into
the night without asking for directions.
The incidents happened on Tuesday night in the area which is well known as an
SAS training ground because of its rough terrain and extreme weather.
An Army spokesman did not appear to know what manoeuvres there were in the
area. He said: ``I know the Marines were in Orkney but there's no way they
could have been blown that far off course on a parachute jump.''
</TEXT>
