<HEADLINE>US plans a final push for peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PATRICK BROGAN Washington, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN mediators will make one last great effort to wind up the Bosnian peace
conference this week.
An American source said that there was no prospect of continuing next week. He
may be forced to swallow his words, of course, but it does appear that the
talks have reached a crisis.
The Secretary of State, Warren Christopher, spent Tuesday at the talks in
Dayton, Ohio, then flew on to the Asia-Pacific summit in Japan. He will return
before the end of the week, abandoning APEC, to make a last effort at resolving
the Bosnian conundrum.
His departure will not help US-Japanese relations, which have been difficult
all year. President Clinton decided late on Wednesday to skip the conference
altogether because of the budget crisis in Washington. Vice-President Al Gore
will represent the United States.
The most difficult issues in Bosnia remain the territorial division of the
country between the Serbs and the Muslim-Croat federation; Sarajevo; and the
war criminals.
The Serbs demand restoration of land they lost in the early autumn offensive by
Croats and Muslims. They want the town of Sanski Most returned to them.
The Muslims are even more obdurately set on recovering Srebrenica and Zepa, two
towns in eastern Bosnia that the Serbs overran last summer. The Americans
concede that they have an absolute moral claim on the places, because the Serbs
massacred between 6000 and 10,000 people when they captured Srebrenica.
But they also suggest that if justice pulls one way, peace pulls another. It
makes little sense for the Muslims to return to isolated and indefensible
islets surrounded by a hostile sea of Serbs. They have trouble enough
justifying holding on to Goradze, their last stronghold in eastern Bosnia.
The two sides are equally obdurate over Sarajevo, which the Government wants to
be a united, multi-ethnic city while the Serbs want it divided.
As for the war crimes, President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia would be
quite ready to turn over Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic and any other
Bosnian Serbs the War Crimes Tribunal may want (though they have other ideas).
But some senior officers and political figures in his own armed forces and
Government have been indicted.
So have officers in the Croatian Army. The American and European mediators are
finding it very difficult to finesse the issue.
</TEXT>
