<HEADLINE>Royal Liverpool Philharmonic, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975339584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THANKS to a two-hour standstill on the Edinburgh/Glasgow line, this review must
confine itself to the closing portion of the Royal Liverpool Philharmonic's
concert under Libor Pesek last night - but it was enough to show how well these
players respond to their conductor and to what feels like the century or two of
good Czech musical tradition he has imposed on them.
With such brightness of string tone, such sweetly blended woodwind and radiant,
unraucous brass, Dvorak's Sixth Symphony could not have been in happier hands.
Pesek paces the music of his compatriots with complete understanding, making
the music move easily, comfortably, but with the extra edge of gusto the finale
of this most glowing of Dvorak symphonies requires if it is to cap what has
gone before. The closing burst of speed, the bounce of the rhythms, seemed
perfectly judged.
To the fizz of Smetana's Bartered Bride overture, which followed as encore,
Pesek brought the same natural flow, achieving excitement not by overpressing
the tempo but by the spruce articulation, the nicely turned phrasing, the witty
pointing that can come when the music has space to breathe. The warmth of
violin tone, in a hall that does not always bring out that feature, was notable.
Karajan, it used to be said, brought power-steering to his conducting of the
Berlin Philharmonic. Pesek gave us simple lyricism. I would like to have heard
the whole concert. Last night's large audience will surely welcome him back -
if another exchange between the RLPO and the Royal SNO can be arranged - and so
will I.
</TEXT>
