<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protesters call for fresh inquiry into #200m electricity plans Pipeline `link' to beached bombs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR, DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE controversy surrounding the appearance of wartime munitions on Scottish
beaches has led to a demand for a third public inquiry into plans for an
electricity interconnector between Scotland and Northern Ireland.
Protesters against the proposed #200m electricity link made the demand
yesterday following a report which claims that Government scientists have
established ``beyond reasonable doubt'' that the laying of a gas pipeline
across the North Channel of the Irish Sea led to thousands of phosphorous bombs
being washed ashore on Scottish beaches.
Mr Struan Stevenson, the co-ordinator of the Stop the Overhead Powerlines
(Stop) campaign, which protested against the proposal by ScottishPower and
Northern Ireland Electricity to build more than 40 miles of pylons across South
Ayrshire, and take the electricity from Ballanatrae to Islandmagee by undersea
cable, stressed yesterday that the undersea section of the interconnector was
an area which was not examined at two public inquiries held in Scotland and
Northern Ireland.
``Both inquiries insisted that the undersea section between Currarie Point and
Portmuck South fell outwith their legal jurisdiction.''
Mr Stevenson said that, despite the dislodging of more than 4500 phosphorous
bombs by its undersea trenching activities for the gas pipeline, there was no
doubt that the British Gas subsidiary Premier Transco had conducted ``extensive
undersea surveys prior to commencing work''.
He added: ``By comparison ScottishPower and NIE have conducted limited and
seriously flawed undersea investigations in this area and should now be forced
to defend their proposal before a full public inquiry. I will be contacting
Michael Forsyth as a matter of urgency to seek an early inquiry.''
The months of evidence heard in Ayr and Larne are still being considered by the
Scottish Office Reporter in Edinburgh and his counterpart in Belfast and
preliminary reports are expected to be available early in the New Year.
On Monday the Government launched a two-week survey, of the half-mile deep dyke
in the North Channel between Scotland and Northern Ireland, in a bid to allay
public fears and establish why the phosphorous bombs have been washed up in the
past month.
A report in the New Scientist magazine yesterday claimed that the scientists,
from the Scottish Office's marine laboratory in Aberdeen, had concluded - just
four days into the survey - that it was ``beyond reasonable doubt'' that the
bombs were dislodged by British Gas ploughing operations in preparing the route
for its inter-connector pipeline.
The article further claimed: ``Underwater video footage taken by British Gas's
contractors and studied by the scientists also clearly shows the bombs, and a
host of other metallic wastes, next to the pipeline.''
The Scottish Office yesterday issued a statement from Scottish Environment
Minister Lord Lindsay dismissing the article as unhelpful speculation.
He said: ``The position regarding the phosphorous canisters which have been
washed ashore on the west coast remains the same as I said it was on Monday
when the `Clupea' set sail from Ardrossan to begin its survey.
``There is circumstantial evidence that the recent pipelaying operations may
have caused some disturbance to the seabed. But there is no merit in
speculation of any kind. We need facts.''
British Gas yesterday declined to talk in detail about the magazine article but
said it would ``consider the implications accordingly'', if given the
opportunity to review the reported findings.
However, Scottish MPs yesterday said the reported findings pointed the finger
of blame firmly at British Gas' pipelaying operations.
Mr George Foulkes, the Labour MP for Carrick, Cumnock, and Doon Valley, has
called for a halting of all commercial operations until further safety checks
are carried out.
He said: ``Unless you have visual evidence I suppose you can't prove it totally
conclusively but the phrase `beyond reasonable doubt' is one the scientists
chose carefully to illustrate what they understand to be the position and when
I say to people that Government Ministers keep denying it they just laugh and
ask where else the devices have come from.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pringle looks to golf to get out of rough A combination of a hot summer and consumers blowing cold has left knitwear manufacturer Dawson International seriously overstretched, says Margaret Vaughan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE laying on of Dr Finlay's healing hands held out hope of a swift recovery
for the ailing Dawson International. The Edinburgh-based textiles group had
fallen victim to the bad medicine of befuddled expansion.
The haemorrhage led to losses of nearly #100m. The company doctor, Mr Derek
Finlay, brought in earlier this year, prescribed a purge of the boardroom and
the loss of 500 jobs.
Yesterday, however, those early hopes of a fast recovery were shaken by the
announcement from the new management, who took over in March, that half-year
profits were down 43%.
The new chairman blamed poor sales on the warmest summer since 1659 and shaky
consumer confidence. Figures for the six months to September show pre-tax
profits have slumped to #9m with sales down to #169m.
While not exactly shaking his head over the patient's chances of a good
recovery, the company doctor is warning that profits for the second half of the
financial year are likely to be even worse. He holds out little hope of a
sustained recovery until the next financial year.
The patient, meanwhile, is being packed off for recuperative purposes to its
old home in Kinross. The decision by Dawson to flit from its prestigious
headquarters in the heart of Edinburgh's financial centre back to its Todd and
Duncan plant across the Firth of Forth is perhaps symbolic of its retrenchment
since Mr Finlay, 63, a former Heinz executive, took over as chairman following
the disastrous results announced earlier this year.
The company is now returning to its core business, the most important of which
is Pringle, the prestige knitwear business endorsed by golfer Nick Faldo. It is
Dawson's key brand.
Things began to go dramatically wrong at Pringle in the final six months of
last year. Sales were plummeting and the company was losing money on its
retailing side and in the US.
The company had diversified internationally into shops, and tried to use the
cachet of the brand name to expand into products such as jewellery and perfume.
Finlay believed that the rapid expansion was a bridge too far and that the
management had lost touch with its core business and become befuddled by the
huge range of products.
Drastic action and no little controversy followed the boardroom coup which was
incited by leading shareholders who had lost confidence in the management.
Almost immediately after taking over the chairmanship Finlay was forced to
defend compensation payments of #2.2m made to ousted directors.
He insisted the company had no choice but to pay off the managers whose
contracts were terminated after the heavy losses in the year to March 1994.
While 500 employees lost their jobs, on minimum redundancy terms, it was
revealed in the annual report that the chief executive of Dawson's US
shower-curtain business, Philip Kemp, was to get a payout of #1.36m. The US
business had lost #20m in the two years before it was finally sold in May this
year.
The ousted chairman, Sir Ronald Millar, ended his 13-year reign by collecting
#378,000. He also got a full year's salary of #188,000 plus pension
contributions of #32,000.
The group's managing director, Nick Kuenssberg, received #308,000 in
compensation and a year's salary worth #150,000. It was he who had presided
over the ill-judged expansion into retail shops.
A final sum of #117,000 went to the finance director, John Embrey, who also got
to draw his #62,000 basic salary until his formal retirement in July.
Further criticism followed when it was disclosed that Dawson had let its former
executives hang on to their share options, which normally lapse when an
employee leaves the company. Sir Ronald and Mr Kuenssberg had over 400,000
share options between them.
Critics saw the payoffs as a rich reward for failure. But Mr Finlay insisted
that by acting quickly and avoiding lengthy and expensive court proceedings the
new board was free to concentrate on the fundamental and strategic issues
needed to help the company recover.
Dawson's key problems had centred on its American adventure where several of
its acquisitions performed poorly. Then the sales increases expected from
opening a number of high-profile Pringle shops never happened.
The new board decided on a back-to-basics policy. The US shower-curtain
business was sold in April for $42m. Ten manufacturing plants in the US closed,
six of them sold. The UK weaving business, Premier Fabrics, went the same way.
Now the company is refocusing on the Pringle brand of golf wear.
There are still problems. The company faces higher wool and cashmere prices and
it is struggling to pass the rises on to the price of an already expensive
sweater. The raw material costs for wool, cotton, and cashmere from China rose
by as much as 40%, although there are hopes that prices might begin to fall.
The retrenchment means that Dawson now is little different from the group of
top quality Scottish knitwear and woollen companies it was in 1982. Dawson
began moving into the US in 1984, buying J.E.Morgan, an established maker of
thermal underwear. It added other businesses, moving into fleece, shower
curtains, and T-shirts.
Until 1990, profits from the US operation rose while those of the UK knitwear
and woollens businesses fell, hit by fashion changes and difficulties in
getting supplies of high-value cashmere from China.
Then changes in the US retail scene followed, which the Dawson subsidiaries
were not big enough to cope with.
The company is now busy dismantling Pringle's retail arm. By last month the
four UK stores had been vacated, five out of nine in Germany are now franchises
and a further two were closed down. The company has kept its in-shop presence
in prestigious stores such as Harrods and The Scotch House.
The new regime wants to focus on the golf and sports and leisurewear. It wants
to reposition Pringle, too, in the American market where golf is big business.
Whenever Faldo crosses a green in his Pringle sweater, there will be an
identical woolly on sale in the club shop.
Can the good doctor, then, put Dawson International back on its feet? The
analysts think so, pointing out that the balance sheet is sound and believing
that the medicine already administered will eventually do its job. There is
nothing though that Mr Finlay can do about the weather. Unless he calls in a
rain doctor.
</TEXT>
