<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>This is no way to run a railway  In the interests of the rail user, Lawrence Kemp warns against the twin-track approach to rail privatisation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lawrence Kemp</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the annual report of the Rail Users' Consultative Committee for Scotland
published yesterday, I say that the one-shop, one-customer division of
Railtrack and ScotRail is not the best way to serve rail passengers.
Let's be clear what's being talked about here: it is not about whether
privatisation is good or bad for the rail industry, that's a separate issue
about ownership; what the report deals with is how you organise yourself to
deliver the service to your customers. I'm saying creating an artificial split
between the people who provide the tracks and signals and the people who run
the trains is not the best way to deliver the service.
Think about what the railways are trying to do - to deliver not only a
satisfactory but improving standard of service to customers.
How would any modern Scottish business go about this? I would suggest its
management would work closely together in one location, building on the
strengths of each member of the team to evolve and implement a flexible plan
with clear, agreed objectives which could be changed quickly in response to
market conditions.
What they would not do is to set up two separate teams in different locations
communicating with each other through a series of complex, contractual
relationships and where the objective of one of the teams is to make a profit
out of the services it supplies to the other. In this sort of relationship the
customer is lost sight of.
Part of the reason for reorganising British Rail was to introduce
competition into the provision of rail services because competition would lead
to better service to passengers. But Railtrack has no competition in supplying
services to ScotRail. It is a monopoly and in the same way, except for the
parts of the network used by the InterCity companies, ScotRail is the only user
of Railtrack's services - another monopoly.
CLEARLY, where you have separate businesses doing what one did before, that
there are tangible increases in costs, eg, more people, premises, communication
costs, which is bad news for the taxpayer because these increased costs are met
through an increase in subsidy to run the railways. For the customers as users,
rather than taxpayers, it's the intangibles that affect the service they get,
the slowing down of decisions due to the separation of organisations, indeed
the lack of decisions due to differing objectives, the arguments over whose
responsibility it is when things go wrong - this is not good for customer
service.
It is difficult to put the situation in financial terms but look at it this
way: Railtrack is to be a business that makes a profit from mainly one
customer, ScotRail. Say ScotRail pays Railtrack #200m a year for use of track,
signalling, stations etc, Railtrack has to make a profit to satisfy its
shareholders - how much, #5m, #10m, #15m? That profit will come in part, if not
in whole, from ScotRail.
Isn't it better to have a situation where the money stays in the business where
ScotRail and Railtrack are reunited again and the best decision is taken for
the business as a whole, ie, the rail business, not the track and signalling
business or the train operating business?
Railways are a complex system made up of a whole series of sub-systems working
in synchronisation like a clock - if you want a clock to keep time you don't
take it apart and hope all the parts work on their own; you put them together,
wind it up, and away it goes. It's the same with railways: put the parts
together, wind them up by the application of some necessary finance, and away
they go.
Against Government and British Railways Board policy based on separation of
infrastructure and trains, I am up against it, but I draw comfort from the fact
that I am not alone. One of the stars in the Scottish railway firmament in
recent years - Chris Green - also firmly believed that ScotRail and Railtrack
should be reunited.
n Lawrence Kemp is past acting chairman of the Rail Users' Consultative
Committee for Scotland.
</TEXT>
