<DOCNO>GH951117-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Privatisation goes ahead despite forecasts of worrying consequences of Scottish break-up Rail users' warning will be ignored</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's relentless drive towards rail privatisation in Scotland will
continue, regardless of yesterday's blunt warning from the main passenger
watchdog body that the break-up is not working and is damaging.
Senior Scottish Office officials signalled there will be no change of heart,
because splitting the network between ScotRail and Railtrack was ``central'' to
the privatisation programme.
However, the Rail Users' Consultative Committee for Scotland said the split was
diverting money, time, and effort away from improving services.
It wants ScotRail and Railtrack re-united. Since the break-up, passengers have
not been well served, while a distinct lack of investment in infrastructure -
from trains to lines and signalling - was of concern.
Mr Lawrence Kemp, past chairman of the committee, declared it was time to
``stop playing shops'' when Railtrack only had one major customer, ScotRail.
His annual report, lodged with Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, makes
embarrassing reading for the Government. It was also seized by opponents of the
privatisation programme.
Mr Kemp wrote: ``Basically, what we have in Scotland is one shop - Railtrack,
with one customer - ScotRail, and the possibility of a few crumbs from the
InterCity companies - not a sensible arrangement.
``Having two separate organisations to do what one did before, and did well,
diverts money, time, and effort away from delivering an improved service to
passengers into providing people, offices, and equipment to do the same job
less well because each organisation has different objectives.''
He insisted that was not a condemnation of privatisation but a criticism of
railway organisation, although he was adamant that:
q There was still no evidence of a coherent, long-term plan to invest in and
develop Scotland's railways;
q It was ``deplorable'' that, for the past 12 months, no new rolling stock had
been provided for Scottish services;
q Railtrack's significant infrastructure problems had resulted in a
deterioration in services, and:
q Rising consumer complaints about staff were due partly to lack of investment.
Mr Kemp, backed by new chairwoman Helen Millar, said the BR break-up might be
appropriate in England but Scotland would be better served if ScotRail and
Railtrack were one.
Mr Kemp said the Government should recognise BR was no longer a national
network, and should set up a Scottish Transport Authority to develop and
implement an innovative transport policy for Scotland.
Labour's Shadow Transport Minister Brian Wilson said of the latest critical
litany: ``If this is the view of a committee that includes several political
supporters of the Government, then what is the rest of the country expected to
think?
``Fragmentation of the railways leads to nothing but confusion, bureaucracy,
and additional cost.''
Liberal Democrat MP Charles Kennedy said the report was a damning commentary on
the shambles of rail privatisation. It had homed in on the key failing: ``The
original, fateful decision to split ownership and control of track and train
operators.''
SNP transport spokesman Andrew Welsh said the Government should heed warnings
in the report and challenged Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch to
reverse the privatisation process, bearing in mind his commitment to an
adequate transport structure to fully exploit business opportunities.
In its report, the committee, whose prime purpose is to protect rail users,
questioned why no new rolling stock had been provided in the past year - in
contrast with Government support for Caledonian MacBrayne, which had received
new ships and was not being privatised.
One explanation was the reorganisation of local government, causing uncertainty
over funding to lease trains, according to Mr Kemp.
However, even when doubts were resolved, builders were not in a position to
proceed with orders: ``It is unforgivable that, when money is available . . .
bureaucracy has conspired against providing a better quality of service to the
rail passenger in Scotland.''
Mr Kemp also warned the phrase ``disproportionately uneconomic'' - used to
justify the withdrawal of Fort William sleepers - may be heard more frequently
in future as an excuse to cut services.
His report argued it was not too late to consider a vertically integrated
railway in Scotland, the ``only way to provide a service''.
Mrs Millar, who said the current system was not working, confirmed some
arguments had already been put in person to the Scottish Secretary. He can also
expected to be pressed soon on the withdrawal of a CalMac ferry which gives the
Skye Bridge a monopoly on travel to the island.
A Scottish Office spokesman said the decision to split infrastructure from
train services was carefully considered when the Government drew up its plans,
adding that Ministers would be interested to see detailed proposals for a
Scottish Transport Authority.
ScotRail said the call to re-unite with Railtrack was for politicians to sort
out. Railtrack also declined to comment on the issue.
q Railtrack confirmed last night that Scotland no longer has rail-borne,
emergency-response cranes. The nearest is on Teeside. Railtrack insisted that
road cranes, hired in Scotland, would suffice, following a survey of needs.
Perspective.....................................17
