<HEADLINE>Second thoughts by rector</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTH Lanarkshire Council yesterday found itself with more problems when the
successful candidate for a top education post changed her mind.
Miss Rosemary McDonald, rector of a Catholic high school in Wishaw, has turned
her back on the job of head of the quality department in the council's
department of education.
The council is already reeling from a Scottish Office decision to hold a
``jobs-for-the-boys'' inquiry following complaints about top-level appointments.
The council expected Miss McDonald to hand in her resignation to Strathclyde
region late last week but she has decided to stay on as rector of St Aidan's.
Last night, North Lanarkshire chief executive Andrew Cowe said: ``We offered
her the post, which is at depute director level. We expected to hear that she
had handed in her resignation to the region late last week. But this was not
so. It has come as a bit of a surprise to me.''
A spokesman for Strathclyde region welcomed Miss McDonald's decision to remain
at St Aidan's, where she has been rector for 11 years. She was one of the first
women in the region to take charge of a mixed high school and, under her
guidance, St Aidan's got top marks from the region's quality assurance unit
recently.
</TEXT>
