<HEADLINE>Loch Lomond regulations</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RECENT correspondence about Loch Lomond requests that a response is made by the
waterskiing fraternity (October 31).
Might we express at the outset our sincere condolences to the family of the
person killed as a result of the recent accident at Loch Lomond?
We do not know the facts of this case and therefore consider it inappropriate
for us or anyone else at this stage to comment on this, particularly pending,
no doubt, a Fatal Accident Inquiry.
Without facts it is inappropriate also to judge whether any of the proposed
by-laws would have prevented the accident and thus it is unfair to level
criticism at the Scottish Sports Council.
Our association has from the outset supported the bulk of the regulations, as
have the Sports Council on behalf of the various sports involved. We feel that
the Sports Council would reject the contention that waterskiers in general have
wielded an excessive influence on the actions of the council.
We continue to hold ourselves ready to discuss all issues relative to Loch
Lomond with the park authority, the Sports Council, or other interested parties.
We sincerely hope that the regulations, when brought in, will be fair to all
the users of the loch and those who reside there.
Duncan Hope,
Chairman, Scottish Water Ski Association,
Town Loch, Townhill,
Dunfermline.
</TEXT>
