<DOCNO>GH951117-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shinty association denies referee's vendetta claims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHINTY referee claims he has been victimised by the Camanachd Association and
is no longer selected to preside over matches as a result of criminal assault
proceedings he took against a player.
Grade one official Donald MacFadyen was struck in the face by Lovat centre
Roddy Munro with a caman during a game last February. Munro was fined #350 by
Inverness Sheriff Court for his actions.
``I'm out in the cold. I haven't refereed a game since this incident
happened,'' said Mr MacFadyen.
``The Camanachd Association won't admit it but I've been suspended. There is no
other word for it.''
Mr MacFadyen received a grazed lip when Munro attacked after being sent off for
foul language during a Lovat versus Fort William match. When the procurator
fiscal became involved, Mr MacFadyen pulled out of officiating at a MacAulay
Cup quarter final match on his lawyer's recommendation.
``The upshot is, I haven't been asked to referee a game since.
``The trial added to the ill-feeling and there is definitely a vendetta. But I
feel I had no option but to go to court. It was the only avenue left to clear
my name.''
Mr MacFadyen described allegations of malice laid against him in court as ``a
lot of dirt''.
``I would like an apology from the Camanachd Association in light of the court
decision and I want to be reinstated as a referee.''
Camanachd Association president Duncan Cameron said Mr MacFadyen's exclusion
was justified because he had declined to referee the MacAulay Cup quarter-final.
Mr Cameron said: ``We do not feel it is right for referees to think they can
pick and choose.
``Referees pull out of games for family reasons and such like but Donald
MacFadyen withdrew because he didn't like our disciplinary decision over
Roderick Munro. He felt the nine-match ban was too lenient.''
Mr Cameron also noted that Mr MacFadyen had later refereed a match in the
Sutherland Cup involving the Fort William side.
``If legal considerations were to the fore, he should have had no complaints
about getting withdrawn from that one.''
Mr MacFadyen's future selection is now a matter for the Camanachd Association,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
