<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Benedict Brogan reports how the pay dispute at Ford's Dagenham plant could have major repercussions throughout the country, striking a serious blow against the Government's low-inflation policies Spanner in the works</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Benedict Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES, employers, and politicians around the country must be asking
themselves what the good people manning the assembly lines at Ford's Dagenham
plant are up to. Despite a dramatic fall in inflation, workers producing the
new Fiesta walked out yesterday in protest at a final pay offer that would give
them, over two years, a 9.25% increase in wages.
Ford management described the offer as the best in the industry and a
recognition that Ford UK's productivity was substantially higher than its
German branch, but union leaders refused to be impressed by the largesse, and
are holding out for a two-hour cut in the working week, on top of a settlement
worth an average #28 extra a week. On paper, the offer is generous: it would
give Ford workers a 4.75% increase this year, followed by a 4.5% increase next
year - or inflation plus 0.5%, whichever is greater, as well as enhanced
pension entitlements.
Despite Ford's insistence that the offer was final, union negotiators rejected
it and will recommend a strike ballot if necessary. Yesterday several hundred
workers on the paint and trim section of the Dagenham line downed tools to
underline the point. It cost them a day's pay, and Ford lost the production of
800 cars. But for the rest of the automotive and manufacturing industry, which
traditionally follows Ford's lead in these matters, the price could be much
higher.
Reaction to the news at Westminster was mixed. For politicians the conjunction
of industrial militancy and continuing low inflation raises a number of
possibilities. With Ford's 22,000 workers due to ballot on the offer, and other
manufacturers - in particular Vauxhall, whose workers are expected to reject a
3.5% offer - watching closely, a return to the days when high inflation was
driven on by unrestrained demands is bad for both Labour and the Government.
For the Chancellor and his colleagues at the Treasury the Ford dispute is a
worry. The management's willingness to offer a settlement well ahead of
inflationary trends will be unwelcome. Despite 16 years of Tory insistence that
pay negotiations were a matter best left to employer and employee, the
Government will look askance at anything that suggests management willingness
to ignore the downward pressure on wages extracted at such an economic price by
two recessions.
The Government is desperate to cut interest rates both to revive economic
growth and to gain what little political benefit would accrue from such a move.
To do that it needs proof of continuing low inflation to counter the pressure
for higher rates coming from the Bank of England. Yesterday's unexpectedly low
figures have provided such an opportunity, and the Chancellor is expected to
act before Christmas to move rates down.
But Kenneth Clarke's relief at seeing yesterday's inflation figures
emphatically reverse months of rising prices - headline inflation fell 0.5% to
3.2%, and the vital underlying rate dropped back below the crucial 3% level to
2.9% - will be tempered by the breakdown of talks at Ford.
Higher-than-inflation wage demands, in the face of stagnating productivity and
steeply rising UK unit labour costs, is not what low-inflation Britain needs.
On Wednesday the Prime Minister welcomed the new legislative year by
proclaiming that the Tories' commitment to low inflation had created the most
stable platform for growth for generations. The Government believes that inward
investment, like the 3300-job Chunghwa plant at Mossend, only comes when
foreign companies feel confident about Britain's long-term future as a
low-inflation country with a flexible workforce. Strike action to reject a
9.25% pay offer, Ministers fear, is not something that goes down well on the
international markets.
For Labour, the Ford stand-off is equally worrying. Tony Blair has repositioned
his party to the economic centre-right. Inflation is out and unreasonable pay
expectations with it. And he has moved to distance the party from its
traditional links with the trade unions. The image of a Labour government
conspiring to fix wages with union bosses over beer and sandwiches in Downing
Street was one of the most damaging identified by Labour reformers struggling
to transform the party.
So to hear the Transport and General Workers' Union official leading the
negotiations warning that 9.25% did not meet the aspirations of the workforce
must have come as an unwelcome reminder that despite Blair's best efforts, a
number of distinctly unmodern forces lie beneath the surface of New Labour. The
Tories have made ``Labour is not fit to govern'' a campaign theme, and will
lose no opportunity to remind voters that Labour in office will face demands
from trade unions for a much looser approach to inflation.
Yesterday Labour sources were resolutely avoiding commenting on the Ford talks,
echoing the Government line that the issue is one for the unions and
management. Their reluctance to express a view on the merits of the trade union
case is a natural product of New Labour's attempts to redefine itself as an
observer of, rather than a participant in, industrial relations.
The only ones yesterday who were cheering the prospects of large-scale
industrial action and ``inflation-breaking'' pay settlements were Tory back
benchers. Desperate for any stick with which to beat Labour, they were rubbing
their hands with glee at the thought of Labour's discomfiture.
With less than a fortnight before the Budget, Kenneth Clarke does not want
anything to disturb the low-inflation platform on which he is expected to base
the tax cuts that he hopes will save the next election for the Tories. Wage and
workforce flexibility are now too ingrained in the British economy for
industrial strife to reappear suddenly. But politically the crisis at Ford
could be a turning point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Threat to St Andrews Plundering the Old Course</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLF, more so in Scotland than anywhere else on the globe, has always been a
game of the people, the most egalitarian of sports. But the pilgrims who would
worship at the shrine of golf's birthplace, St Andrews, and touch the holy
grail of its turf, are in danger of poisoning the chalice for the locals. They
believe a #5m deal with a company specialising in corporate hospitality may
threaten their livelihood, and their birthright as residents to play the
world's most famous course. Honourable men defend the action as the only way to
protect the hallowed links from rampant commercialism, and competition from
planned new courses in the area.
The Old Course is just the latest icon to be plundered by commercialism.
Perhaps we should be reconciled. Golfers have been softened up for this day.
Only addicts who can afford satellite TV can now watch many events, notably the
Ryder Cup and Scottish Open. Rugby supporters levered into purchasing
debentures in order to continue watching their national team, then forced to
watch, impotent, as professionalism, fuelled by satellite TV money,
crash-tackles its way through the ethos that has protected their game, will nod
in knowing sympathy.
Fat cats who can afford #250 per summer round are the only patrons now of
Turnberry. Residence at the Ayrshire hotel is now a prerequisite of teeing off,
as it also is at Gleneagles, which next summer will cost #195 per round. These
are not prices tailored to the pocket of the ordinary man. Yet it is not so
long ago that fathers would take sons to play such courses, or groups of young
men would enjoy a day's golf as an occasional treat which would not require a
second mortgage. No more. At least St Andrews has attempted to maintain green
fees at more modest levels. But the pressure which the new deal exerts on
tee-off times means most of next summer is already fully booked, with
repercussions, it is argued, potentially damaging to tourism there as well as
elsewhere in Scotland. Golf may live to lament hoisting their game on the hook
of commercialism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BRIAN WILSON A voice is stilled as Murdoch wields the axe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWENTY-three years ago, in the first issue of the West Highland Free Press, I
wrote an editorial which contained the following sentiment: ``I do not believe
that newspapers are just another business and I do not accept the right of rich
and powerful men to buy up, close down, merge and centralise as if they were
dealing with unit trusts or soap powder.''
Last night, I had reason to reflect again upon these words when news came
through of Rupert Murdoch's decision to close the newspaper Today, which
currently has a circulation of more than 600,000. A soap-powder factory, and
the jobs which went with it, could not have been more peremptorily wiped out.
As widely recognised by its peers, Today was a very good newspaper since
Murdoch took the strategic decision that it should adopt a Labour-supporting
editorial line. The former Daily Mirror editor, Roger Stott, brought in some
first-class people who still remembered what campaigning journalism is about.
Naturally, I'm disappointed to lose one of the very few Labour-supporting
papers, in a national press which - no matter how disillusioned it may be with
the current shower - remains overwhelmingly Tory in its ownership and
instincts. Though its circulation was relatively small, Today reached an
important young market.
But I can say with absolute honesty that it is not for reasons of narrow party
advantage that I deeply resent its passing. I doubt if the General Election's
outcome will hang on the fate of Today.
It is as a journalist who recognises a good product when I see one and who
cares for the diversity of our press that I despise how the dagger was wielded,
on the basis of a hard-nosed calculation that in a period of rising newsprint
costs, it makes more sense to maximise the Sun's print run than to continue
with Today.
This was a paper which understood the maxim that news is what someone doesn't
want you to print while all the rest is publicity. It uncovered good stories
and campaigned hard on them. While it did most of the things which modern
tabloids do, it also sustained a coherent editorial line on the side of social
justice.
I appreciate that most of the people reading this obituary will have had little
acquaintance with its subject. Despite having an excellent little team at
Kinning Park, its Scottish edition never broke the 40,000 mark and carried
virtually no distinctively Scottish advertising. But it still unearthed and
published a lot of good stuff.
If a newspaper, like the soap-powder factory, is hopelessly uneconomic then it
cannot be protected for ever. But I find it very hard to believe that a paper
which 600,000 people buy each day fits that description. And I also believe
that the 600,000 people who bought it have rights which should not be
disregarded so casually.
It would be over-egging the pudding to describe Today as ``a newspaper of the
left''. Its origins lay in Eddie Shah's union-busting venture in Warrington and
it arrived in its more recent form only via a pretty nondescript initial period
under Murdoch's ownership. The reality is that it was lent a Labour-supporting,
campaigning identity by Murdoch for reasons which were founded in commerce
rather than belief. And what the press baron giveth, the press baron taketh
away.
That is a power which has to be challenged. In this case, Murdoch has not only
decided to get rid of Today. He has also used his power of ownership to ensure
that nobody will be allowed to pick up the pieces. That is a deeply
anti-competitive action and, in any society which cared about such matters,
would not be his prerogative.
The Tories never pretended to implement any safeguards on monopoly and
competition where Murdoch was concerned. The crude deal was his political
support in return for the right to buy up as much as he liked.
I doubt very much if Mr Ian Lang, our supposed protector against
anti-competitive practices, will now be shedding many tears for the death of
Today. And it will be very interesting to see whether he stirs himself if
Murdoch now turns towards the Express.
But I come back to the point that 600,000 newspaper buyers do have rights.
Similarly, in the early 1960s, the Labour-supporting Daily Herald's market of
more than 1,000,000 each day should have had rights. In that case, it was the
dearth of advertising which made the paper uneconomic. In this case, it is the
commercial priorities of a hard-nosed proprietor.
The diversity of the press in a democratic society should not rest upon such
uncertain foundations. If a market is shown to exist, then there should be
mechanisms - such as newsprint subsidies and pooling a proportion of
advertising revenue - which allow them to survive. Other more enlightened
countries have taken such steps.
The press exercises far too much influence within any society to be left
entirely to unregulated market forces. Why should there be anything remarkable
about that assertion, when it is taken for granted that all aspects of
broadcasting are regulated in the interests of balance and, indeed, truth.
I would be delighted if there were more newspapers representing all shades of
opinion. The more the merrier. But it is everything to the left of centre which
is most likely to suffer if money is essentially the only determinant of who
controls the press. Labour, in office, should not forget that reality.
</TEXT>
