<HEADLINE>Triumph in tragedy CAROL CLEWLOW gives a sneak preview of a Mayfest-bound play set in a holiday town with a difference</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROL CLEWLOW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMONG the holiday habits which all but disappeared with the advent of the
package tour, was that of going to the same place year in year out. Anyone
wanting to date a film or play in the first five minutes, has only to show Mr
and Mrs Middle-Class Britain being greeted like long-lost relatives by some
seaside landlady to tell us we are in the fifties.
For it was in the main a middle-class habit, and nothing still on the screen
encapsulates in the same way safe, solid old-fashioned bourgeois respectability
quite like it. Substitute Scarborough for the mythical Austrian spa town of
Badenheim and you have the essence of Badenheim 1939, the new piece by the
Second Stride theatre company.
Badenheim is a favourite holiday destination of assimilated middle-class Jews,
and there were many such Badenheims in Austria.
The production is based on the novel of the same name by Aharon Appelfeld. What
attracts the visitors to Badenheim, as he writes in his programme notes, is
``music festivals, apple strudel, poetry readings and mild flirtations''.
For these simple pleasures they come year after year. Except, of course, that
1939 will not be like any other year. For by now Austria has been annexed by
Germany and anti-Semitism is spreading like a disease.
By now the sinister Sanitation Department is already in evidence, requiring
people to register, barbed-wire barriers are appearing at the end of the town.
By now strange posters are offering holidays in Poland.
Soon the water will be turned off to the swimming pool, food supplies will
start failing. Hotel guests and staff will find that the mysterious Polish
holiday destination is the Warsaw Ghetto and thereafter towns forever shamed by
history like Treblinka.
Until such time as this happens though, the Jewish population of Badenheim
determines to ignore the signs, to dance and flirt and drink its coffee.
Appelfeld himself describes Badenheim 1939 as ``a story of self-deception, of
sweet illusions and insane optimism . . .'' The words make clear the difficult
nature of the task facing Second Stride; how to deal with the notion that it
was such ``sweet illusions'' and ``insane optimism'' that led the Jews of
Badenheim to collude in their own fate.
Second Stride has a multi-disciplinary approach. They use music, song, and
dance as well as dialogue. What attracted them to Badenheim 1939 is that the
core of the place and the piece itself is the town's music festival.
But to allow them to present the piece in a straightforward fashion where we
become an audience as well to the festival's determined merriment would indeed
be a collusion. Our tragedy is that we know the end of the story.
It is to prevent this that he has deliberately ironed out the superficial
gaiety. The waltzing, for instance, is heavily stylised, a danse macabre
accompanied by Orlando Gough's deliberately sombre unjoyful music. The problem
is that somehow this will not do.
For being so concerned about colluding in this unholy fashion in Badenheim's
determined blindness, means we are never allowed to get any sort of sense of
the simple joie de vivre which, while it is the town's tragedy, is also, in
some sense, its triumph.
For while it is this honest-to-God gaiety which the Holocaust turned against
itself and into a death sentence, none the less we need a sense of what gave it
its life-enhancing quality; since the normal unities of tragedy and catharsis
do not operate with the Holocaust, the sheer joy in the chocolate and the cream
cake may be one of the few things we have left to hold on to.
Much the same difficulty attends the portrayal of the encroaching horrors which
the Jews determinedly do not see.
In the novel Appelfeld has an ingenious solution to the problem.
Such things as the appearance of the barbed-wire barriers and bodies being
buried at night by pastry cooks, become one-liners, hidden away in the text
between the more important business of dancing and the flirting, in the same
way that the Badenheimers hide them away in the backs of their minds.
Finding an equivalent answer on the stage, according to Spinks, proved
difficult.
Attempts to present these two particular incidents on stage to show the nature
of what was being ignored proved unsuccessful. So dark and utterly unignorable
were they, so fatally did they over-shadow the piece and undermine the sense of
self-deception which is its raison d'tre, that they had to be removed.
The problem is that without such things there is no back-drop to the
self-deception. It is vital that we get a sense of the evil outside the walls
which is so steadily approaching. We could, of course, get it from the
unfolding personal tragedies of the characters. Unfortunately, all too often
this is lost because of Second Stride's complex performing style.
In simple terms, so much is going on up there on the stage that too often we
lose the vital pointers to the tragedies which are unfolding.
The comparison with annual holidaymakers in Scarborough is not an idle one.
It's worth trying to imagine what it might have been like had it happened
there. In doing so we get somewhere near what the mind-set of the average
Badenheimer might be like, why the insane optimism triumphed, the sweet
illusion and the self-deception.
These people, as Appelfeld says in his notes, knew themselves to be ``loyal
Austrian citizens''. They thought of themselves as Austrian first. Many did not
even think of themselves as Jews so much had they inter-married.
They were middle-class bourgeoisie, the back-bone of any country.
They belonged to a country where culture, dance, poetry, even coffee and cakes
were the stuff of life, not being a Jew.
So assimilated were they that it had reached beyond what we understand to be
the bounds of the word. They didn't believe in the horror that was coming
because they couldn't believe it.
Ian Spinks has said: ``This isn't Schindler's List.'' It isn't and neither
should it be. It's a different piece altogether.
n Badenheim 1939 is at Bury St Edmunds and Sheffield this month and will be at
Glasgow Mayfest next year.
</TEXT>
