<HEADLINE>Giant bid to pump up the volumes Esso's pledge to drop petrol costs has fuelled a price war across Scotland. JANE SCOTT explains why small retailers fear closure in the eye of the tiger's campaign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE'S a rattling of bones and a waving of shrouds in the petrol stations of
Scotland this autumn, and the keening is loudest on the 10 or so forecourts
lining the A8 leading west out of Edinburgh.
These have been engaged for the past three months in a vicious price war which
has seen unleaded fuel, to take just one marker, drop to the point where it is
being sold at a loss.
If it carries on - and petrol stations throughout the whole central belt are
now nudging their prices down to meet the crucial break-even mark of around 46p
a litre - insiders say the industry will be damaged beyond repair, with smaller
retailers forced out of business and some oil companies possibly pulling out of
the UK altogether.
Scotland has traditionally suffered unfairly high prices, generally explained
by the cost of getting petrol to outlying stations, and the doomsday scenario
is that a decreasing number of forecourts in business will allow the major
petrol companies to carve up the country between them, sending prices even
higher.
And the main culprit will be Esso. Three months ago, on August 21, Esso
launched its Price Watch campaign in two parts of the UK, pledging to set
petrol prices that were ``among the lowest'' in the central-belt trial area,
and to match the lowest prices in the second trial area in the North-east of
England.
It was the cue for instant industry dismay. Esso, the leader of the petrol
company pack, had traditionally sold its petrol dearer than the cut-price
operators, preferring to concentrate on service and quality.
That, however, was before the supermarkets drove a discount petrol tanker
through the forecourts of Britain, taking some 20% of the market within the
past 10 years. Supermarkets love discounting petrol; it means more customers
will visit their stores, while all the forecourts could traditionally offer in
competition was a few shelves of puzzle magazines and peanut butter cookies.
Belatedly, some commentators have suggested, Esso realised that it needed to
safeguard its own market share, which had fallen from one-fifth to one-sixth.
Hence Price Watch, and a mad scramble in Scotland to keep pace. Day by day
during the summer, motorists rejoiced as the petrol forecourts of The Gyle beat
each other down, penny by penny, from an average of 54p a litre for unleaded,
until Gulf set what currently seems to be the bottom line, with petrol at just
under 45p.
Danny Roden, Gulf's director of retail and distributive services, says: ``While
we are actually quite big in the central belt of Scotland, we are fairly small
in UK terms, with only 4% market share, so we are a minnow compared with the
likes of Esso. The big difficulty is that this is an aggressive programme by
them. They have said it is to protect market share, but it will inevitably lead
to a considerable number of sites having to shut up because they are
non-viable.''
Shell, with a sixth of the UK market, is bullish about the price war,
suggesting that it was the current revamp of Shell stations and introduction of
advanced fuels and a popular loyalty scheme which forced Esso's hand. It is,
however, currently weathering the second round of customer boycotts this year -
the Brent Spar protests, over the proposed ditching of the oil platform at sea,
had little effect on forecourt sales, say industry insiders.
Spokesman Andrew Vickers says it is too early to predict the effect of protests
over Shell's investment in Nigeria, where the execution of nine environmental
activists, including writer Ken Saro-Wiwa, has attracted worldwide
condemnation. This week protesters picketed a station in Edinburgh.
Shell's projects, including its #2700m liquefied natural gas plant for Nigeria,
are long term, and often outlast governments, Vickers says. ``The effect of a
Shell pull-out . . . would be far worse for the environment of the Nigerian
Delta and far worse for the Nigerian people.''
Commentators say Esso can never hope to regain the ground lost to the
supermarkets and must be planning to reassert its superiority at the expense of
smaller petrol companies and independent retailers, who cannot afford to offer
petrol at cost price for long. Companies throughout the UK are dreading the
expected announcement that Esso will roll out its Price Watch campaign
nationwide.
But petrol companies are not only hoping to attract the motorist through
aggressive pricing. They also need to hold on to the independent petrol
forecourt owners who have contracted to sell their brand of fuel.
Shell says independents are queueing up to adopt the brand, in spite of this
year's bad publicity: ``Allegations made against the company were false and
misleading, and I think people are aware of that,'' said spokesman Andrew
Vickers.
To the consternation of the industry, Esso says it has no defined budget for
the programme. Spokesman Tom MacQuillan described it as ``a long-term review of
our business'' with Price Watch continuing ``until we have got conclusive
results''.
He recognises that smaller operators may be driven out of business. ``More than
1000 sites closed last year. That's not something that we would like to see,
nor is it something we have set out to do. We are simply testing the
circumstances in the market, to improve our own business security.
``We have not set out to create a price war. We have said we will match and be
among the lowest in the two areas.''
MacQuillan denies prices will rise after Price Watch: ``I think price is now
the main driver for the consumer and I think price will stay as the main driver
for the consumer.''
</TEXT>
