<HEADLINE>Watt Scots did for the car</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH the pioneers of car-building came from Germany and France, motoring
would not be the same without the inventions of a series of ingenious Scots.
The idea of harnessing early steam engines to some kind of vehicle produced
many weird and wonderful contraptions, but it was only in the 1760s, after
James Watt's almost complete redesign of the whole system, that
reliably-powered factories, railway locomotives and steam road carriages came
into being.
Watt's flash of inspiration about the separate condenser - only the first of
his many steam-engine patents - came to him in the homeliest possible way. As a
memorial stone in Glasgow Green recalls, he was having a stroll there one
Sunday in 1765, heading for the golf house, when the idea suddenly occurred to
him.
Steam coaches and carriages were, of course, heavy vehicles indeed. Fitted with
sturdy iron-shod wheels, they did not give drivers or passengers a comfortable
ride.
It was another Scotsman, R W Thomson of Stonehaven, who helped towards solving
that problem with the invention of the air-filled tyre. Thomson's original
tyres were based on what amounted to a collection of hollow leather sausages,
with the air at normal outside pressure.
The more sophisticated pneumatic tyre as we know it today was the invention of
a third Scotsman, John Boyd Dunlop. He created it first of all for cycle use.
All the vehicles at the Scottish Motor Show (ending on Sunday) run on petrol or
diesel fuel. It is the same story there. In the 1850s, Dr James Young
established the world petroleum industry. His oil was distilled first of all
from coal, and then from shale, and his fortune came not only from his own
operations in the Lothians, but also from royalties paid to him by the first US
oil companies, in the years before his master patent ran out.
The Scottish shale oil companies became part of BP, whose offices at
Grangemouth still display the brass plate of Young's Paraffin Light and Mineral
Oil Company.
Later in the nineteenth century, while many Scots worked with oil and gas
engines produced elsewhere, none of them made a fundamental contribution to
engine design until Sir Dugald Clerk produced an improved two-stroke type. For
several years, two-strokes were often referred to in the technical press as
Clerk engines.
For a time in the early 1990s, it seemed as if many of the major car
manufacturers were about to come out with modern production two-stroke engines
of the Australian Orbital type. Problems with long-term exhaust emissions have
closed down several of these projects, but it must be only a matter of time
before the lightweight two-stroke, with its minimal number of components, makes
a comeback.
The Scottish contribution to motoring, even if in some cases indirect, is
something to ponder about. Perhaps away from the show, over a flask of coffee.
Even then, there would be no escape. The vacuum flask was invented by Sir James
Dewar - born 1842, Kincardine-on-Forth.
</TEXT>
