<HEADLINE>Touched by the blarney Jack Webster examines the wonder of Wogan at first hand as the broadcasting phenomenon greets the Scottish contingent of his TOGs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack Webster</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975339599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TERRY Wogan comes breezing into the city-centre bookshop in Glasgow, the
punters' pal who plays the jolly jester and seems bewildered by the popularity
he generates without really trying. Well . . .
Our Terence knows what he is doing all right. His broadcasting skills have been
finely honed over quarter-of-a-century or more: the jolly jape, the pregnant
pause, the mock surprise, the disarming confessions of idiocy which are hard to
dislike, especially when delivered with the charm of the Irish blarney.
It irritates some. But there are two million others out there who like it
enough to tune in every morning, waking up to Wogan and finding that it puts
their day off to a good start.
To those unfamiliar with the format, Terry's chirpy chat is mainly in response
to letters from his listeners, a species who have come to be known as TOGs, an
acronym for Terry's Old Geezers (or Gals).
It is a chance for the great anonymous mass to exercise their wit at national
level, even if some of it would be hard pushed to reach the parish magazine.
So the TOGs are a nationwide club, who spread Terry's name across the land on
car stickers and feel a personal satisfaction at being part of the accompanying
fame.
If you are not attuned to that mental attitude it can sound like a load of old
drivel. For the committed TOGs, it becomes addictive.
So the books department of the BBC was on a commercial certainty when it
decided to bring out a volume of what those listeners say.
Terence has added his tuppence-worth and it was the publication of Terry
Wogan's Bumper Book of TOGs which brought him to Waterstone's bookshop to sign
copies as part of the BBC promotion.
To his credit, he mixes with the fans and engages in banter so similar to the
regular radio chats that there must be something completely natural in this
form of self-acknowledged nonsense. In a world so beset with problems and
obsessed with issues, real or imagined, I suppose it is a safety valve for
those who cannot take much more of it. Whatever the vanities, Terry and his
TOGs are harmless. And when they turned up at the bookshop it was surely as
much to speak to their breakfast-time hero as to buy a book which they had
virtually written themselves.
Without Wogan's own warmth to speak them, however, the words tend to come
across in the cold light of print as a pretty witless collection.
In fact I had reached the second half before I felt a smile coming on. These
were ``Thoughts for the day . . .'':
Beauty is in the eye of the beerholder.
There are three kinds of people - those who can count and those who can't.
Why is ``abbreviation'' such a long word?
Don't use a big word where a diminutive one will suffice.
But the TOGs will lap it up - just as they queued to meet the man himself. Not
only that. They brought him jars of jam and miniatures of whisky, at least one
of which was consumed as he signed their books.
And when it was all over, we repaired to the Central Hotel, approaching through
the Central Station, which drew gasps of Wogan admiration for the sheer
splendour of its Victorian architecture.
In the quiet of the hotel lounge, he was able to assess that the Glasgow
book-signing had been the best of the whole promotional tour, full of warmth
and good humour. One of his regulars, a lady called Frankie, had travelled
about 90 miles from north central Scotland for the occasion.
As we raked over his career, Terry recalled that, on his return from television
to morning wireless, he had helped raise the Radio Two audience to two million.
``With so many radio stations around nowadays, there is a limit to what you can
get,'' he was saying. ``You can't get back to the halcyon days of five or six
million.''
Terry is happy to have as many listeners as he has. But he also has serious
words of caution about the future of the BBC, an organisation for which he has
long held the greatest admiration.
He fears that Britain could end up with a radio structure like that of America
and believes that the people will have to make it known that they want the BBC
to be part of popular national broadcasting.
Otherwise, he says, the Government might take it away from them - and they
won't realise what they have lost until it is gone.
In answer to criticism of the licence fee, he points to the bleak alternative
where we could end up paying as much for a few high-profile television events
as for a whole year's licence.
Terry is certainly doing his bit for Radio Two's survival, along with people
like Jimmy Young, David Jacobs, John Dunn, Desmond Carrington, and his old
Glasgow sparring partner, Ken Bruce.
His own routine begins at 5.30am and the chauffeur gets him to Broadcasting
House in Portland Place by 7.15. He is on the air within 15 minutes and claims
that his morning patter is completely unrehearsed, the TOGs' letters even
unseen before the programme starts.
That morning drive begins some way to the west of London, where House of Wogan
looks across towards House of Windsor. Rumour has it that they wave to each
other occasionally. Clearly, Terry's Old Gals and Geezers cross all social
divides.
n Terry Wogan's Bumper Book of TOGs, from BBC Books at #7.99.
Terry's chirpy chat is mainly in response to letters from his listeners
</TEXT>
