<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Let's be bold, Ken</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ranald Noel-Paton, managing director of John Menzies</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WERE he to ask me for advice (so far no letter in the post) I would say: go for
it Ken, now is your chance to produce a Budget which will lift the High Street,
re-invigorate industry and commerce, raise consumer confidence and by the way,
start the process of winning the next General Election.
His first two Budgets were primarily concerned with bringing the PSBR back
under control, introducing (thinly-disguised) tax increases and calling for
tight public spending limits. He has been reasonably successful in spite of
diversions and alarms along the way. Much has been achieved, especially in the
control of inflation, and credit is due. But life is still very much like
wading through treacle.
The economy has slowed markedly, the pace of manufacturing (until recently
performing well) has turned sluggish, the housing market is still in the
doldrums, and both consumer and business confidence continues at a low ebb. The
Chancellor though is in a relatively strong position, in spite of present
uncertainties, and may even have brought Bank of England Governor Eddie George
into line in the matter of interest rate policy. It will not be easy but he now
has to provide a strong dose of adrenalin the economy needs. The fortunes of
the Government depend to a considerable degree on how successful he is. What
then is needed?
From a purely economic point of view , there is a good case to reject any talk
of income tax cuts, consolidate the position of the public finances, maintain a
cautious approach to interest rates, tweak fiscal policy to support investment
and generally keep her steady as she goes. Not good enough; and besides ``she''
is not going anywhere with anything like the necessary sense of purpose.
In general terms, the Chancellor's prime requirement is to restore business and
consumer confidence. The poor state of the housing market is probably the key
element in the national ``feel-bad factor'' and he should introduce measures to
get the market moving again, such as a prudent extension of MIRAS or a further
stamp-duty holiday to kick-start demand.
I believe he should also adopt an aggressive stance on interest rates. The
current slowdown in the economy must not be allowed to become a downturn. He
should use interest rate management as a regulator. The Governor of the Bank of
England has publicly acknowledged that there is no longer a case for high
interest rates and the Chancellor should accordingly reduce them.
Such a move would stimulate every part of the economy, would not necessarily
contradict fiscal prudence and would contribute vigorously to a resurgence of
consumer and business confidence, so vital to the country's economic and his
political needs.
Tax cuts are words on everybody's lips. The Chancellor should listen; he could
rearrange thresholds judiciously but, better, he should cut 1p off the basic
rate of income tax or possibly even 2p if Government spending is properly and
selectively curbed.
Capital gains tax should be restructured to favour longterm investment and
other incentives introduced to boost investment. He should review vigorously
every aspect of taxation policy and reform wherever necessary so as to create
as dynamic a balance as possible.
For instance, leave VAT alone and certainly do not countenance any extension;
reduce the tax on alcoholic beveridge (especially whisky where last year's hike
proved counterproductive to the Exchequer - a silly mistake), and at least we
will all feel jollier; go for a windfall tax on privatised utilities where it
has been suggested that #9Bn could be raised in total without affecting the
utilities' financial viability and use it to the national economic benefit;
adopt a limited reduction in advance corporation tax to encourage companies to
retain profits; fine tune and enhance investment related taxes to promote
investment and innovation; reduce the main rate of employers' national
insurance contributions as a stimulus to employment growth; make technical tax
changes to promote inward investment; and so on. In the space available one can
only make signals but the Chancellor must take this sort of route to stimulate
the economy and revive the national and commercial spirit.
To pay for it, he will have to ensure that there are achievable reductions in
public spending and much tighter controls thereafter. In spite of protestations
over the years from this Government we are still weighed down by shackles of
neo-welfare-statism. Action is required to reduce this burden. Finally, a
successfully stimulated economy will lift the Exchequer's tax revenue.
It is clearly essential that Ken Clarke must achieve this by delivering a bold
and imaginative Budget package of incentives and tax cuts combined with
Government spending curbs. Such a package would yield him the success which he
deserves and to which we are entitled.
</TEXT>
