<DOCNO>GH951117-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lloyd's reconstruction on course despite resignation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sudden resignation of the chief executive of Lloyd's of London disappointed
members of the world's biggest insurance market but they said yesterday that
the troubled insurer's renewal programme was still on course.
Peter Middleton unexpectedly announced his resignation on Wednesday night and
now joins US investment bank Salomon Brothers as chief executive of its
European operations.
Mr Middleton was held in high regard by Lloyd's Names who said he had been
sympathetic to their struggle to settle a compensation package after the market
plunged into losses and pushed many of the Names to the brink of bankruptcy.
``I am very depressed about the fact that he has resigned. I had really hoped
he would see it (the renewal programme) through to the end,'' said one Name.
The chief executive's departure came as a shock after Rosalind Gilmore, Lloyd's
director of regulatory services, resigned in September. Mr Middleton had been
instrumental in putting together the market's crucial Reconstruction and
Renewal Programme.
This includes Lloyd's Equitas reinsurance vehicle, which is intended to free
Names of the burden of past liabilities in return for a one-off payment.
Around half of Lloyd's 30,000 Names are involved in legal action to recoup some
of the record losses of some #8m sustained by the market since 1988 as a result
of a series of disasters and alleged poor management.
The market itself is currently making money but is bedevilled by past pollution
and asbestos-related claims from policies written decades ago.
Names said that they did not see Mr Middleton's loss as a significant blow to
the reconstruction programme. ``I would like to think the settlement will still
work,'' one said.
The chief executive's successor, director of special projects Ron Sandler, has
also been closely involved with the programme. Like his predecessor, Sandler
was welcomed by Names as an outsider to the market.
``The members greatly regret Peter Middleton's departure . . . but the R&amp;R
programme is much bigger than just one man,'' said Roger Pascall, executive
director of the Association of Lloyd's Members.
Mr Pascall said Mr Sandler was already well established at Lloyd's despite only
joining in May and had been seen as Middleton's obvious succcessor. ``He has
already shown himself to be clearly willing to focus on R&amp;R,'' he added.
Lloyd's too was keen to convey that everything is still on course, despite the
change of faces at the top. ``It is still business as usual. There has been no
change whatsoever,'' a Lloyd's spokesman said.
He added Mr Middleton had left simply because he received an attractive job
offer from elsewhere and dismissed some press reports that hinted at a rift
with Lloyd's chairman David Rowland.
``The ship sails on,'' the spokesman said. - Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
