<DOCNO>GH951117-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Finlay on upward slope Ski travel company set to benefit from Borders Enterprise programme</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By TONY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RODDY Finlay knows he should be looking harder at Scotland. As the managing
director of one of only two Scottish firms providing winter ski-chalet holidays
in Europe he is very aware that only 10% of the 1900 skiers he flew out to
France last season are Scots. Most of his customers, in fact, came from the
south of England.
``I suppose it is simple arithmetic,'' he says, sitting in his newly opened
company headquarters in a converted weaving shed in the Borders village of
Ancrum.
``There are 50 million down there and five million up here. We have never made
a big thing about being Scottish but with the high proportion of good skiers in
Scotland it is time for that to change and for us to take advantage of this
area of the market.''
From an experimental start in 1982 Finlay's Skiing has grown steadily to become
an operation with a turnover of more than #1m a year. It has just been chosen
by Scottish Borders Enterprise as one of 13 emergent firms in the region with
the potential to benefit from the LEC's ``Go For Growth'' development programme.
Finlay specialises in quality French chalet holidays in Courchevel and Val
d'Isere. Their price range runs from #260 a week to one top of the range luxury
chalet at #790 a head. Customers include Scottish Olympic equestrian silver
medalist Ian Stark - who has just booked again for Hogmanay with his wife Jenny
and a party of friends - and Genesis founder and rock star Peter Gabriel.
``As Scots operating in Scotland it now makes sense for us to increase our
efforts here. For Scotland we fly from Glasgow and Newcastle and we are selling
and competing on the assets of guaranteed good snow, affordable prices and
chalets staffed by our own people,'' says Kilmarnock-born Roddy.
``You can probably get cheaper accommodation but we believe we have a
significant advantage in still being small enough to control quality personally
and have an intimate personal knowledge of the resorts and each chalet. We can
fulfil the customer's expectations, which doesn't always happen when he or she
books with a larger more anonymous organisation.''
One element of that personal touch comes from Roddy's 47-year-old brother,
Richard, who runs the Val d'Isere operation. Courchevel is supervised by
Frenchman Philippe Bouron who maintains Scottish connection through Julie, his
Stonehaven-born wife whom he met when he worked in Glasgow.
Roddy believes fixed prices and the fact that chalet skiers can choose to spend
much of their evenings ``at home'' are shielding his customers from the poor
exchange rate and increased VAT charges that have British holidaymakers in
France wincing when they reached for their wallets this summer.
Nevertheless he is looking at Italy - probably Courmayeur or the Dolomites -as
an expension project next year. ``Italy is very good value and should provide
good business,'' he says.
And when the snow melts next spring Finlay's is ready with another area of
diversification beloved of Scots - golf. Roddy, who himself plays off seven,
says: ``We are running golfing holidays to some superb championship courses
between Bordeaux and Biarritz. They are less well known than some of the
Spanish and Portuguese golf holiday destinations but are every bit as good and
far less crowded.''
</TEXT>
