<DOCNO>GH951117-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>United sells off US unit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNITED Biscuits has taken another step towards extricating itself from the US,
selling the Keebler frozen foods division for $86m or about #54.8m. The buyer
is the privately owned Windsor Food company of Houston, Texas.
Earlier this month, chief executive Eric Nicoli said UB had reached agreement
to sell its US cookie and cracker business for the equivalent of #316m.
That is by far the largest element in the Keebler operations which, since their
acqusition in 1974, have proved a major disappointment, being too small in
competition with the US giants on their home territory.
The biggest setback was the decision to set up a greenfield plant in 1988 to
take-on Pepsico in its own state - the giant reacted with both savagery and
precision in its pricing policies.
The frozen foods activities include pasta, chilli and barbeque products as well
as the Chinese Food Processing Corp. That makes Chinese appetisers and Dim Sum
dumplings, the majority of customers being in the food service industry.
</TEXT>
