<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Assassin Amir does it again for the cameras</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tel Aviv, Thursday
WEARING a bullet-proof vest and firing a toy pistol, the assassin of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin re-enacted the killing in front of police video cameras
today while Israeli passers-by cursed him, witnesses said.
``Murderer, die. Maniac. You piece of garbage,'' shouted Israelis who stood
behind police barriers watching Yigal Amir, a 25-year-old religious Jewish
student, show police how he gunned down Rabin at a Tel Aviv peace rally on
November 4.
Police in Israel routinely have confessed murder suspects re-enact their crimes
in front of cameras for presentation as evidence at their trials.
Dozens of police cars crowded around the square early this morning while Amir,
linked by a chain around his stomach to a police officer, went through the
motions that shocked a nation and the world.
Amir walked from the parking area, where he had pretended to be a driver for a
VIP on the night of the killing, to an outdoor staircase where he ambushed
Rabin as the Prime Minister strode to his car, witnesses said.
``He took out his gun and moved near a policeman playing Rabin,'' said Yonathan
Shaul, a news photographer for the Israeli newspaper Maariv.
``Coolly, it was incredible, he drew the gun from his hip and `tak, tak, tak' -
a few shots. He put the gun back and continued the re-enactment as if nothing
had happened. Everyone, including all the police, began yelling and cursing.
People went crazy.''
Amir has said he carried out the killing, hitting Rabin with two bullets and
wounding a bodyguard, at Tel Aviv's largest public square because he wanted to
stop the 73-year-old leader from handing over more occupied land to Palestinian
self-rule.
</TEXT>
