<DOCNO>GH951117-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stalemate as budget row gets personal Clinton vows to veto stopgap Bill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday, PRESIDENT Clinton announced today that he would again
veto a bill offered by Congress to re-open the Government. Though the
Republicans have stripped away one of its objectionable provisions, a rise in
Medicare premiums, it would still lock in the President to accepting their
fundamental assumptions on the future of public spending, and he refuses to
accept.
The 800,000 Government workers laid off on Tuesday have been reduced
substantially in the past two days as Congress has passed two more of the
appropriations bills that should have been completed last September. However, a
bitter dispute in the House of Representatives thwarted an effort to pass a
bill for the Interior Department and a dispute with the Senate upset the State
Department and Foreign Aid Appropriations Bill.
The House debate concerns the environment. Radical Western congressmen want to
slash away at existing laws protecting wilderness areas, at the Endangered
Species Act, clean air legislation, and at environmental regulations. A revolt
by environmentally- conscious Republicans defeated the measure.
Meanwhile, the House sent to the Senate a State Department Bill including a
provision banning American contributions to international programmes that
supported abortion. The Senate rejected it, and it is now back in limbo.
The President also announced today that he was ordering workers in social
security and veterans offices to return to work on Monday, to process
applications for pensions and veterans' benefits. These already affect several
hundred thousand people, and Mr Clinton claimed that if applications were not
dealt with on a timely basis, the backlog would not be overcome for months.
It is not at all clear where the President will find the money to pay these
civil servants, but the shutdown of the Government is all theatre, so probably
nobody cares.
So far, the President is winning the public relations campaign. The public
blames Congress, not him. He achieved a further coup today when Mr Gingrich
appeared to be afflicted with a whining vanity.
The Speaker had complained that Mr Clinton had snubbed him on the long flight
to Israel and back for Yitzak Rabin's funeral. He said that the President
refused to negotiate with him and Senator Dole on the budget, and ignored him
throughout the flight. He admitted that he was playing particularly tough in
the budget battle out of pique.
That seemed petty enough, but today the White House issued photographs taken on
the plane showing Mr Clinton, Mr Gingrich, and Senator Dole, together with a
former Republican Secretary of State, George Shultz, in animated and friendly
conversation. It made the Speaker look very foolish.
Washington officially ran out of funds at midnight on Monday because of the
budget deadlock and at once shut down ``non-essential'' functions.
Although these confrontations have happened before the shutdown has never
lasted as long as this one.
McCurry indicated that Clinton, who has cancelled a planned trip to Japan,
might try to minimise the effects of the crisis by designating some of the
800,000 workers who have been sent home as ``essential'' and recalling them to
their jobs.
Clinton was to hold a Cabinet meeting late today ``to see how things are
going'' the White House spokesman said.
Although the government shutdown is the fifth in 14 years, it is already longer
than any of the previous ones, and the political confrontation has unusual
personal undertones.
Meanwhile, after weeks of disagreement over an abortion provision, the US House
of Representatives passed a $243 billion Defense Appropriations Bill today that
includes funding for B-2 bombers, missile defence and a military pay raise.
Over the arguments of liberal Democrats that Republicans were showing they
aren't serious about balancing the budget, the House voted 270-158 to pass the
spending measure - six weeks after its October 1 due date, the beginning of the
fiscal year.
The Senate was expected to take up the measure later today.
The defence Bill adds $7000m to what President Clinton requested and increases
the Pentagon budget $1700m from fiscal 1995, according to budget documents.
Rep Patricia Schroeder, a Democrat, asked how lawmakers could spend more on
bombers while cutting programmes like student loans. ``Will the American people
be more secure with their children in college or with B-2 bombers?'' Schroeder
asked.
A key motivator for the Bill's passage was the continuing federal budget
crisis, which has idled much of the Government's civilian workforce since
Tuesday. That includes 258,000 civilian Defence Department employees and
100,000 reservists.
</TEXT>
