<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drug fights `Aids' in monkeys</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday,
AN experimental drug has succeeded in protecting monkeys exposed to an
Aids-like virus, raising hopes that an emergency treatment could be found to
prevent the Aids virus from establishing itself in humans, scientists said
today.
If the leap can be made from monkeys to humans, one of the most promising areas
for the drug is in preventing women from passing the virus to their babies
during labour and childbirth, the scientists said.
It may even help rape victims avoid infection, said researcher Che-Chung Tsai,
whose report appears in the journal Science.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Goldmans to pursue Simpson for `every penny he owns'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday, THE O J Simpson trial will resume on April 2 next year.
This time, the acquitted ex-football star will face a civil suit alleging that
he must pay damages to the families of his ex-wife, Nicole, and of Ronald
Goldman, because he killed them both, whatever the jury ruled in the criminal
case.
The Goldman family is particularly insistent on pursuing Simpson. They were
outraged by the jury's verdict and intend to sue him ``for every penny he
owns''. The Brown family is more ambivalent.
Though Mrs Simpson's sister is convinced of O J's guilt, her parents are more
concerned with their grandchildren's welfare.
They worry that two children under 10 are already permanently traumatised, and
that their problems will be increased by lawsuits alleging that their father
murdered their mother. On the other hand, if the Goldmans' suit succeeds, and
Simpson is reduced to penury, his children, too, will be penniless. The Brown
family has therefore joined the Goldmans' suit: if it succeeds, and Simpson is
ordered to pay damages, half would go to the children.
The first round in the new legal battle was won by the plaintiffs. A judge in
Santa Monica, the suburb of Los Angeles where the case will be tried, ruled
yesterday that Mr Simpson's deposition must be released as soon as it is made,
and may be videotaped. Simpson had wanted the sessions kept secret.
He will be forced to answer questions that he avoided by refusing to testify at
his trial. Where was he at the time of the murders? Which of the various
versions of events he has offered is the true one? Where are his gloves and
track suit? What was in the bag he took to Chicago but did not bring back?
No doubt the lawyers for the Goldman family will press him relentlessly, and
when the tapes are broadcast, the programme will be watched by huge numbers of
people.
The deposition will be taken soon, though the trial itself is not until the
spring. This case will last even longer than the murder trial.
Meanwhile, Johnnie Cochran, the lawyer who successfully defended Simpson
against double murder charges, was today said to have signed a book deal
topping the #2.7m received by prosecutor Marcia       Clark.
The Los Angeles Times said Cochran's book will be titled My Journey to Justice:
The Autobiography of Johnnie L Cochran Jr. It will be published in the spring
of 1997.
The paper said another of Simpson's ``dream team'' of defence lawyers, Robert
Shapiro, completed  a #1m publishing contract on         Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Klein escapes prosecution for jeans ad</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday
FASHION designer Calvin Klein, who faced criticism over suggestive poses by
young models in his advertising, will not be prosecuted for sexually exploiting
children.
The US Justice Department has decided that no federal laws were violated by a
series of ads for jeans that appeared on television, in magazines, and on the
sides of city buses this           summer.
The department's child exploitation and obscenity section ``independently
verified that minors were not used as models in the particular photographs that
raised questions,'' Klein's lawyers were told.
A broad spectrum of observers, including President Clinton and his wife,
Hillary, blasted the ads and Klein agreed to withdraw them after they had run
less than two months, under pressure from the public and retailers.-AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>European Parliament calls for sanctions on Nigeria</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Strasbourg, Thursday,
THE European Parliament today called on the European Union to consider imposing
an oil embargo on Nigeria to put pressure on the country's military rulers
following last week's hanging of nine minority rights activists.
In a strongly-worded resolution adopted by the bloc's only directly elected
body, the Strasbourg parliament condemned Nigeria for the ``brutal executions''
of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other activists.
The resolution demanded that the EU and its 15-member states take all possible
action to bring about the restoration of democracy in Africa's most populous
state, which is heavily dependent on oil revenues.
It said an oil embargo ``is one of the most effective ways to put pressure on
the Nigerian Government and therefore calls on the Commission and the Council,
taking into account the situation of the Nigerian population, to consider
imposing such a measure''.
The resolution also called for sanctions to include a freeze on the bank
accounts of the Nigerian leaders in Europe and in particular in Britain, as
well as other steps such a sports boycott.
The wording of the resolution, which is not binding for the EU member states,
is stronger than one before the bloc's foreign ministers on Monday.
Nigerian military ruler General Sani Abacha today accused foreign powers of
interference, in his first reaction to the international furore.
``In recent times the international community has made absolute and deliberate
efforts to interfere in our national and internal affairs,'' the
government-owned Daily Times newspaper quoted him as saying.
Abacha said the actions of the Commonwealth in suspending Nigeria over the
executions was ``most unfortunate and uncalled for''.
The nine who were executed on disputed murder charges had been campaigning for
compensation for the Ogoni tribe in south-eastern Nigeria for oil produced
there for decades by multinationals, principally Anglo-Dutch oil giant Shell.
Several nations have recalled their ambassadors in protest at the hangings and
Lagos has recalled its own envoys in retaliation.
It is expected that EU Foreign Ministers in Brussels will formally approve an
arms embargo and other sanctions against Nigeria next week.
In a boost to the military Government, Shell has rejected calls to shut its
huge operations in Nigeria.
Shell, the biggest oil company in Nigeria, and its partners in a Nigerian
liquefied natural gas project met in Lagos yesterday and agreed to go ahead
with the construction of a #2500m plant.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Reno has brain disorder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339629</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON: America's top legal officer, Attorney-General Janet Reno, said
yesterday she had the brain disorder Parkinson's disease.
But she said it was not affecting her work and that she planned to carry on
with her job. ``I'm taking my medicine. I feel fine now,'' 57-year-old Reno
told a news conference. Her only symptom has been trembling in her left hand,
which she noticed last summer.
Displaying a steady left hand for reporters, she said her symptoms were under
control as a result of taking medicine.
Parkinson's disease robs people of control over their movements by causing
tremors, a shuffling gait, and muscular rigidity. It can eventually
incapacitate its victims.
Reno said her doctor, a professor of neurology at Georgetown University Medical
Centre, had told her that ``neither the disease nor the medication should
impair my ability to do the job, and I intend to keep on doing it''.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foreign Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339630</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scot on run from
Spanish jail
MADRID: Convicted drug smuggler Archie Christie, 30, from Neilston, Glasgow,
was on the run yesterday after failing to return to prison at Lerida,
north-east Spain, from a week's leave.
Christie was serving a four-year sentence after being caught with 70lbs of
hashish, worth #200,000, which he was trying to get back to Britain, at a
Barcelona railway station in August last year.
Factory visit
MUNICH: The Prince of Wales was yesterday shown a model of a computer-chip
factory that German electronics giant Siemens is to build in Newcastle. The
prince has been in Germany since Monday, touring Berlin and cities in the
former East Germany. Today he is to visit Riga in Latvia.
Miss Nigeria out
SUN CITY: Nigeria's entry in the Miss World beauty contest has withdrawn amid
outrage over her country's execution of nine dissidents a week ago, a spokesman
for the organisers said last night. Youth groups in South Africa, where the
contest takes place tomorrow, had demanded that Miss Nigeria - 23-year-old
Toyin Raji - be expelled because of human rights abuses in her country.
Roh jailed
SEOUL: South Korean ex-president Roh Tae-woo was taken to jail yesterday after
being arrested on charges of bribery. Roh has confessed to amassing #420m
during his 1988-93 term. Before leaving for jail, Roh apologised to the nation
and said he would take full responsibility for the slush fund scandal.
No arms cut
MOSCOW: Russia said it was not ready to meet a key treaty deadline of midnight
last night to cut the weapons it has along its borders. Defence Minister Pavel
Grachev ruled out any chance of Moscow meeting its obligations under the
Conventional Forces in Europe Treaty and said the agreement's limits on arms
would ruin Russia's defence capability.
Jail sex spree
DENVER: A woman arrested on a prostitution charge was mistakenly locked up with
men - and had sex with two of them before the mix-up was discovered, officials
said. The 38-year-old woman was locked in the men's section of the Denver city
jail last Saturday after being arrested on a prostitution charge. The mix-up
began when the arresting officer indicated in paperwork that she was a male.
Election date
MOSCOW: The upper chamber of Russia's parliament has voted to hold the next
presidential election on June 16 next year. President Boris Yeltsin, whose term
expires on June 12, recommended earlier this week that a date be fixed to ease
speculation that the vote might be postponed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trekkers tell of ordeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kathmandu, Thursday
SURVIVORS of a freak blizzard that killed dozens of trekkers in the Himalayas
last weekend spoke today of Sherpa guides clearing trails with sliced open
petrol cans and of yaks suffocating in the snow.
Trekkers plucked to safety by helicopter were still arriving    in Kathmandu
after avalanches and landslides killed at least 50 people, including 21
foreigners, over the weekend.
Rescue teams today evacuated 11 Americans, a Briton, and a Canadian from the
base camp around Mount Makalu, the world's fifth highest peak. A total of 517
people, including 228 foreigners, have so far been rescued.
The bodies of two foreign climbers killed in a weekend avalanche were today
named as Briton Nicolas Ellman and Canadian Mitchell Karper.        - Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Airport alerts end safely</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was a full alert at Glasgow airport yesterday when an air UK BAE-146 jet
with more than 70 people on board had landing problems - the flaps were not
working properly - as it came in from Amsterdam. The aircraft landed safely,
but the runway was closed for nearly an hour.
And a six-seater Piper Aztec had to return to Dalcross airport, near Inverness,
and make an emergency landing because of engine trouble.
Skipper fined
A DANISH skipper was fined #1500 yesterday and forfeited catch and gear worth
#17,000 when he appeared at Lerwick Sheriff Court. Hans Soenderby, 52, master
of the Froesang, admitted having too much edible white fish in his catch when
trawling for Norway pout, used for fishmeal, 100 miles south-south-east of
Shetland.
Syringes found
HEALTH officials are trying to trace the source of dozens of syringes which
have turned up on the banks of the River Nith, near Dumfries. The syringes have
been discovered near Kelton over the past few months.
Beatle venture
PAUL McCartney is planning to direct his own film of the life and times of The
Beatles using photographs taken by his wife Linda. He will use a technique made
use of in his first film venture, The Grateful Dead - A Photofilm, which
appears to make still pictures move. That film was premiered in London last
night.
Police award
THE Scottish Police College in Fife has won a major honour from the National
Training Awards Office. Its superintendents' course is run jointly with the
Scottish police service and aimed at enhancing service delivery to the public.
Woman killed
A WOMAN was killed yesterday when her car was in collision with another vehicle
on the Inverness-Beauly road at Bunchrew. She was named by police as Mrs Helen
Gallagher, 62, of Delshangie Farm, Glenurquhart, by Loch Ness. Three other
people involved were released from hospital after treatment for minor injuries.
Fire-raiser
FIFE man John Bilsland, 38, of Orkie Farmhouse Freuchie, was released on bail
yesterday when he appeared at Cupar Sheriff Court and admitted setting fire to
the Global Video shop in Crossgate, Cupar. Sentence was deferred until December
14.
Cannabis charge
SENTENCE was deferred until December 14 on Elaine Davis, 31, and John-Paul
Dormer, 28, both of Broad Street, Stirling, when they appeared at the town's
sheriff court and admitted cultivating and possessing cannabis worth #700.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Altnacraig bought out
by Norwegian partners
JEBSENS, the Norwegian shipping group, has finally offered to buy out its
financially troubled Scottish associate Altnacraig Shipping.
But 720 small shareholders, who put #5m into Altnacraig through the Business
Expansion Scheme (BES), will only recover a fraction of their ill-starred
investment.
The BES shareholders, who own 70% of Altnacraig, paid between #1 and #2.25 for
shares in Altnacraig between 1988 and 1990.
Now they are being offered to surrender them for shares in Jebsens, an unquoted
Norwegian company controlled by the Jebsen family, or 60p in cash.
Altnacraig has made a loss ever since its foundation in 1988 and has never paid
a dividend.
But it has always worked closely with Jebsens, a family-owned shipping firm
with which Altnacraig's chairman and founder Sir Ross Belch has close personal
links.
Sir Ross, 75, was formerly managing director of Scott Lithgow shipyards on the
Clyde which once built ships for Jebsens.
Altnacraig now operates as a virtual arms-length subsidiary of the Norwegian
firm, operating four ageing bulk carriers on time charter to the Jebsen-Wilson
Eurocarriers pool. In 1993, Sir Ross founded another company, Altnamara
Shipping, with #920,000 of shares raised under the BES and its successor, the
Enterprise Investment Scheme. This also operates a freighter on time charter to
Jebsens.
Altnacraig's directors have recommended acceptance of the Jebsens bid, which is
said to value the company at #3.25m.
The Norwegian group already owns 21.7% of Altnacraig and its chairman, Atle
Jebsen, pledged in June to make a friendly offer for the company.
But he warned then that Altnacraig shareholders should not expect to get all
their money back.
The Altnacraig board is under pressure to offer a cash exit to BES shareholders
now that they can sell their shares with full tax benefits after having held
them for five years.
And there is also a question mark over how long Altnacraig could continue to
trade as an independent company. Its latest loss of #288,000 in 1994 on
turnover of #3.8m reduced net assets to less than half of shareholder funds.
Jebsens is offering Altnacraig shareholders one Jebsens cumulative convertible
preferred share carrying an annual 10% dividend for each Altnacraig share or
seven Jebsens shares and 225p for every 10 Altnacraig shares.
However, the Jebsens shares would be difficult to sell since the company is not
quoted on any stock market. It has talked of seeking a quotation on the US
NASDAQ exchange, but dealing costs there are relatively high.
Altnacraig shareholders requiring a straight cash exit are being offered 60p
per share. The closing date for acceptances is December 22.
</TEXT>
