<HEADLINE>Anger greets proposal to restrict access to course at St Andrews</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of Scottish golfing holiday tour operators is ready to challenge a #5m
agreement which restricts access to the Old Course at St Andrews. Their claim
is on grounds of restraint of trade.
A confederation of nine companies, the Scottish Incoming Golf Tour Operators'
Association (SIGTOA) is vehemently opposed to the deal between the St Andrews
Links Trust and London hospitality company, the Keith Prowse Agency, to sell
starting times at the home of golf over a 10-year period.
SIGTOA and the St Andrews Hotels and Guest Houses Association believe corporate
interests descending on the town for just one or two rounds, will affect
adversely local business as well as tourism elsewhere in Scotland.
Mr Duncan Dewar, of the Fife-based company Best of Scotland Holidays which
holds the chair of SIGTOA, confirmed they are seeking the intervention of the
Secretary of State for Scotland who appoints links trust members, and of the
Scottish Tourist Board, to protect national interests.
``I have just returned from business meetings in the USA, and the British
Tourism office in New York is being flooded with complaints and switches to
Ireland.'' said Mr Dewar.
``Corporate packages of #1300 are convincing people that Scotland is too
expensive.''
Mr Ian McCaig, a leisure and tourism consultant acting on behalf of SIGTOA,
said: ``We believe this may be a restraint of trade and are looking at the
legal details. For many, the round over the Old Course is the treat around
which they actually come to Scotland.''
The majority of the crowd of 200 which packed St Andrews Town Hall this week
was against the new agreement. Dr David Reid, chairman of the Golf Heritage
Society of St Andrews, branded the trust as ``bringing St Andrews into
disrepute'' and claimed that the action was illegal.
The Hon.John Lindesay-Bethune, a former chairman of the trust, defended their
actions: ``What we have done, we believe to be in the best interests of the
town and the links, in order to improve them and secure them for the future.''
The former captain of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club explained that the links
would benefit from the #5m revenue to compete with six new courses due to open
in the area.
Increasing the price of playing a round on the Old Course to #100, or
``swingeing increases'' in season ticket prices were, he said, equally
unacceptable.
An Old Course spokesman confirmed yesterday that tee-off times are already
fully booked for all of May, September, and the first half of October. June,
July, and August applications have not yet all been processed but already look
likely to have filled all available tee-off times.
Tour operators are concerned not just about St Andrews but other leading
Scottish courses which may be outwith the reach of the ordinary golfer. It is
impossible to play a round at either Turnberry or Gleneagles without being
resident in the hotels. A round over Turnberry's Ailsa course next summer will
cost #250. Other charges next summer:
q.St Andrews - #60 per round. Very limited availability
q.Royal Troon - #90 per round.
q.Turnberry - Hotel residents only. Minimum #190 per single room, plus #60.
q.Gleneagles - Hotel residents only. Minimum #130 per single room, plus #65 per
round.
Leader comment.........................20
</TEXT>
