<HEADLINE>AVOIDING US APATHY</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a Labour Party member for over 15 years, I was intrigued by the letter from
John Foster of the Communist Party of Britain (November 15) where he argued
that the left should not leave the Labour Party but stay inside and battle for
progressive policies. Also, a left split from Labour would confuse the voters.
What I find confusing is that John Foster stood as a CPB candidate against
Labour in the recent local authority elections and now he wants to volunteer me
for a suicide mission!
Many, including John Foster, recognise that New Labour is chasing after the
rightward lurch of the Conservatives and that a future Labour Government would
come into conflict with the aspirations of ordinary working people and the
trade unions.
I have yet to hear anyone argue with any commitment that there is a realistic
prospect of the left reversing Tony Blair's agenda after a Labour victory.
Arthur Scargill's logic is that a new socialist party is inevitable. The left
needs serious discussions about timing, structures, and policies - and these
will not be easy.
But the alternative may be plunging our country to the depths of US politics
where the majority don't vote because there is little to choose between the
major parties.
Allan Green,
40 Victoria Park Drive South,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
