<HEADLINE>Foreign networks buy Royal broadcast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE BBC's Panorama interview with the Princess of Wales is expected to reach an
audience of hundreds of million worldwide following sales of the programme to
foreign broadcasting networks.
The carefully guarded interview, reported to have been seen by only eight
people at the BBC, has attracted interest from a number of networks, including
ABC in the US, CBC in Canada, and NHK in Japan.
The ABC deal alone is reputed to be worth $1m (#660,000). The programme will be
aired at prime time on November 24 in the US.
A BBC spokeswoman said that nobody outside the BBC, neither the palace nor the
princess herself, had the opportunity to vet the final programme.``There has
been no such request and it wouldn't be normal practice,'' she said.
In the Commons, Southampton Tory MP James Hill urged the princess to become a
``roving ambassador'' for Britain. Mr Hill's comments came as it was revealed
that the Prime Minister is to be questioned in Parliament next week about the
Duke of Windsor's alleged ``flirtation'' with the Nazis during the Second World
War.
Labour MP Andrew Mackinlay said he suspected that the duke - who was appointed
Duke of Windsor after succeeding to the throne as Edward VIII in 1936 and
abdicating the same year - was exploring the possibility of being restored to
the throne if Britain had capitulated to the Germans.
The king abdicated in order to marry American divorcee Wallis Simpson.
Mr Mackinlay has tabled a series of Commons questions on the issue following
accusations in a Channel 4 documentary that the duke was involved in a plot to
betray Britain to the Nazis. The Traitor King was broadcast last night.
The MP for Thurrock has asked the reasons for the refusal to release to the
Public Records Office ``certain papers relating to the conduct of the Duke of
Windsor during the Second World War''.
He said: ``It is absolutely scandalous that this matter can be covered up."
House of Commons authorities have refused to allow Mr Mackinlay to table a
question about whether the duke secretly married a woman called Millicent
Milroy in Canada during the 1920s.
</TEXT>
