<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Budget hopes depress currencies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339646</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOND and equity markets on both sides of the Atlantic are taking a lot for
granted. Share prices in London and New York have moved into record-breaking
territory in defiance of concerns about the tug-of-war between the Democrat
President and the Republican Congress over federal debt, and closer to home,
the Chancellor's scope for cutting interest rates on the back of a tax-cutting
Budget.
Wall Street is betting on a quick settlement of the US budget row and a
subsequent cut in short-term money market rates after the next scheduled
meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee on December 19.
The City has its sights set on the meeting between the Chancellor and the
Governor of the Bank of England on December 13 to deliver a half-point cut in
base rates.
Speculation about changes in interest rates is one of the most powerful
influences on stock markets. Dividend yields are inextricably linked to returns
that can be obtained elsewhere and so highly sensitive to the level of interest
rates.
Foreign exchange markets see interest rates in terms of the support they offer
to a currency's exchange rate. The prospect of a cut is regularly seen as
detracting from a currency's attractions.
It is no accident, therefore, that sterling and the dollar should both have a
rather sickly look about them at the moment.
The pound's trade-weighted index is just a touch above its all-time low,
established on Wednesday. And the dollar has given up a good part of its summer
gains against the hard currencies, the Japanese yen and the German mark.
A depreciating currency holds fewer dangers for the US than other nations,
because most essential commodities are priced in dollars. Imported inflation
through the depreciation of sterling is an ever-present threat to the inflation
outlook in the UK.
Kenneth Clarke cannot afford to ignore the reaction of the foreign exchange
markets to his Budget or to any subsequent rate cut, especially if it was
implemented against the advice of the Bank of England.
Investors should not count their chickens before they are hatched. At this
stage there seems little to be gained by chasing share prices into the
stratosphere.
Even if the hoped-for rate cuts materialise, markets often take the view that
it is better to travel than arrive. The faster shares rise the more likely is a
bout of profit-taking.
Policy bonus
LEGAL &amp; General with-profits policyholders may be wondering why, if there is
such a large surplus on their life fund, as the group said yesterday, their
bonus rates were cut this year.
The answer is that when setting bonus rates actuaries look towards the future
rather than what has happened in the past and they reacted with caution given
the outlook for investment returns, particularly fixed interest returns, and
lower inflation.
In addition, part of the surplus on the fund is legitimately owned by L&amp;G
shareholders, given their support for the with-profits fund, particularly in
the early days. The group has looked back into the history of the fund and
found that shareholders indirectly funded 40% of bonuses declared in its first
20 years. L&amp;G argues that the fund is now so strong that shareholders are
entitled to receive a higher return from their investment.
However the benefit to shareholders needs to be kept in perspective. L&amp;G is not
about to declare utility-sized dividend increases. The changes will allow
dividends to increase at a rate considerably above inflation, but L&amp;G may
decide that shareholders would be better served in the long-term if their funds
were used in other ways - like buying another life company.
The industry is after all ripe for rationalisation and acquisitions will be
easy to come by. Either way the changes were well flagged and L&amp;G shares have
outperformed this year so there is little more to go for.
L&amp;G is inviting its policyholders to comment on its proposals and their views
will be taken into account in the final decision to proceed, or on any
modifications. This is definitely to be encouraged. It is an idea other
companies should copy - consulting their shareholders every so often over their
strategy and how the business is run.
Brick wall
THOSE connected with construction and the housing market have become
increasingly vocal, as the Budget approaches, on the need for the Chancellor to
do something to restore confidence and provide a boost for homebuyers.
Sir Lawrie Barratt, chairman of the housing group which bears his name, said
yesterday that unless the Government reverses some of the damaging actions it
has inflicted over the past two years the housing market simply will not
recover.
He says the Government, which used to be the champion of the homeowner, has hit
homeowners with four hammer blows - the re-introduction of stamp duty on house
purchases over #60,000; two cuts in mortgage interest relief; two increases in
interest rates and, the last straw, a cut last month in mortgage interest
Income Support.
Whether the Chancellor will take direct action remains to be seen, but it seems
doubtful, although there are those who believe he may abolish stamp duty. This,
in itself, may not be enough to stimulate a moribund market but would at least
be a gesture and not cost too much.
The Treasury has always been opposed to mortgage interest relief and would like
to see it disappear completely, and no reversal on this policy, which would be
very expensive anyway, seems likely.
The director-general of the CBI has stated that the best way to help
construction and housing is to get interest rates down and the industry may
well have to settle for this.
</TEXT>
