<HEADLINE>Scots reliant on their cars</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339649</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS are clinging on to their cars for eight out of 10 journeys and more are
using them for trips of less than half a mile.
Even people who don't have a car feel their use is too important to be given up
for the sake of the environment.
Cars are fast becoming a new ``mini-freight'' service for regular grocery runs
to supermarkets, according to a major report by the RAC published yesterday.
The survey of Scottish attitudes to cars makes depressing reading for
environmental groups determined to encourage people on to public transport.
``Dependence is a reality for up to 80% of the journeys people make.
"Other forms of transport simply cannot do the job,'' said Mr Jeffrey Rose, RAC
chairman.
He said Scots believed their cars provided independence, a feeling of control
over their lives, driving pleasure, and led to big cash savings.
Mothers, increasingly anxious for the safety of their children, are making more
car trips to nurseries. The RAC would like improved, secure public transport
for very young children.
The RAC asked people to spend a week recording every journey, no matter how
short, to see how much they used their cars. A spokeswoman for the RAC said:
``It just shows how much we have come to rely on our cars and that it is going
to be very difficult to persuade people to change to public transport.
``The way to tackle the problem is to encourage the 20% who feel they are not
dependent on their cars to change to public transport which, of course, needs
huge investment if it is to succeed in attracting people.
</TEXT>
