<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Demise of daily that could only ape its rivals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339651</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TODAY - the brainchild of entrepreneur Mr Eddy Shah - was claimed to be
Britain's first computerised colour, national-daily newspaper when it hit the
streets on March 4, 1986.
However, its introduction took very few sales away from the established
dailies, although it was instrumental in starting a revolution in Fleet Street
which changed the face of the newspaper industry in the UK.
Politically, in its early days, despite a vow to be without party or prejudice,
the paper smacked of its middle-of-the-market rivals, like the Daily Express
and Daily Mail although in more recent years its slant was somewhat less
right-wing.
The comments of one newspaper critic shortly after its launch appeared to act
like a dark shadow during its lifetime, as it struggled to establish itself
even under different ownership: ``It appears not to have stumbled on a single
original notion, and those it has borrowed are implemented with far less elan
than they are by its well-established rivals.''
By June, 1986, the Sunday edition of Today ceased distribution in Scotland,
apparently because it was not well-received by readers who complained of its
failure to give full coverage of Scottish affairs.
Mr Shah dismissed reports of a cash crisis, but sold out to Mr Tiny Rowland's
Lonrho - the former owners of The Herald and Evening Times - within three
months of the paper's launch. Mr Rupert Murdoch, proprietor of the Sunday Times
and the Sun, became its third owner in 16 months when he bought it in July,
1987.
Mr Shah had shot to fame in 1983, when, using the Government's new employment
legislation, he defeated the National Graphical Association in a historic
dispute in Warrington.
In March, 1986, there were 600 on his payroll whereas the Express group,
producing two daily papers with less than double the projected circulation of
Today, employed more than 10 times that number.
In the early days Sainsbury was able to buy a full-page colour advertisement in
Today for #9600. Because of the new production techniques the advertisement
could list actual food prices, something which was virtually impossible in
colour advertisements previously, because of the time colour took to process. A
similar advertisement in the Daily Mail or Express without the up-to-date
prices, would have cost close to #40,000.
The threat to Fleet Street from Mr Shah was clear. Hence the efforts to speed
up the introduction of new technology and sweep away print-union labour
practices which in the end spelled the paper's demise.
Mr Murdoch out-manoeuvred his arch-rival, the late Robert Maxwell, in July,
1987, to add the title to his stable of newspapers, after Lonrho had pumped
more than #40m into it. Both men had seen the potential of the paper, once it
was re-directed and pointed at what was claimed to be a vulnerable Daily Mail
and Daily Express middle market.
News International appointed Mr David Montgomery, former editor of the News of
the World, as editor of Today. He is now chief executive with Mirror Group
Newspapers. A succession of editors followed him to hold the Today seat.
Today's circulation never reached the level hoped for, especially north of the
Border where a Scottish base and Scottish edition was launched last year at
Kinning Park, Glasgow, described by some as Mr Murdoch's Wapping on the Clyde.
Last December sales of 23,000 copies a day north of the Border were said to be
creating major tensions. Today editor, Mr Richard Stott, had said he hoped to
double sales of the mid-market tabloid in Scotland from 17,000 to 34,000. Five
staff worked in the paper's Glasgow bureau.
Although it achieved a 40,000 circulation initially by cutting its cover price
to 10p and a TV advertising campaign, latterly its figures were just 7000 more
than when it served the Scottish market from London.
Overall sales of the paper nationally reached an all-time high last year, but
with increasing pressure from rising newsprint costs dropped 8% to an average
of 573,680 over the last six months.
</TEXT>
