<HEADLINE>Clydesdale lifts profits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339652</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLYDESDALE Bank's pre-tax profits rose by a modest 2.6% to #113.6m last year,
reflecting its policy of concentrating on Scotland and turning a blind eye to
lucrative business opportunities south of the Border.
This limitation is imposed by parent company, National Australia Bank (NAB),
which does not want to see Clydesdale competing head on with its group
stablemate Yorkshire Bank in England.
Clydesdale therefore has to stick to its knitting in a rather patchy Scottish
market and a small corner of North-west England where it has had a small
presence for more than a century.
``We do not have the opportunity that some of our Scottish competitors have to
write business at handsome margins south of Hadrian's Wall,'' said outgoing
chief executive Frank Cicutto.
Mr Cicutto, 44, leaves Clydesdale in March to take a top job at NAB's
headquarters in Melbourne.
He will hand over to his deputy, Fred Goodwin, 38, who was recruited to
Clydesdale in March to be groomed as his successor.
Although profit growth was slim during the year to September 30, Clydesdale
managed to boost core lending by 11.2% to #4716m as senior management was
strengthened by the recruitment of a new team of dynamic young bankers.
The bank achieved 15% growth in business lending and 7.5% growth in personal
lending, mainly in the form of mortgages.
Provision for bad debts was cut by 23% to #16.6m, a level which Mr Cicutto said
would be difficult to reduce further.
The cost-income ratio improved marginally to 59.9% from 60.3%, but remained
nearly 10 points higher than that of Clydesdale's two main competitors - Bank
of Scotland and Royal Bank of Scotland.
Mr Cicutto partly attributes this gap to Clydesdale's continuing heavy
investment, especially in new technology. This rose 40% to about #20m last year
and was charged immediately to operating expenses.
He described 1994/95 as a year of transition in Clydesdale, during which senior
management changes and a new staff remuneration structure were brought in, as
well as a series of new financial products.
Staff resistance to some of these changes led to a one-day strike in February,
but Mr Cicutto said these problems had now been resolved.
He predicted that the structural changes which he has put in place over the
last 18 months would lead to improved efficiency and customer service in the
future which would feed through into new business and higher profits.
Clydesdale has launched new loan products for business investment and a new
flexible repayment mortgage over the the past year, and last month it began
selling life assurance.
``I am very confident about the future of the bank. It is a franchise that we
know we can develop well past where it is today,'' Mr Cicutto said.
He repeated his conviction that there was ``huge overcapacity`` in UK banking
and that further consolidation, along the lines of the merger of Lloyds and
TSB, was inevitable.
``There are no hiding places any longer and only the strongest will survive,''
Mr Cicutto said, adding that National Australia Bank could well play a part in
the consolidation process.
Besides Clydesdale and Yorkshire Bank, the group owns Northern Bank in Northern
Ireland. But there is a yawning gap in its coverage of southern England which
could be nicely plugged by the purchase of a building society.
Clydesdale chairman Lord Nickson, who is a member of the NAB board, said
further acquisitions in the UK remained a possibility.
But he added: ``There is nothing at all at the moment that is ongoing.''
National Australia Bank specialises in buying strong regional banks in western
countries.
It has just bought Michigan National Bank in the United States and is currently
bidding for Ireland's TSB bank in competition with National Westminister Bank.
The Clydesdale results were published alongside those of the National Australia
Bank group, which showed record profits from its seven banks in Australia, New
Zealand, the United States, the UK and Ireland.
Group operating profits rose 15.3% to to A$1936m (#968m).
But the contribution of the group's UK and Ireland division fell 1.9% to A$420m
(#200m), reflecting the high start-up of costs of National Australia Life, its
Clydebank-based life assurance company which began operations last month.
