<HEADLINE>Boy in intensive care after drugs overdose</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339654</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BOY is fighting for his life and another is recovering in hospital after they
took a drugs cocktail including ecstasy.
Eddie Ingleby and Kenneth Williams, both 15, became ill shortly before Leah
Betts died after taking the drug at her eighteenth birthday party.
The schoolboys were taken to Queen Alexandra Hospital in Cosham, Hampshire,
after hallucinating at their homes on Wednesday night.
Kenneth remains in the hospital's intensive-care unit while Eddie is said to be
recovering.
Both boys are from Leigh Park area of Havant, Hampshire.
Kenneth's mother, Mrs Sandra Page, described how her son returned staggering
and stumbling to their home.
She said her son could not speak when he arrived home and added: ``I'd like to
string up whoever is responsible for this.''
Kenneth's step-brother, Carl Page, said his brother kept falling over and
bumping into things.
He said: ``He went into the kitchen and tried buttering a plate. We thought he
was just drunk.
"We put him to bed but he kept getting out and wanted to sleep on the floor.
"He got really aggressive when we went towards him.''
The family called an ambulance at about 11pm   and he was taken to hos-  pital.
Eddie was taken to the hospital about an hour later, after his mother found him
staggering uncontrollably around their home.
Detectives in Portsmouth warned yesterday that the drugs problem was so bad in
the city they could end up with ``10 Leah Betts tragedies every week''.
Drug squad Detective Sergeant Nigel Midgley said Portsmouth's club scene
attracted thousands of people from around the region each weekend and drugs
were widely available.
``We have spoken to both the boys but not surprisingly they do not want to tell
us what they took.
``We believe that they took a cocktail of drugs. It's frighteningly easy to get
hold of ecstasy, amphetamines, and cannabis.''
He added: ``When the boys were brought to the hospital, they were both
hallucinating and drifting in and out of consciousness.
``It was apparently too late to stomach pump them, and this is why we're
finding it difficult to identify what they actually took.
``We'll be interviewing them both when they are released from hospital and
we're now making inquiries to find out where they got the drugs from.''
Drug squad officers say that up to 25,000 ecstasy tablets a week are being sold
in Portsmouth.
They estimate that the ecstasy trade in their city alone is worth #13m a
year.
</TEXT>
