<HEADLINE>Scotland could stand alone - Major A battle plan for the Union</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent RON MacKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339659</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister is preparing to revive the Northern Ireland peace process
and has given full backing to changes in the way Scottish legislation is
handled.
Mr Major signalled his double initiative in an interview yesterday when he made
a remarkable statement about an independent Scotland.
``Scotland could be a separate nation - it is perfectly credible. There are
five million Scots, there are many nations, not least those in the European
Community, no larger than Scotland. Scotland could stand on its own.''
On Ireland, Mr Major is about to send details of a revised ``twin track'' plan
to Irish Premier John Bruton. This approach involves running preliminary talks,
involving Sinn Fein and loyalist groups, alongside an independent commission
chaired by a leading American to oversee the decommissioning of terrorist
weapons.
The second stage would be all-party talks.
Mr Major said in an interview in the Independent that he still wants the IRA to
start handing over its weapons before the all-party talks could begin.
The peace process stalled in early September when Dublin pulled out of a summit
at the last minute after apparently bowing to pressure from Sinn Fein, which
strongly opposes the idea of an arms commission.
The new approach could heal the breach between Mr Major and Mr Bruton but no
date has been set for a meeting between the two.
Mr Major also signalled his support for Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth's
pledge to set out an agenda for the future of how Scotland is governed in a St
Andrew's Day speech.
Mr Major said he wanted people in Scotland to have better access to government.
More powers will be given to the Scottish Grand Committee to pass legislation,
sidelining Westminster.
Mr Major said: ``I can understand very clearly why the Scots sometimes feel
that Westminster is a long way off and that nobody is paying interest in them.
``I think the proposition for a Scottish Parliament is flawed for economic and
constitutional reasons. But I have been discussing some proposals with Michael
Forsyth as to how we might move forward and it is a subject that remains high
on my agenda.
``I hope we will be able to announce the outcome of our discussions within a
very few weeks.''
Mr Major recognised the threat posed by the SNP.
He said that because of the way Labour had framed its devolution proposals they
could provide a platform for the ``separatist party'' to gain a majority in
Scotland and claim a mandate for separatism.
``Once that demon rears its head it is very difficult to deal with, as we have
seen in various parts of the world. We ought not to let it raise its head.
``What I fear is happening, and this is not a political position, is that
Labour is offering a proposition for Scotland to keep the Scottish Nationalists
at bay because it is in Labour's political interest to do so.''
Conceding that Scotland could stand on its own, he added: ``It would be weaker
than standing as part of the UK, and the UK would be weaker without Scotland.''
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said last night the Prime Minister
would have to be less cryptic before he could comment in detail on his
proposals.
``It is welcome that the Conservatives are waking up to the strength of feeling
in Scotland. But if this remedy is simply going to be more cosmetic changes to
the Scottish Grand Committee then the plans will just be treated with
derision.''
He added: ``There is an air of panic about after 100 days of Forysth's three
initiatives a day.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said: ``This is an admission that the Taking Stock
exercise of only two years ago has been an abject failure in satisfying the
Scottish demand for real change.''
He said the Prime Minister should immediately concede a constitutional
referendum.
