<HEADLINE>In line to sample the latest in Hampden cuisine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Black</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339662</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON international duty at Hampden on Wednesday as a foot soldier in the Tartan
Army we were, on your behalf, standing in the half-time queue watching the
snails whizz past, all agog to sample the latest in Hampden cuisine.
When we finally got to the hatch (Motto: A Century of Caring Catering -
Starting Soon) and were dished out the pie in its neat little non-biodegradable
aluminium foil ashet and the plastic cup of superheated Bovril, we were also
handed a plastic poke containing a napkin, a wee plastic Bovril stirrer, and a
sachet of sugar.
``Oh, aye,'' said the chap behind the Diary, with no evidence of surprise,
``it's an acquired taste.''
Take a powder
NEWS in, from the Crime Scene column in the Motherwell People, of some
tealeaves with more than their share of forethought - and non-malicious
forethought at that. After removing three cases of Strongbow, six cases of
Holsten Pils, six cases of Miller Pilsner, and six cases of Spectro beer from a
car parked outside a cash and carry, the thieves also thoughtfully took four
boxes of Askit powders.
Hands on
IN a very informative piece in Farmers Weekly about the ins and outs of the
artificial insemination of cows, headlined ``A.I. - You Must Keep Hand In''.
No, honest. The common pitfalls of this labour-intensive practice are outlined.
Amid talk of Q-sums, submission rates, and inter-oestrus interval, three
mistakes emerge clearly. They are: Reduced fertility due to poor insemination
skills; Getting the A.I. gun in the wrong place and poor semen handling, which
sound sad, painful, and embarrassing.
At the top of the page is a photograph of a farmer, oxter-deep in cow, who
inseminates most of the 300-head Holstein Fresian herd at Ashburton, South
Devon. His name is Patrick Cock.
All shook up
HUGH Reed and the Velvet Underpants, one of the growing number of tribute
bands, have just been commissioned to do the music for a forthcoming film about
Robert Burns. Hugh O'Hagan, for such is his given name, and the boys recently
appeared on Trial By Night, putting forward the proposition that Rabbie was
Scotland's first and greatest superstar. Towards this end, they disguised
themselves as Rabbie Burns and the Tartan Trews and played that little-known
ditty You Ain't Nothin But A Tim'rous Beastie.
They have also recorded You're Bard and a reggae version of Ye Jacobites By
Name. They will positively not be playing The Cottar's Saturday Night Fever or
My Love Is Like A Red, Red Rose, Yeah, Yeah, Yeah, as we have just invented
them, but readers will no doubt be able to improvise on the theme.
Bands on the run
MORE on tribute bands. Colleague Ian Bell is not a fan of the Bootleg Beatles
but we are, as we have seen them perform and they are splendiferously good. We
have also seen the Counterfeit Stones, The Australian Doors, and Bjorn Again,
one of the many Abba soundalikes. Bands we would like to hear include The Real
Pretenders, The Man Who Would B.B King and Unfrank Sinatra. Real and imagined
names will be welcomed.
In the dark
ENTREPRENEURS in Blandford in Dorset, possibly in an attempt to make the place
sound more wild or less like a place for scoring heroin, has just opened a new
niterie named, in a burst of daring innuendo, The G Spot. The Diary has grave
fears for the club's future, as a survey among our female colleagues shows
that, in their experience, 93% of men will not be able to find it.
Clash of interests
A NEW category of events has entered the ken. This is the Back To Back Haud Me
Back, as tomorrow the Lord Provost and Glasgow City Council host at 12 noon the
visit of the Salvation Army Texas Brass and Timbrels UK tour, and follow this
up at 1pm with a similar reception for the AGM of the Association of Lourdes
Hospitalite. The second wee gay and hearty offers a finger buffet, wine, and
soft drinks while the first has the same buffet, but does not specify the
refreshments on offer.
Out there in Texas, where the tall timbrels grow, they are usually called
tambourines.
But the free minds at the Diary would be willing to bet our much-grooved Dylan
records that the Sally Ann won't have a Mr Tambourine Man on call.
Sailing on
A PIECE of good news from Her Majesty's Commissioners of Customs and Excise is
that the petition for the winding up of Flagship (Scotland) Ltd has been
withdrawn and that the Anniesland-based leisure club sails merrily on. One
would hope that this is an analogy for the state of the nation. Gubbing anybody
5-0 can't be bad.
Get a life
UNCONFIRMED word has reached us that the good burghers of Greenock and Port
Glasgow have invented a new sport. Hamster fighting is sweeping the area, and
largish sums are reportedly changing hands over this mind-boggling exercise in
man's inhumanity to wee furry animals usually called Hammy.
Without wishing to condone this heinous practice, a few questions do arise,
such as; how does one excite a hamster to the level of slavering vicious
fighting beast? And how exciting are the lives of those who watch them? Any
further intelligence would be appreciated.
IAN BLACK
Sturdy McCulloch Shredder
THE ever-vigilant eye of the Diary may
just have solved the vexing question of exactly what the concert hall are going
to do with those embarrassing murals, by tenacious local artist Ian McCulloch,
which are still refusing to vanish and were last seen adorning the walls of the
Tramway, though they are not there now. Advertised in the Daily Telegraph last
week, for a very affordable #199.95, is a Sturdy McCulloch Shredder, whose end
product is ``a superb weed inhibiting mulch or excellent compost''. They could
add it to the rather larger heap of compost already written about the murals.
</TEXT>
