<HEADLINE>Ecstasy victim's gift of life As Leah Betts's heart is transplanted to a young woman, millions say they would do the same</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339664</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ECSTASY drugs victim Leah Betts lost her struggle for life yesterday - but her
death brought new hope to others through the gift of her organs.
Her distraught parents Paul and Janet Betts said: ``We are certain she would
have wanted this.'' The couple wanted to break the news of Leah's death
themselves.
She died four days after taking the rave drug at her 18th birthday party.
Mr Betts said: ``It gives us some comfort to know that her death in some way
may give life to others.''
Transplant operations are believed to have begun within hours of 18-year-old
Leah's life support machine being switched off at Broomfield Hospital,
Chelmsford, Essex, early yesterday morning.
The teenager's heart, lungs, liver, kidneys, and corneas are likely to be used
to give new life to transplant patients. Mr Betts said it had always been
Leah's wish to donate her organs if she died.
``Leah's wish was that she should help others live in the event of her death. I
have respected that wish,'' Mr Betts said.
``This morning, her organs were donated and that should help six to seven
people to start a new life and possibly to see again.''
Leah had lain in a coma, sustained by a life-support machine, for four days
after she collapsed at the family home in Latchingdon, near Maldon, Essex, last
Sunday.
Mr Betts fought back tears as he said: ``One comforting thing is that she
probably died in my arms at her 18th party.''
At an emotional press conference, Mr Betts drew a deep breath and announced:
``Leah's ordeal is now over . . . it has been horrendous for us but the thought
of Leah living on to help others has made it that much more bearable.''
Mr Betts revealed his ``great anguish'' at the thought of surgeons cutting open
his daughter, even when she was dead, and he confessed: ``It frightens me.''
However, Mrs Betts, a nurse who advises young people against the dangers of
drug-taking, added: ``It gives me a peaceful feeling . . . she has given life
to six or seven people. It is comforting.''
She also made a moving appeal to other young people not to bow to peer pressure
to experiment with ecstasy, which has been the drugs phenomenon of the 1990s.
``This fashion must die like our daughter has died,'' she pleaded.
Mr Betts, a retired policeman, said he would treasure memories of his daughter
``from bouncing her on my knee to when she came running down the hall on
Saturday night dressed in her new outfit, saying, `how do I look?'
``She looked so beautiful. I have the same memories as any parent could have of
any child.''
Mr and Mrs Betts, together with Leah's three sisters and a brother, had
maintained a 24-hour bedside vigil.
Mr Betts praised staff at the hospital, describing those in the intensive care
unit as ``absolutely fantastic, so compassionate and caring'' and admitting
that without their support ``we would have crumpled long ago''.
``Also the transplant teams because that's a fear I had to overcome and they
again were very compassionate.''
Mr Betts also thanked members of the public for their support, delivered in the
form of letters, cards, telephone calls, rosaries, and prayers.
Mr Betts spoke of his anger towards those who peddled drugs and he called for a
radical review of the sentencing policy for drugs pushers.
``The hatred I have got is welling up inside me not only as a father but as an
ex-policeman.
``I do believe that if a sentence is passed it should be kept, instead of being
sentenced to five years and then you let them out after five months because
that is the biggest load of bull I have come across. What deterrent is that? It
killed my daughter and it is killing others.''
Six people were arrested yesterday in connection with the inquiry into the
supply of drugs to Leah. They were later released from custody.
A police spokesman said two of the six had been charged with intent to supply
drugs, although this was not connected to the Leah Betts incident. Another
youth was arrested last night and was being questioned by police.
Posters showing Leah in a coma will be handed out tonight at Raquel's
discotheque in Basildon, where Leah is thought to have bought the drug.
</TEXT>
