<HEADLINE>Entrapment defence success frees Scots bodybuilder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339665</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BODYBUILDER who admitted supplying an undercover detective with #100,000
worth of ecstasy tablets walked free yesterday after making Scottish legal
history by becoming the first person to successfully run a defence of police
entrapment.
The charge against 24-year-old amateur bodybuilder Steven Coan was found not
proven.
He had claimed that, in a police ``sting'' operation, detectives induced him to
commit a crime which otherwise he would not have committed.
Two of the men who sat in the dock of the High Court in Glasgow with Mr Coan
during the seven-day trial were found guilty of supplying 5000 ecstasy tablets
in the Marriott Hotel in July.
James Maclean, 20, unemployed, of Canada Court, Glasgow, and John McDonald, 26,
a joiner, of O'Neil Avenue, Bishopbriggs, were each sentenced to seven years. A
fourth accused, Brian Smith, 30, gas fitter, of Friendship Way, Renfrew, who
had the main charge dropped against him earlier in the trial, was jailed for
three months for possessing ecstasy. The sentence was backdated and he walked
free.
Releasing Mr Coan, of Brown Street, Anderston, Glasgow, the trial judge Lord
Weir told him: ``Fortunately for you, the jury has seen fit to acquit you.''
The court heard how the undercover police ``sting'' began when Edinburgh
bodybuilder, Mr Sandy Bryden, 40, was caught with a boot load of 38,000
Temazepam capsules after a cross-Border Scottish Crime Squad surveillance
operation.
Mr Bryden claimed in court he had been paid #500 by Mr Coan - a friend from
bodybuilding circles - to bring the capsules from Penrith to Glasgow, and that
he had done other runs in the past.
The court heard that, soon after Mr Bryden's arrest, police targeted Mr Coan.
Mr Bryden co-operated - in the hope things would go easier for him.
Undercover Scotland Yard detectives, experts in carrying out ``sting''
operations, were drafted in.
Their evidence made Scots legal history because, for the first time, they were
allowed to testify under assumed names and behind a screen.
In his evidence, Mr Bryden told how he introduced Coan to an undercover
detective called Robbie in an Edinburgh pub.
During that meeting, Mr Coan and Robbie, he alleged, discussed a big ecstasy
deal.
A series of other meetings followed in Glasgow's Marriott Hotel and Coan was
introduced by Robbie to two other undercover colleagues.
Mr Coan claimed the purpose of his meeting wasn't ecstasy but to get supplies
of anabolic steroids, which are legally used by bodybuilders throughout the UK.
Mr Coan told the court he thought ``Vic'' was a wealthy London club and gym
owner as well as being a major anabolic steroid supplier.
However, Mr Coan claimed, Vic asked him to get him ecstasy and hinted that the
anabolic steroid deal might not go ahead if he couldn't help him.
</TEXT>
