<DOCNO>GH951117-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Teachers' vain bid to save pupil</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339667</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 17-year-old schoolboy collapsed and later died while watching a rugby match
at Loretto School in Musselburgh, East Lothian, yesterday.
Pupils watched as staff and a doctor tried in vain to resuscitate John Kelsey,
a boarder at the school, before paramedics arrived. He was taken by ambulance
to Edinburgh Royal Infirmary, where he later died.
Headmaster Keith Budge said the boy's parents, who live near Aberdeen, had been
informed and were travelling to Edinburgh. He said John had been studying for
A-Levels, and that pupils and staff were ``in a state of shock''.
``Parents are being contacted to ask them to take their children home early for
the weekend,'' he added.
The public school's old boys include the late MP for Perth and Kinross, Sir
Nicholas Fairbairn, and retired judge, Lord Allanbridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why grocers are right up my street</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack Mclean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE modern bakers - that is to say the large chain bakers - claim to bake bread
on the premises. In fact, and now you know, they don't. Some of them partially
bake, and some of them don't even bother with the subterfuge. What they do is
pipe chemically-induced scents redolent of childhood days before the Great War,
and pipe music evocative of it in their shops and sell you a pile of E-Number
glutens and tell you lies really. Well we all like to swallow a lie. Frankly
I'd rather swallow a wee mendacity than most of the bread I encounter but there
you are.
What I can't swallow though is the visual aesthetics of it all. Dear heavens I
remember the time when the bread was real and there was a wee rail for ladies
to put down their shopping bags, and the assistant behind the counter asked how
your man or weans were. Soda scones and flies' cemeteries. The sweetmeats might
not have been much but the nostalgia was grand.
A few years back I wrote about a bakery itself, an old and distinguished place,
Shorts of Shawlands. Claimed that their pies were easily the best in the world.
Round mutton pies with crusts on them which could have been moulded by
craftsmen from Church's Shoes, a spiced interior which would have demanded the
Crusades to get hold of the ingredients, enough grease to lard Gene Vincent's
bop for a year.
But the shop itself was splendid and gloriously old-fashioned in the way that
made you think the old-fashioned phrase ``old-fashioned'' had the imprimatur of
quality and class. Sadly Shorts was moved round the corner and I suspect, after
a recent visit, that the receipt for these pies has been changed to fit in with
the contemporary demand for food which tastes of toddlers training pants.
Invented smells and ersatz tastes, indeed manufactured sounds, are all very
well; I can cope with them. All I have to do is close my eyes to them. But
there comes a time when a sense cannot be treated in this way. The time has
come.
When I am cheated of my eyes I come to the edge of fury, teetering over the
volcano, looking into the bad fire of false consciousness. And this week saw
that. And involved every sense at that, including one of bewilderment. For it
was just the other day that madness took over in the matter of shops and sight,
and all the other senses too. Greengrocers.
Greengrocers are not usually thought of as romantic establishments but they
are, my dears, they are. Shops are. My old Grandma used to enliven our daily
trips to the shops in Stevenston, Ayrshire, with a History, Geography, and
Literature lesson in every one. The Post Office had stories of the glamour of
Rowland Hill and how William Makepeace Thackeray had laboured for about an hour
and a half a day in the then postal service.
Post offices in the early 1950s smelled of unwashed three-piece suits, Stafford
Cripps, and sealing wax. And now to cabbages and kings, but in a minute.
My Grandma was wont to explain that cloves came from Madagascar, ``an island
situated in......'' when I spied the jar of them in the local licensed grocers.
That Belfast ham actually originated in Ayrshire, and was sent back from
Ireland through a complex series of economic arrangements. Gigot was a Scotch
cut of mutton and the word came from the French language. Every shop had a
story.
Goddammit we used to go down to see Sannie Frew who owned the coal merchant's
and where my Grandma paid her quarterly bill and she was wont to tell me
stories of 35 miners buried alive and the funereal celebrations which ensued.
Every step of a shop had a tale to it.
And even greengrocers too. If butchers displayed their bloody wares and crusted
steak pies lined with elaborate frills of parsley, and fishmongers
ostentatiously showed their produce, dabs and flounders, shellfish, scuttling
lobsters - Glasgow's sawyers were wont to stick entire deer with antlers aloft
outside their doors - it was as nothing to the exotic colour of a greengrocers.
Outside in the street the greengrocers put out their wares. Boxes piled upon
each other of green cabbages, orange, well oranges, red apples, vivid tomatoes,
sedate beige mushrooms, potatoes looking like antique artefacts claimed from
some recondite archaeological dig, and today is even better.
The purples of aubergines, the wrinkled Corporation green of avocados, the
bright parrot flash of colour from green, red, yellow peppers, the comforting
sculptural shapes of fresh ginger root or the smooth suave pods like kiwi fruit
or Chinese gooseberries.
Red and purple plums, tumbling black and green grapes, spiky pineapples, the
curves of clumps of bananas. Here, we are going on a bit. But was it not a
bonnie picture, the panorama of fruit and veg, out in the street, like bright
umbrellas over cafe tables in a cobbled Paris street?
But was not a greengrocer finally told that he could no longer display his
produce out in the street? Derbyshire magistrates told the poor man that he
could no longer allow the populace to enjoy the burst of art and colour which
greengrocers everywhere have set before us since before the times of Nell
Gwynn. The magistrates said his show obstructed the pavement.
A TV crew came out to film this villain and discovered otherwise. They filmed
this hapless greencrocer's shop and it took seconds for the telly boys to
discover that not only could a double buggy get by this so-called obstruction
but, better still, they even managed to film a wee old lady in a wheelchair
buying her iceberg lettuce from the stall out in the street.
In short, our English greengrocer was giving more access to the disabled than
he would have done if he confined his sales technique to inside the shop. The
real disabled were the Derbyshire councillors who thought up how to blind
greengrocers, and citizens, to art and tradition at that.
</TEXT>
