<DOCNO>GH951117-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inmate found hanged in cell at Perth Prison</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339674</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PORTUGUESE waiter who was jailed for five years after a bungled attempt to
rob a Scottish nightclub has been found hanged in a cell at Perth Prison.
A fatal accident inquiry will be held into the death of Jorge Manuel Liandro,
from Manchester, whose body was found when cells were unlocked at 8.30am in the
prison's E Hall yesterday.
He was convicted at Aberdeen High Court in February last year on charges of
assault and attempted robbery and was serving a five-year sentence.
Last year, suicides in Scottish jails rose to 15, leading to a review of
suicide prevention strategy. The results of the inquiry, by Professor John
Gunn, of London University, one of the UK's leading forensic psychiatrists, are
expected to be published before the end of the year.
This year, the number of deaths in custody in Scottish prisons which are
possible suicides is said to be nine.
Liandro was sentenced after being found guilty of trying to rob Mr G's club in
Aberdeen. He was also convicted of assaulting Ms Myra Mackie, 60, a cashier, by
pointing a handgun at her, and at two men who chased him down the street.
His trial featured in a BBC documentary series The Trial, which showed him
being consulted by a solicitor and talking confidently about being cleared of
the offence.
Last week, police were called to Perth Prison twice within 24 hours after an
incident in C Hall when a 22-year-old inmate was stabbed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
