<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>INSURANCE CE Heath disappoints at half-time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339676</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INSURANCE broker CE.Heath hopes that the hive-off of its computer activities
will result in the new company having a stock market valuation of around #60m.
It is expected that the formalities will be completed in January with existing
Heath shareholders receiving shares in the computer company - which has still
to be named - some time in February.
That points to it being worth about 90p per existing Heath share which
yesterday dipped 5p to 163p.
Heath has bought the minority 30% stake in the Datasure subsidiary from fellow
broker Lowndes Lambert for #6.15m.
Disappointing half-time results were accompanied by a boardroom re-organisation
which sees chief executive for five years Peter Presland put in charge of
computer activities. He is succeeded by John Mackenzie Green who in recent
years has been on the international side.
Pre-tax profits in the six months to September showed a 61% increase but that
was after a #3.89m gain on the sale of the 22% stake in Heath International
Holdings (HIH) of Australia to Winterthur. That carries a nasty sting in the
tail in that there is a capital-gains tax liability amounting to #8.8m on the
disposal which has had the effect of pushing Heath into a net after-tax loss of
#2.22m. That has helped prompt the decision to cut the interim dividend from 5p
to 3p.
The current half year will lack both the HIH contribution and six months of
computer profitability together worth about #5m. That points to full-year
profits of about #13m with the on-going insurance business running at an about
#7m annually. The decision on the final dividend will be made at the time of
the computer sell-off details.
