<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh hotels change hands in deals worth #3.9m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Kirst dorsey</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339677</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``HOTEL'' was the name of the property game in Edinburgh yesterday as it was
annouced that two establishments have changed ownership.
Glasgow-based hotel and casino group Stakis announced that it would pay #2.9m
for the Clarendon Hotel, a 52-bedroom property located opposite the 136-bedroom
Stakis Edinburgh Grosvenor Hotel, near Hay-market.
Nearby in the New Town, businessman and hotelier Peter Taylor announced he was
purchasing The Howard from receiver Touche Ross for #1m. The four-star
establishment, which has been operating under receivership for four years, is
located on Great King Street.
Stakis took over the Clarendon yesterday, while Mr Taylor will take ownership
of The Howard on December 1.
A Stakis spokesman said the group intended to spend #500,000 upgrading the
Clarendon and restoring six extra bedrooms. He added that the hotel would be
closed for approximately two months early next year while renovations were
carried out.
The Clarendon will operate as an annex to Stakis' Grosvenor Hotel, although
exact details of how the two will function together have not been determined,
the spokesman said.
In addition to the two Haymarket properties, Stakis also owns the 134-bedroom
Edinburgh Airport Hotel, which opened in May.
The Glasgow-based group operates 18 hotels in Scotland and 24 in other parts of
the UK. It also runs 23 casinos and a combined hotel and casino in the Isle of
Man.
The new owner of the Howard said he intended to carry out renovations to the
small luxury hotel, but he was unsure what the total price tag would be.
He plans to revive refurbish parts of the interior, improve parking facilities
and develop the restaurant, bar and private function rooms.
Mr Taylor, who also owns the Channings Hotel in South Learmonth, said he had no
intention of adopting a ``group'' approach towards The Howard. The interior
refurbishment will be superficial - making a temporary closure unnecessary.
They will simply ``add the little touches that make the difference''.
Mr Taylor said an investment in the staff would also mark the difference
between The Howard and other hotels.
``Small, simple things have held them back from doing the best job they can
do,'' he said. Mr Taylor added he was interested in acquiring hotels in both
Glasgow and Aberdeen, but stressed he would make no purchases until
``absolutely perfect'' locations became available.
n NORTH British Trust Hotels is preparing to host a charity event in its
recently-refurbished Greens Hotel in Edinburgh.
Norris D Beith, chairman of North British Hotels Trust, will present almost
#25,000 in donations to four beneficiaries on Monday, November 27.
Renovations to the Greens Hotel were completed in May. The West End property,
formerly run as a budget hotel, was refurbished in a twenties style and
equipped with modern facilities and meeting rooms.
The #1.2m renovation was designed to attract business travellers.
</TEXT>
