<HEADLINE>New data encourages fresh hopes of an early cut in interest rates after the Budget October retail price index falls 0.5%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R.E.DUNDAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339678</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE main measures of inflation all fell last month on the back of the biggest
decline in the retail price index for any October since 1944.
The unexpectedly good figures came the day after poor retail sales and
unemployment data hit sterling and were accompanied by a substantial surplus in
the public finances last month.
Once again the City concluded that the chances of an early cut in interest
rates had improved. The public borrowing figures improved the financial
background against which the Chancellor must make his Budget judgment in 11
days' time.
Rate speculation in the money markets drove share prices up to record-breaking
levels. The FTSE-100 share index jumped 39.4 points to 3610.8 as the Dow-Jones
index on Wall Street made further progress towards 5000. Footsie's previous
all-time high of 3598.0 and its record close of 3593.0 were set on October 18.
Sterling moved off the floor on the back of the news, and its trade weighted
index edged up from 82.6 to 82.7, but it remains very weak, largely because of
the mounting speculation about lower rates.
The retail price index fell by 0.5% to 149.8 (January 1987 = 100). As a result
the headline rate of inflation tumbled from 3.9% in September to 3.2%, a much
bigger drop than the City had been expected. The underlying rate, which
excludes mortgage interest payments, declined from 3.1% to 2.9% in
contradiction of a forecast in last week's Bank of England inflation report
that it would increase.
The RPIY measure, which is closely monitored by the Bank of England, retreated
from 2.6% to 2.4%. It excludes indirect and local authority taxes as well as
mortgage interest.
The headline rate benefited from cheaper mortgages, which knocked 0.2% off the
RPI, and a mortgage increase last year (also worth 0.2%) dropping out of the
annual calculation.
The big surprise was a 7.6% decline in seasonal food prices, which had risen
sharply in the summer because of the drought. This factor reduced retail prices
by 0.2%. Lower petrol prices and a fall in insurance premiums also benefited
the figures. Prices of clothing and footwear and household goods fell slightly.
James Capel's Adam Cole said: ``Core inflation improved slightly in October and
shorter term measures suggest the peak may well be in sight.''
But he warned that if erratic items such as seasonal food were stripped out
there was little in the October figures to change the outlook for underlying
inflation.
``Equally there is nothing to preclude a near-term rate cut if the Chancellor
avoids a give-away Budget,'' he added.
Goldman Sachs's Martin Brookes said: ``Perhaps the main factor against a cut in
rates at the December 13 monthly monetary meeting is the renewed weakness in
sterling.''
But unless the pound declined significantly further there was a strong chance
of a base rate cut in the next few weeks, he added.
A big increase in corporation tax receipts enabled the public sector to repay
#1262m of debt against a repayment of #467m in the same month last year. In
addition September's borrowing was revised down by #400m to #3349m.
In the first seven months of the fiscal year the Public Sector Borrowing
Requirement has totalled #18.8bn, little better than the #19.6bn at the same
stage last year.
However, privatisation proceeds are negligible this year, whereas last year
they amounted to #3800m in the first seven months.
Receipts picked up last month. In particular corporation tax contributed
#7315m, representing a 33% increase on the same month a year ago. October is
the second biggest month for corporation tax payments.
But there were also signs of a general pick up in revenues. In the first seven
months total tax receipts were up by 9.4%, stronger than in recent months, but
still below the 10.8% forecast in the Treasury's summer statement. With retail
sales in the doldrums the biggest shortfall is in Customs and Excise where
receipts are 6.6% higher against a forecast of 9.8%.
The belated improvement in revenues still leaves the Treasury's forecast of a
1995/6 PSBR of #23.6bn looking decidely optimistic. Both James Capel and
Goldman Sachs are forecasting a PSBR of #28bn, which will force the Chancellor
to finance tax cuts in his Budget from reductions in planned public spending.
The latter said last night that it expected tax cuts of around #5000m
``financed in large part by cuts in public spending plans''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A sense of foreboding haunts the workers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339679</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE no desire to get embroiled in what looks like another synthetic
Westminister slanging match between Ian Lang and Margaret Beckett over the
Minister's thoughts on job insecurity. But, away from yesterday's ritual party
point-scoring, the issue does actually matter to an awful lot of people.
It matters to the many who fear their jobs might be casualised or might not
exist this time next year. It matters because of the impact that sense of
unease has on the rest of their behaviour, as members of families, as
consumers, as citizens of a still-relatively-civilised society. And it matters
for the future effective functioning of the companies and organisations which,
in pursuit of competitiveness through cost cutting, have helped sow that sense
of insecurity in their own workforces.
Given his party's present standing in the polls, you might have thought the
President of the Board Trade would be feeling a shade uneasy about his own
long-term job prospects. But, on a visit to the CBI conference in Birmingham on
Tuesday - where he singularly failed to persuade the employers' organisation to
take the Tories' side in the forthcoming election - Mr Lang indulged in some
off-the-cuff asides to journalists about job insecurity being ``a state of
mind''.
Labour's roundhead Shadow pounced. ``Cavalier, insensitive,'' intoned Mrs
Beckett. ``It is profoundly offensive for a senior Minister to tell people job
insecurity is just in their minds. They know it is not true. It is a grim and
depressing reality.''
To be fair to Mr Lang, he actually said: ``Job insecurity does exist. What I am
saying is job insecurity is a state of mind.'' And, of course, he's right. Fear
of redundancy is a state of mind. A nagging, persistent worry that old
employment certainties have gone for good. It's not the physical fear triggered
by the sight of a redundancy notice with your name on it thrust into your hand.
Or the sick feeling in the pit of the stomach, the sense of utter rejection
felt by those confronted by the black bin bag on the desk and instructions to
be off the premises within the hour.
This is a sense of foreboding which haunts the inner self. Where else, than in
the mind, could anyone experience it? But, in what passes for political debate
in this country, saying: ``It's a state of mind'' translates into yesterday's
Mirror headline: ``It's all in your mind''. In other words, you are all deluded.
I don't know whether that's what the President of the Board of Trade intended.
But the phenomenon of job insecurity is no delusion. And, while it has been a
major factor in the reluctance of consumers to consume with any enthusiasm in
recent years, it is now becoming a matter of concern for more and more
employers, slowly but surely discovering that delayering, downsizing and all
the other euphemisms for cutting overheads by cutting jobs do not, all too
often, deliver the productivity and efficiency gains intended.
In the 1960s, more than 70% of the UK workforce was in permanent, full-time
employment. Now that percentage is down to 46% and falling. More and more of
the casualties of that process have ended up on the dole. In the past 30 years,
the base levels of claimant unemployment have climbed inexorably, from
1,000,000 in the 1970s, to 1,700,000 in the 1980s, to 2,200,000 in the 1990s.
Those not on the register and not in full-time jobs have either become
economically inactive, gone back into the expanded tertiary education system,
discovered an economic existence in the black economy, become self-employed or
signed up for the world of flexible (part-time, temporary) employment.
Despite some of the frothier hype about the enterprise culture, many of the
3,300,000 people now self-employed in the UK (the figure comes from the
Government's own Labour Force Survey) are not on the brink of building growth
businesses. They are, rather, self-employed contractors supplying their
personal skills on a freelance basis to a range of customers.
In some industries, like my own, there has always been a freelance tradition.
Elsewhere it is relatively new. The existence of self-employed journalists,
building workers, software engineers, designers, window cleaners and myriad
other trades has long brought a measure of flexibility to the labour market.
But now that concept has been taken much further. The flexible employed
workforce - 1,500,000 temporary workers, 4,600,000 permanent part-timers,
according to the latest LFS bulletin - has grown rapidly in recent years, as
more and more companies have sought to match the size and shape of their
payrolls to the variable demands from their customers.
If a manufacturer of consumer goods has to despatch two-thirds of annual orders
in the three months before Christmas or a retailer sells 70% of weekly takings
on a Saturday the implications for permanent nine-to-five jobs are patently
clear. The majority of part-time workers, according to the LFS, do not want a
full-time job and are happy to provide some of that flexibility. But business's
enthusiasm for labour flexibility has gone much further than that.
The fashion, in the past decade, has been to reduce core staff to a minimum and
outsource more and more functions, either to sub-contractors who are expected
to be equally flexible or to agencies which will come up with people, but only
when they are needed.
Employers searching for improved competitiveness want the flexibility to match
payroll costs to even unexpected ups and downs in demand. Hence the growth of
temporary employment contracts in industries like electronics. Some of the
assembly plants in Silicon Glen don't even employ many of their own shopfloor
workers. They contract that out to agency companies, whose main asset is a pool
of work-anywhere operatives.
There is nothing new in this. When I was growing up in Greenock in the fifties,
tradesmen in the local shipyards were paid off, Friday by Friday, as their work
on a particular vessel was completed. Off they went to find another ship, in
another yard, that needed their skills.
But it created a sense of insecurity then. And it does today. And, as
accumulating evidence from the United States shows, breaking traditional
employment bonds with employees may not result in the competitive gains
intended. Job insecurity may be in the mind. But it may also be taking its toll
in the office and on the shopfloor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lenders reduce loans</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339683</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO major mortgage lenders yesterday cut interest rates on their fixed rate
loans. The Royal Bank of Scotland reduced the rates on its range of such loans
and on home improvement loans by up to 1.2%, while Alliance &amp; Leicester
Building Society said its rates on loans with one, two and five-....year fixes
were going down by up to 1%.
Other lenders said they were holding their rates, though Halifax commented that
it was monitoring the market and would respond if necessary and Cheltenham &amp;
Gloucester indicated it would remain competitive.
The moves reflect strong competition in the mortgage market while house buying
remains depressed and the overall climate which is pointing to the next move in
rates in general being down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inferior loo</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339684</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I had occasion to use the so-called Super Loo at Glasgow Central station and I
was shocked.
At the time of opening some years ago it appeared to be at the cutting edge of
toilet technology. It has not maintained this position. Today it is far
inferior to the average lavatory in Glasgow's shopping malls and service areas.
Railtrack or the responsible concessionaire should take immediate action to
bring the place up to appropriate hygiene standards, or remove their entrance
charge.
Rodney Snook.
Shanton Cottage,
Shanton Road, Cove
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The good things in Glasgow that novelists ignore</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339687</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WOULD be foolish of me to refute the claim by my old newspaper colleague
John Burrowes that Glasgow still has a ``raw and real'' side to its character
but he knows just as well as I do that the kind of thing he and other novelists
write about Glasgow may easily be written about any major city in the world.
And not only cities. How many novels are written about leafy, rural towns and
villages in England, and Scotland, where mutilated bodies are found in the
shrubs, where sex and fraud scandals are the talk of village halls?
The sad truth is that sex and violence sell better than sweetness and light and
good deeds, which is why books, films, and plays about the former far outweigh
the other.
When I was the city's ``spin doctor'', a breed for which John Burrowes has such
contempt, I was interviewed by hundreds of news media people from every
continent and I told every one of them not to tell their readers, viewers, and
listeners that I had tried to pretend that Glasgow as some kind of paradise on
earth because, and I quote, it has all the ills of any other major city.
I did, however, ask them to tell about the good things the city had, too, the
kind of things that are never mentioned in the books of John Burrowes and Ron
McKay. Even in the days of Alexander McArthur and his No Mean City there were
efforts being made by many people to improve the city.
For decades there have been politicians, administrators, developers,
architects, builders, designers, organisers, heads of industry and commerce,
traders, artists, musicians, dreamers, people with ideas and no money, people
with money and no ideas but a willingness to back others, and people who just
wanted to get their names in the papers, all working to enhance the quality of
the city.
These people have no place in the novels of John Burrowes, Ron McKay, and James
Kelman.
Glasgow is a bubbling cauldron of endeavour, determination, enthusiasm,
self-interest, and arrogance and is a product  worth boasting about to the
world.
I don't want John Burrowes exterminated. I don't even want him to stop writing
sex and crime novels. I just want the world to know that not everyone in
Glasgow behaves in the way his characters do.
There is hardly anywhere in the world that has not benefited at one time or
another from the ingenuity, imagination, enterprise, skills, inventiveness,
clarity of thought, and genius of people born or trained in Glasgow.
Harry Diamond,
27f Greenholme Court,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
