<DOCID>GH951117-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Official confirms jobs `backing'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339689</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR Monklands District Council official yesterday told the
``jobs-for-the-boys'' inquiry how he became a member of the Labour Party at the
age of 56 - after taking up the Monklands post.
District building services director Ian McDonald, told William Nimmo Smith QC
that he joined the party last year - three years after moving from the private
sector.
However, Mr McDonald denied that party membership or being a relative of a
councillor was an advantage in getting a job or gaining promotion within the
DBS.
He admitted however that the green job application forms did indicate that the
candidate had the backing of a councillor.
The inquiry - now in its fourth day - has already heard that other coloured
forms were used to denote applications from outside and inside the council.
Mr McDonald said: ``I saw different coloured forms. Out of 1978 forms I
personally processed, the maximum I ever saw in terms of green forms was 10.''
Asked by Mr Nimmo-Smith if the green forms meant the candidate came on the
recommendation of a councillor, Mr McDonald said: ``One could construe that,
yes.''
Mr McDonald maintained he accepted responsibility for all appointments but took
no account of councillors' recommendations, or Labour Party membership.
Earlier, local Conservative party chairman Gordon Lind, one of the council's
chief critics, told Mr Nimmo-Smith that rumours over nepotism had persisted for
years.
Mr Lind had submitted unsigned letters he had received to the inquiry.
Mr Nimmo-Smith said he found the material ``repugnant'' and not worthy of
consideration. Mr Lind also told of his disappointment that one of his
``sources'' would not be giving evidence at the inquiry.
Asked about a specific case of nepotism, he said: ``I cannot speak of any
specific item in relation to that.''
Another witness, Ms Eileen McCauley, 34, a local newspaper reporter who was
first to report on the Monklands allegations, told Mr Nimmo-Smith that her then
employer, the Airdrie and Coatbridge Advertiser, had taken no specific
political line on the story.
Ms McCauley rebutted suggestions that the newspaper had carried the
``Monklandsgate'' stories to embarrass the late Labour leader John Smith, MP
for Monklands East in 1992.
Workers from the district building services department gave evidence to the
inquiry following claims that many got their jobs because they are members of
the Labour Party.
Mr Nimmo-Smith had said already that his own investigation uncovered only 10
party members from a workforce of 81 and seven of these had not been members
when they got their jobs.
Mr Raymond Queen, a glazier and a former member of the Labour Party, told the
inquiry he applied for his job after seeing it advertised in a newspaper. He
said that he believed he got the job on merit alone.
Witness Joseph McCaffery said he knew of no cases where there was any suspicion.
</TEXT>
