<HEADLINE>Queen Mother strolls through hip operation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339690</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Supported by sticks and pride: the Queen Mother at a Remembrance service last
week.    Picture:  PA
THE Queen Mother was recuperating last night after a total hip replacement
operation.
As a steady stream of flowers from well-wishers arrived at King Edward VII's
Hospital for Officers in London, Buckingham Palace declared that she was
``making a good recovery''.
The one-and-a-half-hour private operation was ``completed successfully''
yesterday morning and the Queen Mother is expected to remain in hospital for
about two weeks.
At 95, the Queen Mother is one of the oldest patients in the world to have
undergone the operation.
While the procedure is now considered routine, and has a 95% success rate, the
surgery and anaesthetic pose greater risks the older the patient is. The Queen
Mother expects a longer-than-average recovery period.
The operation comes at the end of a year when, despite suffering evident pain
and discomfort from her hip and leg, the Queen Mother has taken a central role
in national commemorations of the Second World War.
Her simple but moving speech opening May's VE-Day anniversary celebrations
emphasised her continuing place at the heart of the nation's affections.
Although visibly unsteady on her feet and suffering from the heat, she insisted
on taking full part in the hour-long ceremony.
The next day, crowds sang Congratulations to her as she appeared on the
Buckingham Palace balcony.
The Queen Mother's health has been remarkably robust for much of her long life,
and she has never let the physical ailments which come with advancing age daunt
her spirit.
Despite several health scares and a number of operations, she has always
delighted millions by returning to official engagements and meeting the public,
displaying an energy which would be envied by many younger people.
Just four months ago, she underwent a successful operation at the same
hospital, to remove a cataract from her left eye.
In recent months, she has relied on a walking stick or wheelchair, even
appearing in a golf buggy, nicknamed the Queen Mum-Mobile.
At her last public appearance, the annual Field of Remembrance Service at
Westminster Abbey a week ago, she walked with difficulty, using two sticks, and
had to be helped by the Duke of York when her turn came to plant a wooden cross.
She was not present at the Cenotaph on Sunday for the Remembrance Day Service.
The hip replacement, performed by Mr Roger Vickers assisted by Mr William
Muirhead-Allwood, is performed successfully on around 50,000 elderly people
each year.
It involves sawing off the head of the thigh bone and removing the surface
layer of the hip socket.
A metal ball and polyethylene socket are then cemented into place to form an
artificial joint.
Usually patients stay two or three weeks in hospital, but it can take three
months before they can walk unassisted and six months to a year before they
make a full recovery.
Routine post-operative checks on the Queen Mother yesterday were a ``success'',
said Buckingham Palace, which will issue daily bulletins on her progress.
The team of doctors and surgeons are remaining at the hospital and are on hand
if required.
Mr David Murray, consultant orthopaedic surgeon at the Nuffield Orthopaedic
Centre, Oxford, said: ``The operation often has a dramatic effect. Patients can
be suffering severe pain beforehand and afterwards find the pain has completely
gone.''
Asked if performing the operation on a patient as old as the Queen Mother was
risky, Mr Murray said: ``There is a risk from the operation and the older the
patient the bigger the risk.''
Lifetime of resilience - Page 8
</TEXT>
