<HEADLINE>Shock, horror closure rocks newspapers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339691</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE announcement by Rupert Murdoch's News International that the Today
newspaper will cease publication has set the newspaper world buzzing.
In an industry that lives off gossip and scandal, the rumour mill was working
overtime last night in the watering holes of what used to be ``Fleet Street''.
The new ``street'' now covers an area from the Daily Mail's Kensington
stronghold in West London to Canary Wharf in the east.
The favourite version of anticipated events was that Mr Murdoch was preparing
to seek a 20% stake in the ailing Express group which would involve the closure
of the group's Daily Star and a shift of operations to News International's
Wapping HQ.
Such intricate manoeuvering would reduce the possibility of any problems with
the Mergers and Monopoly Commission and boost the Express, which would then be
edited by Richard Scott from Today and become a pro-Labour paper.
Who knows? There would appear to be some logic to such a scenario and stranger
things have happened in Fleet Street in the past.
Certainly the Express is struggling and persistent rumour has it that
celebrated composer Sir Andrew Lloyd Webber is also interested in mounting a
rescue bid together with Tony O'Reilly, owner of Ireland's Independent
Newspaper Group, who also has a 43% stake in The Independent and Independent on
Sunday.
The Independent, which lost its editor Ian Hargreaves earlier this week, is
also in dire financial straits and with more heads set to roll there are
serious doubts as to whether it can retain its reputation as a quality paper
and indeed survive at all.
The recession, escalating newsprint prices, and the price war instigated by
News International in the summer of 1993 and which Mr Murdoch is only now
easing up on, have all served to transform newspaper publishing from the one
time ``license to print money'' to a precarious business which latterly has
seen papers come and go and others switch ownership.
The recent sale of Thomson International's five Scottish titles - the Scotsman,
Edinburgh Evening News, Scotland on Sunday, the Aberdeen Press and Journal and
Evening Express are an indication of a growing realignment of the industry.
Ownership of the British newspaper industry has tended to become more and more
concentrated in recent years, with about eight groups dominating the national
newspaper market, most of which are also diversifying into the broadcast and
electronic media.
After the Scandinavians and the developed Far Eastern nations, the British
still buy and read more newspapers than most, but there has still been a slow
though steadily increasing decline in the total circulation of our national
newspapers.
However, that has been almost exclusively in the popular section of the market,
with quality newspapers tending to hold their own or show overall growth in
recent years.
News International, the UK arm of Mr Murdoch's News Corporation which includes
global broadcasting, film, and publishing interests, is the biggest player with
its UK titles including the Sun, News of the World, Times, and Sunday Times
aggregating about 37% of national daily newspaper circulation and a slightly
larger slice of the Sunday market.
The Mirror Group, with its Daily and Sunday Mirror, Daily Record, the People,
and a 43% stake in the Independent and Independent on Sunday, tends to produce
somewhere in the region of 24% of national daily newspaper circulation and
around 30% of the Sundays.
The other big groupings include United News and Media - owners of the Express,
Sunday Express, and Star - and the Daily Mail and General Trust with its Daily
Mail, Mail on Sunday, and London Evening Standard. Both also have extensive
regional newspaper operations, the Mail's latest acquisition being Aberdeen's
Press and Journal.
Other major players include Hollinger, which owns the Daily and Sunday
Telegraphs, the Guardian Media Group - which includes the Guardian, the
Observer, and the Manchester Evening News - and the Pearson Group, which
publishes the Financial Times.
More re-alignment would appear inevitable.
