<TEXT>
MORE than two million people have already contemplated the situation faced
yesterday by Leah Betts' father and stepmother and entered their names on the
computer register of organ donors set up one year ago.
The UK Transplant Support Services Authority in Bristol currently has 2.2
million names on the list, with a further 100,000 applications waiting to be
processed.
This is apart from the unknown thousands - possibly millions - who have the
traditional donor card. There are thousands issued every year but how that
corresponds to the number of card-carrying donors at any one time can only be
guessed at.
Ms Katharyn Burdon, the authority's administration manager, said yesterday:
``All we can say is that there is always a desperate shortage of organs for
transplantation and we would like people to think very carefully about it and
talk about it.''
Against this, there are nearly 6000 people in the UK waiting for organs of one
sort or another, with only 2009 transplanted last year.
``Not everyone who registers is going to become a donor - it is usually the
result of an accident or brain haemorrhage,'' said Ms Burdon.
Registrations are growing steadily but it goes in peaks and troughs - a
particular event like the Transplant Games which were held in the UK this year
generates interest, then it might dip until something else happens.
Donor cards are to continue meantime but the ultimate aim is to have all
prospective donors on the register.
The majority of patients who get transplants are kidney patients, largely
because they can be kept alive for years with dialysis. Medical science can't
buy as much time for patients who need a heart or a liver.
Forms to join the register can be obtained from main Post Offices, on new
driving licences, or when changing or registering with a doctor. There is also
a Freephone number, 0800 555777, through which forms can be requested.
As with the donor cards, the computer register will not over-ride the wishes of
relatives who do not want the organ to be transplanted. The registration forms
allow people to specify which organs they wish to donate.
The number of lives which can be saved when one person dies grows steadily.
Last year there were 1173 kidney, 18 combined kidney and pancreas, 201 heart,
43 heart-lung, 88 lung, 477 liver, and nine pancreas transplants.
As at 30 September, however, there were 5065 patients waiting for kidneys, 311
for hearts, 171 for heart-lungs, 197 for lungs only, and 139 for livers.
</TEXT>
