<HEADLINE>PRODUCT OF THE WEEK Sovereign route to growth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339696</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PEP yielding 11.5% with the prospect of some capital growth sounds too good
to be true, yet this is precisely what is being offered by a new company,
Sovereign Debt Trust (SDT).
But before investors rush for their cheque books they should remember that
above average returns always mean above average risks - and this is the case
for SDT, which is sponsored by Greig Middleton.
SDT will be a kind of investment trust quoted in Dublin and will be launched
through an offer for subscription. As its name suggests it will invest in
government securities. This would normally be considered a safe investment but
in SDT's case it means securities issued by developing and emerging countries
with relatively poor credit ratings.
Half the portfolio will be invested in Brady Bonds, which were devised in 1989
by the then US Treasury Secretary James Brady to reduce the Third World debt
crisis. No country so far has defaulted on the Brady bonds it has issued. In
order to reduce risk the portfolio will be spread across 15 to 20 countries
Nevertheless the risk must be recognised, though it is arguably less than
investment in emerging-country equities. Should there be a downturn in world
trade then developing-country debt would tumble in value. In addition,
particular problems in a single country would unsettle the whole market. This
happened when Mexico had to be baled out by the US last year. So SDT is really
only of interest to larger investors, which is recognised in the #6000 minimum
investment.
The investment is PEPpable and dividends can be taken in cash or shares. Income
will be paid gross and if the share option is taken there is only liability for
capital gains tax          on disposal (for non PEP-investors). The gross
redemption yield is estimated at 14%.
The capital gain will come from a movement back towards par value by bonds as
they move towards maturity. Baring Asset Management will run the fund and it
believes that despite a recent recovery emerging country bonds are greatly
undervalued. The annual management charge is 0.95%.
</TEXT>
