<HEADLINE>PowerGen pleases the City</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339698</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACT FILE
Interim      1995       1994
Turnover #1104m #1137m
Pre-tax profits #133m #118m
EPS   13.4p 10.8p
Dividend 6.5p 5.0p
POWERGEN, the smaller of England and Wales' two electricity generators,
reported interim profits in line with City expectations at #133m before tax, an
increase of 13% on last year. Improved operating efficiency was the reason for
the improvment. Greater competition in its market meant its share slipped to
22.3% from 24.4%.
Commenting on the results, PowerGen's chairman, Sir Colin Southgate, said that
by any standards the financial performance in the first half had been very
strong and subject to unforeseen circumstances. ``Your directors expect 1995/96
to be another successful year for the company.''
PowerGen is awaiting Government clearance for its #1950m bid for Midlands
Electricity (MEB). The company sees no reason for a monopolies reference. Sir
Colin said this was because of the rapidly increasing competition in
generation, open and regulated access to the transmission network and
distribution networks, and the prospect of full nationwide competition in
supply. The de-regulated supply market in 1998 will also bring to an end the
main long-term deals between generators and regional electricity companies.
National Power, the biggest electricity generator, is also awaiting a decision
from the Government, expected next week, on its #2800m bid for Southern
Electric. PowerGen owns or has received acceptances for more than 70% of MEB.
The bid has been extended to November 24.
If the takeover is successful it is expected to boost PowerGen's earnings in
the current financial year. In addition, Sir Colin said it would position the
company for the full liberalisation of the electricity supply market in 1998.
and international markets.
Eastern Group, recently acquired by Hanson, has agreed to pay #450m for two of
PowerGen's power stations. The payments for a 99-year lease on the stations are
to be made annually over eight years and will be adjusted to reflect the actual
generation of the plant. The deal for the plants at High Marnham in
Nottinghamshire and Drakelow in Staffordshire is still subject to regulatory
approval.
</TEXT>
