<HEADLINE>A time for cool heads, judge advises jurors You are bound to feel the pressure, Mr Justice Mantell tells panel of seven men and four women</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339705</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JURY was yesterday advised that cool heads were required when the decision
was made on whether Rosemary West was guilty of murdering 10 young women and
girls.
No-one could pretend other than that the jury had a heavy responsibility, Mr
Justice Mantell told the seven men and four women as he began his summing up in
the seven-week trial.
The task was made all the more onerous because of the sensational nature of the
case and the considerable media interest surrounding it, he said. ``You are
bound to feel the pressure,'' the judge told the eleven jurors. A male juror
was excused earlier in the trial for an undisclosed reason.
Nevertheless, it was their duty to set aside any prejudice and preconceived
ideas.
He told the jurors they had to decide the case from what they had heard within
the courtroom and what they had seen during a visit to 25 Cromwell Street,
Gloucester. They should put out of their minds what they had read in
newspapers, heard on radio, or seen on television.
That, he said, would not be easy because the case had been reported extensively.
Mrs West pleads not guilty to 10 counts of murder, including that of her
daughter Heather, and stepdaughter Charmaine.
The judge said: ``Rosemary West is standing trial for murder. You are her
judges.''
He said it was his job simply to preside over the trial, tell them what the law
was, and remind them of the evidence.
On matters of law, they had to accept what he said and apply it. Each of the 10
charges of murder had to be considered separately, he told the jury.
It was suggested that the Wests had a system for enticing girls and young women
to 25 Cromwell Street so that they might be debauched and abused. If that
evidence was accepted by the jury, it would have a bearing on more than one of
the charges.
It was axiomatic of the English legal system that in a criminal charge the
prosecution must prove guilt. A defendant never had to prove his or her
innocence.
That was particularly important in a case such as the one being heard in Court
No 3 at Winchester where the defendant had given evidence and had called
evidence on her behalf.
The prosecution had to satisfy them beyond reasonable doubt and that applied to
each and every charge.
Mr Justice Mantell said that in certain circumstances it need not be just the
person who had delivered the fatal blow who was guilty of murder. Where two
people acted together to commit the offence, each was guilty, he continued. He
gave the example that if Mrs West enticed a girl into a car so that she was
rendered helpless and sexually abused as a prelude to being killed, Mrs West
would be guilty of murder even though the victim might have been ``dispatched''
by Frederick West.
Every charge came with the alternative of manslaughter, Mr Justice Mantell told
the jury.
However, in this case, what he said about that was theoretical.
He told the jury they may think that the person responsible for what happened
to the bodies of these young women, ``either before or, one would like to
think, immediately after death'' must have had murder in mind.
The question for jurors was whether in each case it had been proved that Mrs
West participated in the killings and, if so, was it with intention to murder.
Alternatively, if not, was it such to satisfy a charge of manslaughter.
Mr Justice Mantell occasionally emphasised a point by looking towards the jury
and asking: ``Do you understand that, members of the jury.''
Almost in unison they nodded their heads.
The judge said that, during the trial, he and the jury had had the advantage of
experienced and able counsel and this had made their task much easier than
might have been the case.
There had been a total absence of rancour and ill-temper.
In addition, he and the jury had the privilege of listening to two excellent
speeches. Mr Brian Leveson QC, for the Crown, had been analytical.
For the defence, Mr Richard Ferguson QC, had used a broader brush. ``The
difference between a Canaletto and a Van Gogh, you may think.''
At one stage during his summing up, Mr Justice Mantell suggested that Rosemary
West's remains had been recovered from Letter Box field.
Mr Leveson suggested that the judge had meant to say Rena West.
``What did I say?'' Mr Justice Mantell asked.
``Rosemary West, your lordship,'' said the Crown counsel.
The judge turned to a screen and declared: ``You are absolutely right - one of
the advantages of the computer.''
In the course of a review of the evidence, the judge said a key witness, Mrs
Janet Leach, who had been a confidante of Frederick West during several months
of police interviews, had been less than frank with them.
``Let's not mince words,'' he said. ``She lied to you.''
During her evidence, she had denied reaching agreement with the media over
money for her story. However, did that mean that her evidence about what Fred
West had said to her was not to be believed.
The judge also referred to the evidence of Mr West's daughter, Mrs Anne Marie
Davis. As with every other witness, they would have to consider whether or not
she was telling the truth.
Apologising to the jury, the judge said they would have to consider not only
the murders but the dissection of the bodies.
``You have to imagine cutting out kneecaps. . . a single rib. . . a collarbone.
. . fingers and toes, easier, perhaps,'' he said.
The Crown asked how could Mrs West have lived in the same house and not have
known.
Equally, Mr Ferguson, for the defence, could ask how could Anne Marie live in
the same house and not know, the judge said.
Mr Justice Mantell will continue his summing up today. The jury will retire to
consider verdicts on Monday.
</TEXT>
