<HEADLINE>Salmon crisis was avoidable</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339708</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S salmon farming industry now faces its biggest threat ever because of
UK Government intransigence.
The industry has for over four years advocated the establishment of producer
organisations in Norway, Scotland, and Ireland with full power to control the
number of young salmon put to sea matching supply with an anticipated demand.
This practical solution is provided for under the Common Fisheries Policy of
the European Union.
The present collapse of the market (reported on November 10) was as predictable
as it was inevitable. The huge increases of smolts to sea by Norway in 1994
guaranteed a glut by November 1995. Norway has now over 50,000 tons of salmon
for which there is no market and prices are at their lowest ever. There is
worse to come. Next year's Norwegian crop is bigger still - estimated at
390,000 tons against 260,000 this year.
The industry has warned the Scottish Office repeatedly for five years of the
inevitable market collapse which must follow massive over-supply, exactly as
happend in 1989-1992. It's first-year economics.
The new Minister, Raymond Robertson, like his predecessors, opposes the
measures necessary to stabilise the industry in the longer term. He speaks only
of short-term measures that in no way address the central problem of recurring
over-supply.
As a result he will bear responsibility for the issue of P45s to many of the
2500 men and women in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland working in the most
remote and vulnerable places, as well as the loss of the 5000 or more
additional jobs dependent on them.
There can be no more stark example of mis-government from London than the
persistent refusal of Scottish Office Ministers and Whitehall mandarins to heed
expert advice from the salmon farming industry. Any Scottish government would
do better.
Fergus Ewing,
SNP Business Spokesman,
52 Queen's Drive, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
