<HEADLINE>Cancer system `failing women' Screening is too little, too late, professor claims during lecture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339711</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
BREAST cancer screening and treatment is failing women because it arrives too
late and does not address the nature of the disease, it was claimed last night.
Professor Hugh Simpson, head of Glasgow University's pathology department, said
the whole approach of detecting and removing lumps had progressed little in the
last 150 years.
Delivering the prestigious Sir James Young Simpson memorial lecture at the
Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh, his distant kinsman appealed for
support for a new test for much earlier detection of the pre-cancerous
condition.
Professor Simpson said three out four women died within 10 years of diagnosis
of breast cancer in the UK. Those who survived treatment carried a 50% chance
of further cancer, six times the normal risk.
``There is widespread dismay and worry among women about the prevalence and
danger of breast cancer,'' he said.
``In essence, treating lumps is shutting the stable door after the horse has
bolted.
``Cancer does not grow in a normal breast and the other breast is not normal
either. The lump is the tip of iceberg. Breast cancer is just an isolated
effect in a diseased breast.''
He said that, although it may be too early to draw final conclusions, four
controlled trials had failed to show a significant reduction in mortality
between those who had undergone screening by mammography and those who had not.
Nor was mammography offered to women under 50, a group which accounted for one
third of breast cancer cases.
``What I am suggesting is a completely new test. In a way, it is a revolution.
There is particular room for improvement in the under-50s, for which there is
no early diagnosis,'' he said.
The test works on the principle that cancer almost invariably develops in and
around the milk ducts. Women undergo a rehearsal for lactation every month when
blood flow increases in the breasts.
Pre-cancerous abnormalities can be shown using a special heat-sensitive bra and
the equipment has already been tested by researchers in Glasgow and Manchester.
Those identified at risk can then be offered a range of treatment. Where
appropriate, they would be asked to lose weight, change diet by eating
oestrogen-blocking soya products associated with Japan and China, where breast
cancer rates were one sixth of the West, take Tamoxifen, the standard
anti-oestrogen drug, or even undergo preventive surgery.
Professor Simpson presented earlier findings to President Clinton's special
commission on breast cancer in America two years ago.
Addressing a distinguished body of surgeons last night marks a further degree
of acceptance of his theory.
He has also been invited to set up an international trial by the European
Institute of Cancer but so far has been unable to secure the necessary #100,000
funding.
``It is very controversial stuff but I think I am right. My main point is that
the people who have been critical have not examined the data,'' Professor
Simpson said.
</TEXT>
