<HEADLINE>Surgery cancelled as demand `peaks'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339713</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR heart operation was postponed this week at Aberdeen Royal Infirmary
because of pressures created by ``peaks'' of activity in the NHS trust
hospital's intensive care unit.
On a number of occasions last year, a similar situation arose when the flagship
hospital had peaks in demand.
Yesterday, a spokesman for the hospital confirmed it was in discussion with
Grampian Health Board in an effort to secure more funding to help cope with the
unit's problems.
``Obviously, we have to balance our resources,'' he said. ``You cannot always
have places for the worst possible peak. Grampian is the only rising population
in Scotland.
``We have a vast geographical area to look after, we have mountains which
attract both hill walkers and skiers. We have the offshore industry based in
Aberdeen, we have the biggest fishing industry in Europe based in Aberdeen, and
we have a lot of potential danger. These things put pressure on us.''
He added: ``We obviously cannot have a massive department with everyone
standing around just in case but at times we will have a peak of activity when
we will be overstretched.''
He said also that the unit's high-technology equipment meant that staff could
not be temporarily transfered, as in other wards.
The unit caters for 12 people, with four beds for cardiac surgery and eight for
general intensive care. The patient whose surgery was cancelled would probably
have the operation within a day or two.
Dr John Herne, medical director of Aberdeen Royal Hospitals Trust, said the
unit was ``more than full'' and this created problems, particularly with
elective surgery.
``I am sure any delay is an emotional burden on a patient,'' he said. ``In an
ideal world, it would not happen. However, we do not live in an ideal world but
one in which some compromises have to be made.
``If more money could be found to run this service it would make life easier
but the same is true in all parts of the health service,'' he said.
A health board spokesman said: ``We recognise the intensive care unit, like
other facilities, has to respond to peaks in demand. The continuing pattern of
use of intensive care unit beds is therefore kept under close review by the
board.''
</TEXT>
