<HEADLINE>Telegraph shares firm as cover prices rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339714</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES of Conrad Black's Telegraph group firmed 19p to 428p yesterday, helped
by cover price increases at Rupert Murdoch's Times, signalling what could be
the beginning of the end of the damaging newspaper cover price wars.
The buoyant share performance came despite a fall in Telegraph group profits
from #33.9m to #25.6m before tax in the nine months to September as the soaring
cost of newsprint offset extra revenue from the 5p rise in cover price to 35p
on July 3.
The third quarter did move into the black at the operating level after a loss
last year. But for the full nine months, after stripping out a one-off
first-half #7.5m contribution from the sale of the group's stake in Carlton
Communications, profits tumbled even further to #18.1m, of which almost #17m
(against #19.3m last time) came from interest in associated companies including
the 25%-owned Australian Fairfax operation.
On the plus side, though, the newspaper price wars, already cooled off, now
look to be coming to an end with the Times due to lift its price 5p in an
attempt to restore profitability.
It is not so much the price competition but newsprint and other costs which are
forcing a change of tactics by the news-paper magnates. Competition, though,
remains intense and the Telegraph group says it is committed to taking all
action necessary to protect its market leadership.
For the third quarter alone, operating profits were #500m compared with a loss
of #2.6m for the same period last year. This was despite a 30% rise in the cost
of newsprint on July 1.
Looking ahead to next year, although profit will be affected by rising
newsprint prices worldwide, the group says it is confident of maintaining the
circulation strength of its titles and of a steady growth in advertising in a
continuing competitive business environment.
Newspaper advertising revenue over the quarter rose 7% against the same period
last year. Classified remained strong, showing an 18% increase year-on-year.
However, financial and display advertising continued to perform disappointingly
with little change over the year.
The 12% decline in income from associated companies was largely due to the
weakness in the Australian economy coupled with increases in newsprint costs
both there and in Canada. The Telegraph also took a loss of around #900,000
from its share of asset disposals in Canada.
Circulation has stood up well. Average circulation for the Daily Telegraph in
the six months to September was 1,064,717, an increase of some 25,000 over the
same period last year and around 400,000 more than its nearest rival. In the
same period average circulation of the Sunday Telegraph was 696,964 though the
ending of the weekend voucher did have an adverse impact on sales, which dipped
to 673,540, still an increase of 11% over April 1994, the month before the
weekend voucher promotion was introduced.
With the appointment of Charles Moore as editor of the Daily Telegraph,
following the departure of Max Hastings to the London Evening Standard, and
Dominic Lawson's move from the Spectator to edit the Sunday Telegraph, there
will be a degree of rationalisation and attendant costs. The Telegraph group
reckons there are a few cost-savings still to be achieved but these will not
fully absorb the impact of further newsprint price increases expected in 1996.
But although the third quarter has been ``erratic'' in certain advertising
markets, there is some optimism, says the company, for the last quarter's peak
advertising months of October and November and newspaper advertising revenue is
expected to continue to outperform 1994.
q PROFITS of the Fairfax newspaper group in Australia, which includes the
Sydney Morning Herald, suffered from the upsurge in global newsprint prices,
falling a worse-than-expected 21% to A$33.8m net. Many analysts had been
expecting a drop in the region of 9%.
``The result reflects the impact of declining economic activity in Australia
and tougher trading conditions, combined with a very substantial rise in
newsprint costs.'' The price of newsprint jumped by 22% in the quarter.
</TEXT>
