<HEADLINE>Clarke finds rabbit in hat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339717</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Continued from Page 1
Clarke will, over the next few days, now concoct a Budget which will be
``prudent'' in terms of fiscal strategy and advantageous to the Government in
the run-up to the next General Election.
The Public Sector Borrowing Requirement in the first seven months of this
financial year was #4500m down on this time last year.
This is a vital figure for the nation's economic health and the Government's
survival over the next 12 months.
Mr Major can now truly ``smoke out'' the Labour Party on its economic strategy
in a way that this week's Queen's Speech legislation programme of 16 Bills
failed to do.
The good economic figures were unexpected by the City and, indeed, by Tory MPs
at Westminster. Mr Major, on this basis, can now demand total loyalty from his
back benchers on all issues that come before them in the legislative programme
for the next 12 months.
The Prime Minister and the Chancellor quickly had another private meeting about
the Budget strategy which is part of what the Tories might call their ``autumn
offensive'' against Mr Blair.
This was in danger of foundering until yesterday's economic figures. The
pressure will now fall on Mr Blair on November 28 when he has to respond to the
Budget statement in the Commons to produce a credible alternative economic
strategy.
THE Chancellor's Budget statement in 12 days' time was transformed yesterday by
a sparkling combination of economic figures.
Government borrowing is less than expected and the inflation rate is under
control. On November 28, this will give Kenneth Clarke scope for ``prudent''
tax cuts that will meet with the approval of the international markets.
The relief of Cabinet Ministers was obvious at Westminster. They now believe
that they have a serious opportunity to regain the initiative from Labour
leader Tony Blair, who is showing an unprecedented 40% lead over Mr Major in
public opinion polls.
The Cabinet now believes Mr Clarke can safely deliver about #3000m in tax cuts.
The inflation rate fell to 3.2% - the biggest October drop for 50 years. The
underlying rate, which excludes mortgage payments, fell too, from 3.1% to 2.9%.
Tory back benchers met for only five minutes at their weekly political meeting.
Afterwards those few who felt it necessary to attend were saying that this
could be the real turning point for the Government.
The pound recovered and shares went up - precisely the situation that the
Chancellor needs as a warm-up to his Budget statement.
A fall in interest rates is now a serious possibility before Christmas, to
encourage signs of a rebirth in High Street sales and to encourage consumer
confidence.
The key factor is the Government's borrowing requirement, which is also reduced
in yesterday's figures.
This combination provides the opportunity for which the Cabinet has been
waiting. They see a package capable of bringing back erstwhile Tory voters.
