<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339721</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACT FILE
1995       1994
NAV   48.85p 45.29p
EPS   3.06p 2.93p
Dividend 2.8p 2.75p
GLASGOW Income Trust provided a strong yield in the year to September 30, but
lagged behind the FTSE All-Share Index in total returns.
Gross dividend yield was 7.7%, beating a yield of 4.4% in the All-Share and
enabling the trust to reach its target of outperforming the index by 75%.
On the other hand, total returns on income and capital amounted to only 15.6%,
failing to keep pace with a 19.8% total return on the All-Share Index.
Net asset value rose 8% to 48.85p per share, while earnings per share to 3.06p.
A final dividend of 1p pushes the full-year payout to 2.8p.
Fund manager David Williams said a simple comparison between Glasgow Income
Trust investment returns and the All-Share returns was misleading - like
comparing ``apples and lemons''.
For instance, he noted that Convertible shares represent 27.4% of Glasgow
Income Trust's total assets, but are not represented in the All-Share Index.
The trust's total returns compare favourably with a more representative
benchmark consisting of a combination of the TOPSI-100 index of high-yielding
ordinary shares and the COSI-80 index of convertible securities, he said.
The trust's 15.6% total return was 0.6% higher than the return of this
composite index.
</TEXT>
