<BYLINE>Julie Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339722</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN elegiac walk through Tuscany. The season salutes the long decline of the
Italian summer in the colours of Tuscan clay, in brilliant versions of burnt
sienna and yellow ochre. The landscape of Ghirlandaio threads its vineyards and
olive groves through rich oakwoods, and we follow the ways of hunter-gatherers
as well as farmers.
The hills which in June are sunny with wheat and sunflowers are stripped to
their soil. In small, quiet ways farmers and their wives are shutting down the
land for the winter; beneath a hilltop hamlet a man rebinds his vine branches,
a woman with a sickle feeds a bonfire of dessicated maize stalks.
We are walking from the Etruscan redoubt of Volterra, a thrilling town on a
crag over 2000ft high, to the medieval masterpiece of Siena, about 45 miles
away. We walk alone; this is a journey for anti-social ramblers. We have no
guide, only the meticulously explicit route instructions of our tour operator,
Sherpa Expeditions, and some less than useful maps.
We don't walk the whole distance, but get a little help from local buses. The
country bus network has a wide and inexpensive remit.
An elegiac bus ride through Tuscany. As the APT coach potters peacefully from
one village to the next, we mourn the lost fortunes of our own rural bus
system. The journey is almost voluptuously nostalgic. The driver and his
regulars exchange friendly words and when we reach the precipitous suburbs of
Volterra there's a sudden flurry of custom. Three very old, very stiff couples
haul themselves on board for the stage to the town centre.
When we reach the Piazza XX Settembre the reason for their short journey
becomes clear: here, at a heavenly bus terminus overhanging medieval ramparts
and Etruscan gate, the elderly of Volterra take centre stage at its nightly
passeggiatta.
An elegiac stroll through the church of San Francesco. I get up early to
explore alone and, as the sun rises, find the open door of another church. It
holds the silence of six centuries, its treasures are unguarded.
Three days and two nights later, catching up with our luggage in friendly
hotels in San Gimignano and Colle Val d'Elsa, we break out of the oakwoods of
our final route and see on the horizon the great spear of the Torre del Mangia
and the bell-tower of Siena's cathedral.
The breath quickens. Between the rock of Volterra and the crowned hill of Siena
lies a landscape barely altered since medieval travellers lifted their eyes to
the same views and, like us, propelled themselves across it by their own
energy. The distances walked have not been great - about eight or nine miles a
day - but like hills the world over the Tuscan hills go up and down, and we're
quite happy to surrender the last lap to another local bus, as recommended.
The bus breasts a hill and the valley below delivers a peculiar shock: the
autostrada between Siena and Florence. Deep in our civilised wilderness of farm
tracks and forest paths and quiet country roads we have almost forgotten the
existence of motorways and their cargo of noise and speed.
But we enter a town which has most triumphantly banished the motor car from its
centro historico - the town which became a model for other Italian cities, and
which should be a model for ours. Siena showed it could be done. In the land of
the three-car family it prised its citizens from their steering wheels and
returned them to their feet; and now they drift contentedly through its
gorgeous brick-and-stone channels, rivers of pedestrians flowing into the
exquisite shell-shaped declavity of the Piazza del Campo.
An elegiac moment in the candystripe Duomo, where a little poem explains why so
many sceptical, Kirk-raised Protestants feel moved to light candles in Catholic
churches. It reads better in Italian, but my linguistically-gifted
sister-in-law provided this translation:
I don't know how to pray.
I don't know what to say.
I don't have much time.
Well then?
This light which I offer is a piece of my love,
a piece of my time, a piece of myself.
This light which shines will be my prayer,
which I will continue though I leave this place.
I light a candle in Siena's cathedral, one of many on my walk through Tuscany.
They were all dedicated to my mother, who died this month after a long twilight
of illness, and who was loved as much as any mother could be. She was in my
thoughts, or just behind them, every step of the way.
</TEXT>
