TELECOMMUNICATIONS
Cable &amp; Wireless
boosts interims
LORD Young, executive chairman of Cable &amp; Wireless, whose leadership of the
company has come under increasing criticism, has defiantly stated that he
intends to leave the international telecoms group, 80% owner of BT rival
Mercury, on his 65th birthday on February 27, 1997, writes CHRIS STONE.
He said in a statement that he was announcing the decision now ``in order to
end the recent ill-informed and destabilising comment and to put the record
straight.''
There has been increasing speculation that Lord Young was under pressure to
resign, a suggestion he recently described as ``absolute balderdash''.
Yesterday he unveiled a 9% increase in half-year profits ahead of exceptionals
from #567m to #616m on turnover up 7% at #2711m. Matching the profit advance,
shareholders are to receive a 9% boost in the interim dividend from 2.83p to
3.08p on earnings per share also up 9% ahead of exceptional profits at 13p.
Criticism of the company has centred on what has been perceived as its lack of
strategy but Lord Young commented: ``Progress continues to be made on all
fronts with financial performance our management focus on delivering consistent
and superior earnings growth.''
At home, Mercury increased turnover by 5% to #833m and operating profit
increased by 7% to #103m, reflecting the impact of reorganisation of the
business. Mercury revenues incorporate a 12% increase in switched minutes and
customer line growth of 38% partially offset by tariff reductions.
</TEXT>
