<HEADLINE>Apology urged for jobless</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339727</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday demanded an apology from Board of Trade President Ian Lang
after he described job insecurity as ``a state of mind''.
Shadow Trade Secretary Margaret Beckett said Mr Lang's comments were
``profoundly offensive'' to the millions of people who had real cause to fear
for their livelihoods.
However, Mr Lang said later that Labour was taking the remarks - made on
Tuesday during a news briefing at the CBI conference - ``completely out of
context.''
Mrs Beckett produced figures showing that 8.5 million people had experienced at
least one spell of unemployment since the Tories were re-elected in 1992.
``For all these people job insecurity is not just a state of mind, as Mr Lang
claimed. It is a grim and depressing reality,'' Mrs Beckett she said.
``Mr Lang should either apologise or he should resign.''
Mr Lang's comment previously had gone largely unremarked. He had told
journalists in response to their questions: ``Job insecurity does exist. What I
am saying is that job insecurity is a state of mind.''
A DTI spokesman said that Mr Lang was making the point that with unemployment
falling over the last year and 500,000 new jobs created since the recession,
the overall employment situation was not as bad as some people believed.
Mr Lang, on an official visit to Germany with the Prince of Wales, later issued
a statement strongly denying Labour's interpretation of his remarks.
``This is Labour playing politics again, taking a statement completely out of
context,'' he said.
``There is a serious issue to be addressed and that is how we create more jobs
in this country. That is the best way to deliver greater job security.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
