<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protest over `racial abuse' at barracks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339728</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR last night urged Defence Secretary Michael Portillo to look into
allegations that the black wife of a British soldier was subjected to racial
abuse at a barracks social evening.
The alleged incident is being investigated by military authorities.
Shadow Defence Secretary Dr David Clark outlined details of the case as he
wound up for Labour on the second day's debate on the Queen's Speech.
Dr Clark said two black women, one of them married to a soldier posted
elsewhere, attended a social event on August 10 at Oakington Barracks,
Cambridge.
``The women were subjected to racial abuse, which included persistent chants of
`nigger, nigger, nigger'.
``At a later stage in the evening, the soldier who had been perpetrating most
of the abuse had disappeared, and he came back with four other soldiers,
witnesses allege, and subjected the women to further abuse, such as: `You
niggers are only good for swinging from trees and burning, if I had my way I
would get a white hood.'''
Dr Clark said he would not subject MPs to further examples of the taunts.
``The House will share my anger and concern. But to make it worse, as the two
women were leaving, two of the soldiers pointed guns at the by now petrified
women.
``I will say no more. I understand this is an exception. But plainly, such
occurrences have no place in our civil society, nor any place at all in the
British armed forces.
``Events such as this really must be stamped out.''
When he replied to he debate later, Mr Portillo did not respond on the case.
</TEXT>
