<HEADLINE>Health scare workers return</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339729</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHEMICALS used in making men's trousers were thought yesterday to be the
initial cause of health complaints which made workers vacate the Daks-Simpson
factory at Polbeth, West Lothian, this week.
As the 365 workers returned to their jobs after a two-day stoppage, a Health
and Safety Executive spokesman said investigations had shown the likeliest
reason for skin rashes and nausea, experienced by some, was surface irritants
in the fabrics.
These were chemicals used to reduce creasing and retard fire. Guidance had been
given to the company.
HSE officials were carrying out further work to see if the irritants could be
reduced but it agreed there was no serious health risk.
The spokesman said it was believed the chemicals had triggered the trouble
although other factors, such as outside ailments and anxiety, could then have
developed.
Yesterday, a statement from Daks-Simpson at Larkhall, Lanarkshire - which
experienced a similar incident last week - said workers had been told tests had
been carried out and nothing had been found to cause concern.
The Polbeth factory had been cleaned thoroughly throughout Wednesday and
over-night, and the employees were advised they could return safely.
Mr Kevin Johnson, managing director, said: ``Hopefully, the matter is now
behind Daks-Simpson in Scotland and we are all looking forward to getting back
to normal.''
</TEXT>
