<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>two strokes and even fewer rivals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339730</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the early Sixties it seemed incredible that Erik Carlsson and his two-stroke
Saab could win the RAC Rally three times in a row, and the Monte Carlo twice.
Handicaps and overall places decided on class performance were being phased
out, and the RAC Rallies of 1961 and 1962 were scratch events, decided on
flat-out forest stages.
Carlsson won going away from the field. And yet his 841cc Saab 96 peaked at
something like 75bhp, compared with the 210bhp of the Austin-Healey 3000s which
had almost three and a half times its engine capacity. Brilliant driving was
the major element in Carlsson's victories, but the two-stroke Saab was a car to
marvel at.
The most accomplished driver of a similar car in Britain was Alastair
Robertson, who prepared one for rallies in 1967. He placed it in the top three
of the Scottish championship and regularly outpaced the opposition in the
Saab's capacity class.
The Saab was usually thought of as a forest or winter rally car, but Alastair
Robertson was also an ace on smoother surfaces, as he showed on the all-tarmac
Circuit of Ireland, when he managed to wear the rear tyres of this front-wheel
drive car completely bald!
He recalls that the 96 may have been short of power on the climbs, but it could
be driven absolutely flat-out downhill. The Scandinavians who gave the Saab its
rally baptism devised the technique of left-foot braking.
Some of us think we remember the little two-stroke engine screaming to nearly
9000rpm. In fact, it would hit six-five or seven, and the characteristic
``whoop'' as it revved up was caused by the opened-up air cleaner on the
competition cars.
After the two-stroke went out of production, Alastair Robertson moved on to
rallying a Saab V4. Ten years later, his two-stroke was found languishing in
Dundee, and he bought it back.
He rebuilt it as a Monte Carlo model, and put in one final nostalgic entry for
the Trossachs Rally in 1979. Then it retired. However, if a suitable historic
rally turned up, with forest stages, he might be tempted to put its competition
numbers on again. He would never say so himself, but that would be something to
behold - a classic rally car of the Sixties with a genuine expert back at the
wheel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blow to Forsyth battle against home rule as Scottish business switches sides Firms no longer fear devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339731</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE has been a sea change in the attitude of the business community towards
home rule, according to a survey to be published next week by the Scottish
Chambers of Commerce.
The results of the survey of more than 3000 firms will be a body blow to the
fierce campaign against constitutional change being waged by Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth.
Business and commerce traditionally has been seen as hostile to the idea of a
Scottish parliament, but the acting director general of Scottish Chambers, Mr
Peter Dunn, indicated that there had been a shift in attitudes.
``The result of this survey will shake the very foundations of current thinking
on the devolution issue,'' he said, adding: ``There has been an immense change
in the last two or three years''.
This shift comes as Mr Forsyth looks at ways of undermining the demand for
change. He will deliver a lecture on St Andrew's Day, the same day that the
Scottish Constitutional Convention stages the formal launch of its proposals
for a 129-member Parliament.
Ironically, the Scottish Secretary's anti-Labour message will come in a lecture
commemorating one of the party's great stalwarts, former Strathclyde Regional
Council leader Dick Stewart.
The Scottish Local Authorities Management Centre at Strathclyde University
organises the lecture and this year it invited Mr Forsyth to speak, and he
chose the date to coincide with the Convention's big day.
Privately, senior Labour figures are furious at such a propaganda coup being
handed to the Scottish Secretary. ``Dick will be birling in his grave,'' one
source said.
Now Mr Forsyth will have to contend with the evidence that business people are
warming to the idea of devolution. The survey was carried out on behalf of the
Scottish Chambers and law firm Maclay Murray &amp; Spens by the Fraser of Allander
Institute at Strathclyde University.
The Scottish Chambers last carried out a survey in 1991 and at that time 67%
supported no constitutional change, with only 28% opting for a Scottish
parliament. This will provide a benchmark for the latest findings.
Mr Dunn called the results ``dynamite'' and said that personally he was not
afraid of devolution because he had spent recent months educating himself about
the issue. He said of the survey: ``This will stimulate the business community
into a full and frank discusion on the implications of devolution for Scotland.
It is time to talk.''
The survey asked how proposed changes compared with the status quo, citing as
four possibilities - decentralisation of decision making; a devolved
legislature without taxation powers; a devolved legislature including tax
powers; and independence.
The firms were asked whether change would make the business environment better
or worse, or leave it unchanged. The questions were also couched in terms of
short-term and long-term impact, and their effect on operating costs, turnover
and growth.
The results will be released in Glasgow next Tuesday and the indications are
that they will be encouraging for the Labour and Liberal Democrat Convention
partners.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said: ``Scottish business is now
more and more coming round to the idea of a Scottish parliament, despite the
most hysterical and vitriolic anti-devolution campaign ever mounted by the
Tories.
``Clearly Scottish business doesn't buy the Tory propaganda. Neither should the
rest of the Scottish people. The power to get our economy working means getting
the lifeblood pumping through our industries and businesses, but you cannot do
this when the heart that is pumping is 500 miles away in London.
``That is why a Scottish parliament will be good for Scottish business.''
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said: ``I warmly welcome the news
that Scottish business people are willing to embrace home rule. A Scottish
parliament will bring massive opportunities for Scottish businesses and provide
a much more beneficial regime than presently exists.
``Michael Forsyth's scaremongering seems to have had no effect. Scottish
business people are unlikely to be convinced by lies and misrepresentation. We
will continue to talk to the business community in the coming months to
convince them of the merits of a Scottish Parliament.
Tories remained understandably sceptical. Scottish Conservative vice-chairman
Jackson Carlaw said: ``Obviously, we await the outcome of the survey with
interest, although it is fairly typical that the alleged conclusions have
become public knowledge before the survey itself.
``What businessmen must realise, and I count myself as one of them, is that if
Labour were to win a General Election then we would have a tax-raising
Parliament. That is their policy. Like it or not, we would have to accept that
outcome.
``The crucial question must be do businesses believe that a tax-raising
parliament will make Scotland more competititive or less? Will it make Scotland
more prosperous or less? Will it result in more inward investment or less?
``This week has seen the biggest inward investment in the UK's history come to
Scotland. Are the bosses of Chunghwa keen to pay their 3000 potential employees
more money to make up for the extra tax burden?''
Scottish Tory Party chairman Sir Michael Hirst also referred to this weeks
Lanarkshire jobs boost. During a visit to Dumfries he said: ``Despite this
delightful news and other recent inward investment successes for Scotland, our
political opponents are still hell-bent on constitutional proposals that would
put this all at risk.''
SNP chief executive Michael Russell said the party looked forward to seeing the
results because if business people were shifting away from supporting the
status quo it was only a matter of time before they realised the benefits of
independence in Europe.
He said: ``This completely blows a hole in the argument that Scottish business
is standing firm against any change. If they begin to countenance change, then
this opens the door to our proposals. Some business people now see independence
as akin to a management buy-out.
</TEXT>
