<HEADLINE>No Fiesta for Ford as strikes hit plants</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339732</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNOFFICIAL action by several thousand workers at Ford's Dagenham car plant in
Essex and Transit van works in Southampton yesterday in protest at the
company's ``final'' pay offer marred the launch of the company's new Fiesta.
Dagenham workers took immediate unofficial strike action yesterday on hearing
that the company's ``final'' pay offer fell well short of their 10% demand and
included no reference to reduced hours.
Production of around 60 Transit vans was lost at Southampton.
A full shift's production of 800 new Fiestas, the first of which went on sale
yesterday, was lost.
Normal production is expected to resume today and a more considered reaction to
the offer - worth 4.75% from the end of next week and a further 4.5% or the
then rate of inflation plus 0.5%, whichever is the greater, next November -
should emerge on Wednesday.
Ford said it was disappointed with the action and urged workers at both plants
to return to normal working.
Meanwhile, unions yesterday began consulting Ford's 22,000 manual workers on
the offer ahead of a special delegate meeting next Wednesday.
Mr Tony Woodley, national officer of the TGWU, chairman of the union side,
said: ``While we recognise that the company has at last offered our members a
real but small increase in their standard of living, it still fails to make up
for the drift in Ford workers' pay within the motor industry in recent years.''
q Vauxhall car workers are voting on whether to take industrial action over
the company's offer of a 3.5% increase now and a similar rise next year, with
the ballot result due on Monday.
