<HEADLINE>Britain `loses' #136m in EU funding</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339733</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN has lost #136m in European Union subsidies because of mismanagement by
the Government. Most of the money represents a windfall profit from the pound's
forced exit from the European Exchange Rate Mechanism on Black Wednesday of
1992.
Because the Government had not anticipated receiving the extra money from the
European social fund it could not find projects for funding on time. Such
projects specify help for the unemployed. As a result, the European Commission
cancelled payments.
The disclosure will greatly embarrass Ministers who are proclaiming Britain's
leadership in the fight against EU waste and mismanagement.
Details of the loss were included earlier this week in the EU's Court of
Auditors report. The passage on the UK's use of social fund money went largely
unnoticed because, it was assumed, the money could simply have been carried
forward for a year and reclaimed.
Two years ago, doubts were raised about the money being lost. The Government
denied that anything was wrong.
However, last night a Government spokesman admitted that it appeared to be gone
for good. ``The extra money which came our way was not spent and it was not
carried forward,'' he said, adding that the matter was still being discussed in
London.
The pound was blown out of the ERM in September 1992, after a desperate fight
by John Major and the then Chancellor, Norman Lamont, to save it ended in
failure and acrimonious exchanges with the Germans and vilification of
speculators. Mr Lamont later resigned and Mr Major came close to losing his job.
The upside was that Britain stood to gain hugely from the fact that Brussels
subsidies to the UK - a major recipient of EU social funding - are paid in
Ecus, the European currency unit which is the official but non-existent coin of
Brussels in all its dealings.
When the money was paid for the 1990-93 period Britain received enough Ecus to
provide an extra #136m in sterling, reflecting a drop in the value of the pound
of up to 20%.
To qualify for the money Britain had to promote special programmes mainly
involving training and help for the unemployed. The aid had also to be spent
within specific periods.
However, at the end of 1993 the rules were changed as the social fund swelled.
A rule stating that unspent or unclaimed money could simply be carried over was
altered.
</TEXT>
