<HEADLINE>`Green Card' obsession led to `humiliated' Chinese intellectual killing his wife Marriage plot led to killing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339734</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CHINESE woman's obsession with an arranged marriage of convenience to allow
her to stay in Britain turned to tragedy after she began an affair with the man
who was to be part of the plot, a court heard.
Fan Hong was strangled by her husband Gang Zhao after he found her kissing her
lover at a railway station.
Zhao's upbringing during the Chinese revolution, which was said to mirror that
of the bestselling book The Wild Swans, meant his marriage was all the more
precious to him, said Mr Stephen Coward, QC, defending.
Mr Philip Matthews, prosecuting said Zhao, 37, was studying a post-graduate
degree in English at Luton University.
It was always his intention to return to China, where he would have almost
certainly become a professor.
His 33-year-old wife and nine-year-old son, Zutian, joined him in September
last year and they lived in a house in Biscot Road, Luton.
However, Mr Coward said their problems began after they watched the film Green
Card over Christmas last year.
``His wife became obsessed with wanting to stay in England. She loved it here.
``The film was about a marriage of convenience and she came up with the idea
that they could divorce and each marry an English person, then after a short
time divorce their new partners and remarry, each then having the status to
remain in England.'' said the defence.
Mr Coward said Zhao went along with the plan to keep his wife happy, even to
the extent of going to the Chinese Embassy to set in motion their divorce.
One potential ``husband'' for Fan Hong was Robert King, who lived in in the
same building.
Mr Matthews said: ``By February this year, she was seeing Mr King on a daily
basis. Zhao discovered they had been alone in the bedroom together and drew
conclusions from that.
``He confronted Mr King about it and he apologised.''
The prosecutor said it seemed the affair was over and Fan Hong began working as
a waitress at a Chinese restaurant in Harpenden.
On April 2, Zhao and their son turned up when she finished work to take her on
a suprise family picnic.
``She had left for the railway station and when Zhao got there he saw her and
Mr King kissing.
``There were some ructions and blows were exchanged,'' said Mr Matthews.
During the night of April 3, Zhao strangled his wife with a cord, the court was
told.
The following morning he took his son with him to Luton police station and told
the civilian on duty: ``I have murdered my wife. She has been having an affair
with an Englishman and I have found out.''
When police went to the bed sit, they found her partly clothed body and a note
written by Zhao.
It said: ``Robert King living upstairs seduced my dear, lovely wife by
hypocritically promising to help her to become a resident with a marriage of
convenience.
``I love my wife dearly and cannot bear knowing of her sleeping with another
man.
``I totally repent what I have done but it is too late.
``I am sending my son home, whom I love more than anything. I hate Robert King,
he ruined my family.''
Zhao denied the murder of his wife but pleaded guilty to her manslaughter on
the grounds of diminished responsibility.
He was jailed for three years and has promised to return to China on his
release.
Mr Justice Hooper said he would not officially be deported ``because of the
possible adverse consequences that may have upon his return''.
Three psychiatrists said in reports that Zhao was clinically depressed at the
time due to his marital circumstances.
One said events at the railway station were ``humiliating and threatening` and
that something must have been said in the room ``to cause the worm to turn''.
Mr Coward said when Fan Hong became friendly with Mr King: ``She never
contemplated becoming emotionally or sexually involved.
``But when she did she became torn as to what to do for the best.''
He said Zhao's promising life was in ruins.
``When he returns to China he will be personna non grata because he will have
been deemed to have been an ambassador while in this country.
``His son is living with his wife's family and they will not allow him any
contact with the boy.''
Mr Coward said Zhao's family were ``politically significant'' and during the
revolution were ``ritually humiliated''.
He was nine when the revolution began and his brilliant university career did
not start until the end of the revolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
