<HEADLINE>A fight to the finish</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339735</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scotland's Colin McRae
could win the World
Rally Championship next
week, says Ross Finlay
UNLIKE the Formula One championship, the winner of which was known before last
weekend's Australian Grand Prix, the World Rally Championship comes to a
fighting finish on the Network Q RAC Rally, starting on Sunday from Chester.
Two drivers share the championship lead. The title will be decided on this
final round, and at the end of it we might have the first-ever Scottish world
rally champion.
Towards the end of last month's Catalunya Rally in Spain there was an
over-wrought atmosphere within the Prodrive Subaru team when orders were given
for Colin McRae to pick up deliberate time penalties, so as to allow his
Spanish team leader Carlos Sainz back into first place, thus winning his home
event, with McRae second. But it was revealed soon afterwards that Sainz had
already signed to join a rival team after the RAC Rally. His ``sweetener''
victory came too late.
The result is that McRae and Sainz start the RAC Rally on Sunday from Chester
exactly level on championship points. Nothing is certain in rallying, and there
is always the possibility that, although Sainz has won the rally twice in the
past, and McRae once, neither of them may score additional points this time.
If that happens, Sainz will be the champion, because the tie-break system
favours whoever has scored more individual event victories during the season.
When McRae deferred to Sainz, that not only put them level on points, it also
gave Sainz three wins this season so far - to McRae's one.
Although the Subaru drivers start favourites, and one of them must win the
driver's title, the team leading the manufacturers' championship, by a
wafer-thin margin, is Mitsubishi, whose efforts are directed by another Scot,
Andrew Cowan.
The other principal team involved, Toyota Team Europe, has been bundled out of
this year's championship after being caught cheating on the Catalunya. The
power of an engine rises with the amount of air forced into it, and, to keep
power outputs with in reasonable limits, world championship cars must be fitted
with an exactly-sized air restrictor. TTE's cars in Spain used tampered-with
turbochargers which by-passed the restrictor.
Sunday's 28 miles of stages, between Chester and Leeds, are in parkland and the
grounds of stately homes. They are less ``Mickey Mouse'' than in the past, even
though the fixation about providing car-damaging water-splashes just for the
benefit of the TV cameras may persist. Monday is when the real action starts.
Clerk of the course Fred Gallagher, who lives in Edinburgh and is himself a
rally co-driver of immense experience, has designed a Monday morning to
remember. His 37-mile stage at Pundershaw in Kielder Forest is worth all the
parkland stages in creation. Soon after that, the cars still in the running
cross the border for the only two stages in Scotland. Details in the motorsport
diary.
While the RAC Rally is not run on biblical lines, there is almost an element,
as on all world championship rounds, of the first being last and the last being
first. The Subaru Impreza of Colin McRae and his co-driver Derek Ringer, for
instance, has carried competition number four throughout the season, but will
leave Chester first because they won the RAC Rally last year.
Another Scottish co-driver, Robert Reid, partners Richard Burns in Subaru
number six, which will start ninth. And Alister McRae, winner of the Mobil
1/Top Gear series, the top UK rally championship this year, drives a Ford
Escort Cosworth numbered 44 but leaving 14th. His car is prepared by Malcolm
Wilson, but is heavily supported by Ford.
Confusing the issue still further, the convoy is occasionally re-seeded,
according to drivers' positions on accumulated stage times at certain
pre-arranged points. One Scottish driver given a notable present in time for
the RAC is Robbie Head. His factory-backed Renault Clio Maxi is in the
two-litre Formula Two category, whose cars are less powerful than the full
world championship entries. The Renault now has 270bhp on tap, instead of the
220bhp available before. Engine-tuning experience from the British Touring Car
Championship Lagunas, and a rally programme in France, makes the difference.
The 190-strong entry list includes a good selection of other Scottish-based
drivers. Dom Buckley drives a Mitsubishi Lancer. Brian Lyall, John Baird,
George Gauld, Gordon Smith, Malloch Nicoll and Sandy Dalgarno are in Escorts,
while Red Barry has entered a Suzuki Swift.
These private entrants will be battling for class and category awards rather
than being able to match the works teams' times, although they will give one of
the toughest rallies in Europe their best shot. Though preoccupied with their
own adventures, they will no doubt find time to give Colin McRae at least moral
support.
The McRaes - Colin, Alister and their father Jim, himself a British champion -
form a unique rallying dynasty. Jim is the number two seed in the Miller Oils
Historic RAC Rally, which tackles a series of Yorkshire forests tomorrow,
before the main rally begins, as well as all but one of the Sunday stages.
His car is a Porsche 911, like the one driven by the number one seed in the
historic event, Ake Andersson from Sweden.
Andersson pipped McRae senior for first place last year, and you may be sure
that it is not just the youngsters in the family who will be determined to
outpace their rivals.
</TEXT>
