<HEADLINE>EU commissioner looks at Scots aid amid concerns over funding review</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339736</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING European Union decision-maker arrived in Edinburgh yesterday amid
rumours and concerns that European aid to large parts of Scotland could be in
jeopardy because of a forthcoming coming review of structural funds.
However, EU Regional Commissioner Mrs Monika Wulf-Mathies insisted that no
decisions had yet been taken over setting the new criteria for distributing
such funding.
She had come on her first visit to Scotland to see for herself how the EU money
was being spent in areas such as Niddrie and Craigmillar in Edinburgh, West
Lothian and Tayside.
Today, she will address the annual conference of the East of Scotland European
Consortium in Edinburgh.
Asked if Scotland should be worried over the review, Mrs Wulf-Mathies said she
did not think major changes of funding for Scotland would come in the 1995-1999
period, but she did not want to close the debate before it had started.
The country's economic performance had been quite good but she was well aware
that there still were parts which were very deprived.
However, she believed a review of the criteria for gaining Objective 2 status
was necessary. The results would be announced in the early spring.
Lothians Labour Euro-MP David Martin, who accompanied the commissioner on her
tour of the Edinburgh area, said he believed Scotland did have something to
fear.
Even on the present criteria, Scotland would be in danger of losing its
eligibility in some areas.
For example Niddrie/Craigmillar only had qualified for funding in the 1994
programme. It would be very damaging if the area now dropped out again.
The same could be said for places like former mining village Newtongrange,
which the commissioner visited. Midlothian only had received funding about five
years ago.
Mr Martin said: ``We don't want new areas which are using the money well
suddenly finding that halfway through the programme they are not going to have
European funding.''
He said the East of Scotland was due to receive about #100m up to 1999.
Asked about the recently reported loss by the EU of #400m through fraud, Mrs
Wulf-Mathies said this had not been related to the structural funds.
The new commission had changed its attitude to financial management and towards
the fight against fraud. It was very anxious to improve its financial
performance.
</TEXT>
