<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Four arrested in dawn raids</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339737</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETECTIVES investigating the killing of schoolgirl Naomi Smith arrested four
people in a series of dawn raids yesterday.
Naomi, 15, was stabbed and sexually assaulted before being dumped under a slide
at a recreation ground just 200 yards from her home in Ansley Common, near
Nuneaton, Warwickshire, on September 14.
Her body was discovered by her father, Brian, and Emma Jones, her best friend.
Officers visited 15 addresses in Ansley Common and Nuneaton at around 6.30am
yesterday. An unspecified number of people were helping with inquiries at
police stations in Nuneaton, Bedworth, Atherstone, and Rugby.
None of those arrested yesterday was among the five people previously detained
in connection with the inquiry and later released.
Last month, detectives began DNA tests on more than 800 men aged 15 to 28
living in and around the Warwickshire village.
They warned that anyone who persistently failed to volunteer for testing would
be likely to become the focus of inquiries.
Detective Superintendent Tony Bayliss said police had been able to obtain a DNA
profile of Naomi's killer.
There was no indication whether yesterday's raids, described as a major police
operation, resulted from the DNA testing programme.
Police decided to target young men on the advice of a forensic psychologist who
drew up an offender profile.
The inquiry team have interviewed more than 1800 people and obtained witness
statements from more than 400.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour `will reverse nursery voucher plan'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339738</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office was accused yesterday of ``using four-year-olds like
political footballs'' as Labour's Scottish Education spokeswoman Helen Liddell
promised to reverse the plans for nursery vouchers to be implemented in a new
Education Bill.
She said Labour would reverse the policy in government and Labour councils
would agree to pilot schemes only ``under the strictest of conditions,''
although she feared that ``a devious and panic-stricken Government'' would go
over the heads of opposed councillors and implement them anyway.
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said the backlog on school repairs
had now reached #500m.
Teachers and pupils throughout Scotland were ``having to endure decaying
classrooms and are clamouring for extensions or repairs.''
The Scottish Office has not yet named a date for the Education Bill's
introduction or whether it will begin in the Commons or the Lords.
In a letter to Education Minister Raymond Robertson, Mrs Liddell acused the
Government of rushing the schemes in Ministers' panic preparation for an
election.
She asked: ``Have you no concern for the education and emotional development of
the four year olds you intend using as political footballs?''
Calling the voucher exercise ``a charade'' she pointed out that only 16% of
those who responded to the Government's consultation exercise supported
vouchers.
Mr Wallace said his party was ``wholly sceptical'' about vouchers and issued a
list of outstanding education repairs in the Scottish regions and islands to
back its pledge to spend an extra #55m on education capital spending.
The list shows: Strathclyde #142m, Borders #9.4m, Lothian #69m, Central #92.2m,
Tayside #25m, Fife #36m, Dumfries and Galloway #15m-#20m, Highland #34m,
Grampian #72m and Orkney #300,000.
q Mr Robertson last night lost patience with the union which formerly
represented him over the issue of nursery vouchers (writes Barclay McBain).
The Educational Institute of Scotland, to which Mr Robertson belonged when he
was a teacher, was on the receiving end of a furious attack from the Minister.
The union's deputy general secretary, Mr Fred Forrester, said vouchers were
unacceptable in principle, unworkable, and amounted to no more than a political
ploy to avoid major expenditure on pre-schooling ahead of the General Election.
However, Mr Robertson said it was ``absurd, illogical, and desperate'' for the
EIS to accuse the Government of stalling to save money.
</TEXT>
