<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Icy atmosphere as the Pirates row over rent</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339740</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TALE of pirates unfolded yesterday in the unlikely setting of Paisley, with
protagonists crossing swords with accusations of eviction and blackmail.
It began with the Paisley Pirates Russian ice hockey player Alex Koulekov
claiming that he had been forced from his three-bedroom home after the club
failed to pay his rent.
The player, his wife, Galina, and nine-year-old son Vitalik, are now sharing a
hotel room after claiming they had been given just 48 hours to leave their flat
in the town's Grahamston Court amid claims that the club had consistently
failed to pay rent for the premises on
Last night, however, Paisley Pirates' coach Martin Shields denied that the
family had been evicted because of any cash wrangle, admitting only that the
club and the player's landlord had ``fallen out''.
He said: ``We agreed with the people who had the flat that it would be best for
both parties if we terminated the lease. I am not prepared to go into any
detail.''
Mr Shields said he had shown the Koulekovs a luxury bungalow on Monday but they
had refused to pay an extra #48 a month on top of the #350 a month rent the
club has an agreement with the player to pay.
The next thing Mr Shields knew, the player had been quoted in the local paper,
claiming he and his family were being forced to live in a hotel room with all
their belongings.
``We don't understand what is happening to us. We don't know why the Paisley
Pirates are treating us this way. We had to leave our home and our friends.
We're shattered,'' Mr Koulekov, 40, told the local paper.
Mr Shields said: ``I feel gutted and annoyed at the stand Alex has taken. He is
our fourth import and not a regular player in the team. However, he is on #600
a week.''
``All he pays for is his gas, his electricity, and his phone. The bottom line
is that we will not be blackmailed and held to ransom. He is not hard done to
and knew the situation on Monday.''
The Pirates, who were established three years ago, play in British Division One
and regularly attract crowds of more than 1000.
The couple who rented their home to the Russians confirmed last night that they
had been forced to seek legal advice and end the leasing agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Portillo's stance on Europe comes under fresh attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339741</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHADOW Foreign Secretary Robin Cook last night launched the angriest attack so
far on the Government over its foreign policy and the proposals contained in
the Queen's Speech. He said the Government was bankrupt and broken-backed.
On the second day of debate on the Government's plans for the forthcoming
session of Parliament, he targeted, in particular, the stance on Europe and the
``jingoism'' shown by Defence Secretary Michael Portillo in his speech to the
Tory conference last month.
Mr Cook said: ``Since the Queen's Speech is so slim on ideas, so thin on new
initiatives, so irrelevant to the real problems of Britain, any further Queen's
Speech from this administration will set new standards in minimalist literature.
``The best feature about this debate is that the next time it may be a Labour
Queen's Speech. That will put Britain on the road towards a competitive
economy, based not on exploitation of low wages but investment in high skills.''
He pledged Labour to the Social Chapter, and said: Labour would seek alliances
and partnerships within the international community, rather than see Britain
standing alone.
In his attack on Mr Portillo, Mr Cook condemned his attitude to Europe,
focusing on the Defence Secretary's strong rejection of a European army.
Mr Portillo in a speech yesterday, derided the concept of a single European
army, and declared that Britain would never be told by Brussels when to fight
and when not to fight.
In an outspoken address to a high-powered conference on future British
security, he criticised European federalists' aspirations for a common defence
policy, warning that Nato would be weakened and enemies could foolishly decide
to attack.
Mr Cook said that Mr Portillo's ``exceedingly ungracious'' speech to the party
conference sounded depressing in the original English, but must have sounded
frightful in German. ``Your jingoism had its day 100 years ago. It is a
positive menace in the modern world.''
Earlier, Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said few MPs doubted that the future
of the United Kingdom lay in the EU.
However, he added: ``Beyond that basic premise lies the question of what sort
of Europe we want, what sort of Europe is right for Britain.''
The Foreign Secretary said: ``We will be motivated by the interests of the UK.
``This is not a matter of blinkered self-interest. It is a matter of the
Government's inescapable obligation to its own people and it is a reflection of
the principle that a voluntary association will not prosper unless it balances
the interests of all its members.
``While recognising the benefits that the EU continues to bring to us, we also
want to make it work better.''
Mr Menzies Campbell, for Liberal Democrats, said that at at the EU
intergovernmental conference next year the Government should reaffirm that the
UK was at the heart of Europe.``We should declare it is our intention to join a
single European currency, if one is created, if the financial criteria are met.
Winding up the debate later, Mr Portillo promised that Britain would use its
presidency of the Western European Union to build defence structures that
worked.
Defence was first the responsibility of a sovereign nation, he insisted. ``We
will not meet the challenge of tomorrow by institutional tinkering or by
submerging our sovereignty and our armed forces into supra-national
constructions.''
During the debate, Mr Rifkind covered the main issues of foreign policy,
including Nigeria.
He said Britain may take tougher action against Nigeria following last week's
execution of nine minority rights activists, including Ken Saro-Wiwa. He
refused to rule out further general sanctions against Nigeria, including the
freezing of their bank accounts and foreign assets.
Mr Rifkind also paid tribute to assassinated Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin and said that the peace process would continue despite his death.
</TEXT>
