<DOCNO>GH951117-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rumours of Lang  quitting seat denied</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339742</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOURCES close to Mr Ian Lang, President of the Board of Trade, yesterday
scotched rumours that he does not intend to contest his Galloway and Upper
Nithsdale seat at the General Election.
The rumours circulating in Scotland and at Westminster were described as
``complete and utter rubbish.''
The suggestion had been either that the Minister would be adopted by a more
secure English seat -joining the so-called ``chicken-run'' - or that he would
be leaving Parliament to concentrate on his business affairs, but both these
notions were completely discounted by sources.
At the last election Mr Lang, a former Scottish Secretary who has been Member
for Galloway since 1979, had a majority of 2468 over the Scottish Nationalist
candidate. Slight boundary changes make little difference to the electorate.
Last night, the chairman of the Conservative association in the constituency,
Mr William Kennedy, said of the rumour that he would not be standing again:
``That is absolute rubbish. Anyone suggesting that is going to be very
disappointed.
``Ian will be contesting this seat at the next General Election and he will win
it too.''
</TEXT>
