<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The catalytic conceptualist</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339743</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Saab's so-innovative
approach to engine
power is fired by
Per Gillbrand, who is
sharing his thoughts
with us this week.
PER GILLBRAND has been in Britain this week discussing his ideas about engine
design, a rare opportunity for one of the most ingenious lateral thinkers in
the motor industry to leave his Nordic lair.
The head of Engine Concept Development at Saab is an enthusiastic advocate of
turbocharging, and a man who believes that the conventional petrol engine still
has a great deal to offer in terms of improved performance, lower fuel
consumption and greatly reduced emissions - all from the same installation.
Using an exhaust gas turbocharger, which needs no mechanical power source to
run itself, and is operated by the exhaust flow being produced by the engine
anyway, what would otherwise be lost energy goes back into the system as a
performance booster.
It gives the turbo engine a power output attainable only by an unblown engine
of much bigger capacity, and thus more expensive to build in the first place,
as well as being a heavier load for the vehicle in which it is installed to
heave around.
Turbocharging is an integral part of Saab's new Ecopower engine specification,
seen in its early stages in the 1996 model-year 9000. Per Gillbrand is
confident that, as the programme develops, it will produce petrol engines able
to meet the American Ultra Low Emission Vehicles standard.
One important part of his emission reduction work concerns the catalytic
converter.
There is no doubt that this invention was forced on the motor industry before
its technology had matured. The environmental lobby paid no attention to
engineers' plaintive remarks that they had not yet reached the point of making
catalytic converters work properly from cold. It pressured the industry into
fitting the devices, then issued statements criticising manufacturers . . .
because catalytic converters did not work properly from cold.
Technically, a ``cold start'' does not mean something which happens on a winter
morning. It refers to an engine being started when its own temperature is below
85 degrees Centigrade. In other words, quite a lot of the time.
Swedish studies suggest that in the first few minutes after a cold start, many
engines produce as much pollution as they would over a 200-mile journey when
running warm. They may also use fuel at a rate of single-number miles per
gallon. Saab's intention is to fit electric engine-block heaters to be switched
on an appropriate time before the engine is started.
Another part of the Ecopower project, which also involves Saab's existing
highly sophisticated Trionic engine management, is a system which injects cold
water into the cylinders on the rare and brief occasions when the car is going
flat out, and therefore most likely to produce the highest emissions and worst
fuel consumption. The water spray reduces the temperature in the combustion
chambers from a critical level.
Where does the cold water come from? Another neat piece of lateral thinking
here. It is diverted from the windscreen-washer supply. And, yes, Gillbrand's
team is already figuring out what effect anti-freeze or other washer additives
may have.
Saab has also effectively reinvented the sparking plug. Instead of the familiar
arrangement of mounting the two electrodes across which the spark must leap at
the base of the plug itself, Per Gillbrand's idea is to have one electrode at
the bottom of the plug, and the other on the piston crown. This arrangement
produces a spark of 50,000 volts, far greater than any conventional plug can
handle, while the spark gap and timing can be optimised by the Trionic
management system.
The strong spark gives better and cleaner combustion. It will work with leaner
fuel/air mixtures than are generally possible now. Obviously, the less fuel in
the mixture, and the more efficiently it is burned, the lower the fuel
consumption and the fewer pollutants the combustion process will produce, even
before features like the catalytic converter come into play.
Per Gillbrand expects that these innovations will reach production level before
the end of the century. He has other schemes in mind too, like ``asymmetric''
turbocharging of the V6 engine, which involves a turbo unit driven by the
exhaust from just one bank of cylinders, but feeding boost to both.
When you consider that these developments are among the ones which are openly
admitted, and that there must be a host of others still kept under wraps, it is
easy to share his belief that the conventional petrol engine still has many
miles to go.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>THE LATERAL THINKERS WHO ONCE THOUGHT DIAGONALLY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339744</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF Saab has always been an innovative company, there is a good reason for it.
Founded in the Thirties as an aircraft manufacturer, the Swedish firm decided
in 1945 to enter the motor industry, despite the fact that it did not employ a
single person with experience of designing, developing, building, testing or
selling cars.
The prototype Saab 92 was ready the following spring. In a European industry
which elsewhere re-established itself with pre-war models having all the
aerodynamic subtlety of a block of flats, its wind-tunnel-inspired bodywork
looked like something from an alternative universe.
The 92 used a transversely-mounted engine driving the front wheels. Saab people
are understandably miffed when the praise for introducing this layout so often
goes to the Mini, which BMC launched in 1959.
Turbocharging, pollen-filtered ventilation and aircraft-inspired ``black
panel'' instrument displays were all Saab innovations in volume production
cars. Some projects, though, have been less well publicised.
During the era when the company used three-cylinder two-stroke engines, a
hush-hush experimental car was built with a pair of three-cylinder blocks
mounted in line. The straight-six engine thus created was so long it could not
be fitted either transversely or longitudinally in the production car's engine
bay. It is probably the only example on record of a saloon engine installed
diagonally.
This monstrous device could never have reached production, but it is exactly
the kind of daft project manufacturers should indulge in from time to time, to
let their designers and engineers rip.
The car was unexpectedly revealed, years later, at a factory open day. When it
was started up the racket was indescribable, but the few old hands who had been
in on the secret exchanged knowing grins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheriff warns students' attackers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339745</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPATE of ``student bashing'' in St Andrews will be stamped out, a court was
told yesterday.
Sheriff Charles Smith sentenced one attacker to 60 days in jail and another to
three months' detention. He said that recent assaults had resulted in almost
``a siege mentality'' within the town's 5000-strong student community.
The court heard that the police were reacting by increasing patrols in town
centre streets, and the university authorities were subsidising the purchase of
attack alarms and providing a free, safe bus service.
Graeme Henderson, 21, of Bothy Cottages, West Pitkierie, Anstruther, was jailed
at Cupar Sheriff Court on a total of six charges. Stuart Spence, 19, of
Sandyhill Crescent, St Andrews, was sentenced to detention.
They were involved in six incidents in St Andrews town centre in the space of
less than 30 minutes, during which one student was repeatedly punched and
robbed of #2 and another was assaulted and pushed through a large plate glass
shop window, causing damage estimated at #1000.
Henderson admitted threatening to kill a 20-year-old student if he told the
police.
Spence pled guilty to attacking an 18-year-old student by punching and kicking
him and pushing him through the shop window, and punching and kicking another
teenage student.
Mr Edward Russell, prosecuting, said that the student pushed through the window
had escaped with a small cut to his abdomen..
Mr Richard McFarlane, solictor, for Henderson, said that the accused's
recollection of the incidents were clouded because he had been drinking.
Spence's agent said that since the incidents, the accused had gained full-time
employment and had distanced himself from his previous circle of friends. ``He
has turned over a new leaf,'' he said.
</TEXT>
