<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Agony advice on when a nice girl should say `no'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339746</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``I WALK alone'' was a popular hit song a few decades ago. Mr Robin Cook, on
day two of the Queen's Speech debate, came close to suggesting that it would
make a good theme tune for the Government's European policy.
We are constantly, it seems, in a minority of one at get-togethers with our
European Union partners. Mr Major formed another such minority at the
Commonwealth Conference over French nuclear tests. Can we have an excess of
``finest hours'' in which we stand alone or was 1940 enough?
Mr Cook and Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind shaped up to each other like a
couple of agony aunts split over whether a girl should go with the crowd or not
be afraid to opt out if the crowd wanted her to do something a nice girl
wouldn't do.
Auntie Malcolm took the view that if a girl is invited to join a Social Chapter
or is offered new currency by Continentals urging her to ``integrate baby,''
the correct answer is ``Non''.
Auntie Robin, like Auntie Bob, believes ``it's good to talk''. Where does all
this being independent get you? Foreign trips are no fun. You end up a
wallflower.
He seemed to take the view that you chat to your pals, talk over what you will
want to do that evening and if your idea doesn't get the most votes you go
along with the majority. No point in opting out is his advice to his
correspondent, Brit for short.
Auntie Malcolm did not hesitate to point out that Auntie Robin's advice had
been potentially lethal in the past. Who was it who said a girl should not try
to defend herself if attacked? Who was it who once advised having nothing to do
with the neighbours until their smart houses and gleaming cars brought about a
rethink?
Come off it, said Auntie Robin. What about his paper's previous columnist,
Auntie Margaret, who had banged on for years about not getting intimately
involved with foreigners and then suddenly changed her advice and told Brit to
throw caution to the winds. As Brit sobbed to her mum later, it had only been a
single act but the consequences - as sometimes happens - would be with her for
years.
It is now pretty clear to those of us who read both papers that if poor Brit
tries to take the advice of both columnists she will turn into a schizophrenic.
Recently, she wrote to Uncle Michael for help, and was told sternly that all
foreign boys were after just one thing.
When she took her troubles to Auntie Robin, he sternly lectured her that Uncle
Michael's jingoistic approach to foreign boys was out of date 100 years ago.
Nowadays, if one of them invites a girl to go to, say, Maastricht, with him for
a week he might very well just want to talk.
Auntie Robin concluded that if a girl socialises and accepts a bit of
give-and-take she can have a wonderful time abroad. Auntie Malcolm is not so
sure. That sort of thing could lead to a girl losing her freedom of action, her
self respect and who knows what else.
Poor Brit - happy groupie or self-respecting wallflower. What is it to be?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
