<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Concern as Steel chairs country group</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE Environment Correspondent                                                      ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339747</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN organisation set up to represent rural interests, chaired by the former
Liberal leader Sir David Steel, was launched yesterday and immediately dubbed
``a wolf in sheep's clothing''.
Scottish conservationists expressed concern that the organisation had been set
up to represent the hunting and shooting lobby and to counteract recent
publicity engendered by anti-blood sports and animal rights activists.
Mr Simon Pepper, head of operations at the World Wide Fund for Nature Scotland,
said of the Countryside Movement: ``I think we are due an explanation to what
extent this movement, born at the same time as the Countryside Business Group,
represents the same aims.''
Mr Pepper pointed to statements by Mr Eric Bettelheim, founder of the
Countryside Business Group, which exhort landowners, sporting tenants, and
businessmen to win the war ``against our contemporary enemy, the animal rights
brigade''.
The CBG aims to spend between #3m and #4m campaigning for the preservation of
traditional country pursuits.
The Countryside Movement, which is being backed by the CBG, said yesterday it
planned to launch a #3.5m media campaign in its first year aimed at effecting a
widespread change in awareness in the countryside.
Mr Pepper said yesterday he found Sir David's involvement in the organisation
``puzzling''.
He added: ``I am also confused that a prominent Scottish public figure like Sir
David launching a countryside movement does not appear to have made contact
with two representative organisations - Scottish and Countryside Wildlife Link
and Rural Forum.''
Sir David could not be contacted for comment last night.
The director of the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds in Scotland, Mr
Stuart Housden, said the society had declined to participate in the new
movement.
One of the directors of the new body is the Duke of Westminster - a major
landowner in Sutherland as well as in England.
Mr Hywel Davies, chief executive of the Royal Highland and Agricultural Society
of Scotland, is also on the board.
Countryside offensive...16
</TEXT>
