<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scot tips waitress #60,000 for a few beers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339748</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE old chestnut that Scots are mean will surely be buried forever after a
Canadian waitress benefited to the tune of $125,000 (#60,000) after being
tipped by an expatriate Scot who had spent a mere $10.50 on beers.
Mr John Steele, 55, found he did not have enough money to tip his favourite
waitress, Ms Tracy Dalton, 24, during a regular visit to Al Mac's Bar in
Toronto on November 4.
Annoyed at his predicament, he signed and left his Lotto ticket with the
broadcasting student who splits her studies at York University with her bar
duties, insisting that   he would share any
winnings.
``I'm a cheap Scotsman,'' Mr Steele explained. ``So when I get tired of giving
money I'll just sign over a lottery ticket and say, `That one's a winner'.''
Ms Dalton, who put the ticket in her purse and  forgot about it, takes up the
story.
``Last Sunday, I was buying bread and thought, I might as well check the
ticket. It turned out to be worth $250,000 Canadian (#120,000).''
She did not see Mr Steele for another couple of days. On the Tuesday, the pair
picked up the money - and took half the total each.
Mr Steele, a motor-parts salesman, whose family emigrated to Canada when he was
a boy, plans to use his share of the proceeds to return to Scotland. He will
save the rest. Ms Dalton, meanwhile, plans to continue at university.
The normally canny Scot, by his own admission, said he had no regrets.
``If you're going to win, wouldn't you want to win with a friend,'' he said.
``Besides, you've got to pay for good service. Right?''
Ms Dalton, back behind the bar last night, was again pouring drinks for Mr
Steele. Asked how the tip of a lifetime rated, she replied: ``It's not a
standard 15%, that's for sure.''
Mr Steele, a bachelor from Lochore in Fife, emigrated in 1952 with his parents
and two sisters. He is a lifelong Rangers' fan and is a member of a Toronto
supporters club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wheatsheaf sale denied</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339749</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEARTS chairman Chris Robinson last night denied he had sold his catering
company Wheatsheaf Catering and was about to plough the profits into the
Edinburgh club.
Addressing the annual meeting of Hearts' shareholders in Edinburgh last night,
Mr Robinson said: ``I am certainly not about to walk away from Wheatsheaf
Catering, which has been my life for 18 years.
The 90th AGM of the club was attended by the largest gathering of shareholders
yet.
Mr Robinson gave a detailed financial report to the shareholders and revealed
there had been a ``#1.37m hole'' in terms of the club's borrowing facility.
The ``hole'' had included #200,000 from corporate subscribers which had not
been paid and an #87,000 bill to the Inland Revenue. Mr Robinson denied rumours
that directorships could be purchased for #100,000.
However, he did not rule out such a move in future but stressed the need for a
resolution of agreement from 75% of shareholders.
Mr Robinson also answered specific questions about the club's finances from
minorities shareholder spokesman Dr Gavin Kennedy, who was concerned that the
club was on the brink of receivership.
There was also a heated discussion about the team's finances with former
chairman, Mr Wallace Mercer, who made a surprise appearance.
Mr Mercer expressed his anger that Mr Robinson had blamed the club's financial
position on his tenure as chairman.
Angry exchanges................44
</TEXT>
