<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Painful blow for Ellis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339750</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRAHAM Ellis, the Currie hooker, has ruptured a biceps muscle in his left arm
and is out of the Scotland squad for the Test against Western Samoa at
Murrayfield tomorrow.
Ellis, who played for Scotland A against the tourists last weekend, and was on
the bench for tomorrow's international, was injured during a Scottish squad
session at Murrayfield on Wednesday night. The replacement hooker is Steve
Brotherstone, of Melrose.
The misfortune suffered by Ellis, who is receiving hospital treatment and may
be out of the game for eight weeks, continues the tale of woe which has
afflicted Scotland so far as candidates to fill the vacancy created by the
retirement of Kenny Milne is concerned.
Kevin McKenzie, of Stirling County, who was the heir apparent, did not come
into the reckoning for tomorrow's game as he has still not recovered from the
knee ligament damage sustained in a club game against Melrose.
Martin Scott, of Orrell, is also indisposed and the task of filling Milne's
boots has gone to the Hawick hooker, Jim Hay, who was a member of the Scotland
touring squad to Zimbabwe during the summer.
The Western Samoan wing-threequarter, Brian Lima, recovered from the hand
injury which kept him out of the side which defeated Scotland A at Hawick on
Sunday, represents the only change to that combination for the Test at
Murrayfield.
Meanwhile, hooker Onehanga Matauiau will join the Western Samoan party on
Sunday as the replacement for the injured Trevor Leota, who sustained
concussion in the match against North and Midlands at Perth on Tuesday night.
The mandatory three-week rest imposed on players with concussive injuries left
the Samoan management with no alternative but to send Leota back home.
Matauiau (22), who plays for the Moataa club in Apia and who captained the
Western Samoa under 21 side last season, will not join the touring party until
Sunday, the same day that Leota is expected to fly home.
Brendan Reidy, who was at loosehead against Edinburgh and North/Midlands, will
cover the hooker position as he did for the Samoans in the World Cup in South
Africa.
Western Samoa - V Patu; B Lima, T Vaega, G Leaupepe, A Tela; D Kellet, J
Filemu; M Mika, T Leiasamaivo, P Fatialofa, L Falaniko, P Leavasa, S Kaleta, P
Lam, S Vaifale. Replacements - M Vaea, C Burnes, S Leaega, S Smith, G Latu, B
Reidy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McPherson reveals that his mystery injury is a sore point FOOTBALL ROUND-UP</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339751</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MYSTERY injury is threatening to keep Hearts defender Davie McPherson out of
Sunday's Edinburgh derby against Hibernian at Tynecastle.
``In the last few games I did play, I was carrying what I thought was a groin
or a hamstring injury,'' he explained. ``At first, I couldn't run without pain,
which wasn't too bad, but eventually I couldn't run at all, so something had to
be done.''
A visit to a specialist failed to solve the puzzle, but if McPherson did not
know why he was hurting, he certainly knew where.
``Because I played with the injury, it affected my back and my legs. They seem
to be okay now, but I still have pain in another part of my anatomy which will
remain nameless. Let's just say I'd like to get to the bottom of things,'' he
joked.
Meantime, Hibs have an injury crisis. Counted out is striker Keith Wright, who
injured a hamstring at Falkirk last weekend, Graham Mitchell still will not be
ready, while Willie Miller and David Farrell are long-term injury victims.
Scotland Under-21 striker Kevin Harper injured a shoulder in training this week
and is toiling. But Andy Millen will return to the midfield, allowing Darren
Jackson to move forward into attack.
q.John Brown launched his book in Glasgow yesterday and warned that he was
ready to stay around until Rangers had won 10 titles in a row.
Asked if he would be able to help the club win their eighth successive title,
he answered: ``I want to be there for 10 in a row.''
But he warned: ``Celtic look as if they will push us all the way this season. I
think they are better prepared than they have been for some time. However, they
will be at Ibrox this weekend and we have to make sure that they do not
continue the good form they have shown at our place in recent years.''
Brown's book, Blue Grit, is published by Mainstream and is now available.
q.DUNDEE should have a full squad for tomorrow's Tayside derby at Tannadice,
while Dundee United are confident that defender Maurice Malpas will overcome
the ankle he injured last week against St Mirren.
q.MANAGER Alex McLeish is frustrated by an unprecedented injury crisis at
Motherwell. He admitted yesterday: ``I'll have to wait and see who turns up
with their boots before picking the team for Kilmarnock. The injury situation,
which has been horrendous all season, is now even worse after two more players
were crocked in training, and four others have gone down with a flu outbreak.
It's a worry in case it spreads even further.''
But Scotland defender Rob McKinnon has recovered from injury to lighten the
gloom.
q.ROY Hodgson, who recently took charge of the Italian giants Inter Milan, was
yesterday given the go-ahead to lead Switzerland in the European Championship
finals.
Swiss Soccer Federation Chief Giangiorgio Spiess was thought to be unhappy
about Hodgson's dual role, but confirmed yesterday that the Englishman would be
in charge of the Swiss in England next summer.
q.MARTIN O'Neill goes into hospital next week for a groin operation, and that
could bring a change in training methods at Clyde.
The Scotland Under-21 cap, who is being watched by a number of major clubs
including Aberdeen after requesting a transfer, will be out for up to three
weeks.
Concerned about the number of groin strains suffered in training, manager Alex
Smith said yesterday: ``From now on we will train in the same kind of boots
that we play in, to see if that will make a difference.''
Central defender Jim Thomson is emerging as the latest transfer target. Dundee
United could follow up their interest in Thomson, who spent last week training
at Tannadice.
q.BLACKBURN  and Dundee United are front-runners to snap up Caledonian's Iain
Stewart.
Watched by Blackburn, Scotland's top scorer took his tally to 15 goals in 13
games with a double at Hampden last Saturday, while United are understood to be
highly impressed after several trips to eye the 26-year-old trainee driving
instructor.
Meanwhile, Thistle's classy teenage defender Richard Hastings has been watched
by Liverpool, Celtic, and Dundee United.
q.BP YOUTH Cup-holders Rangers have a home tie against Motherwell in the fourth
round. The full draw, made yesterday, is:
Raith Rovers v St Mirren, Partick Thistle v Aberdeen, Falkirk v Kilmarnock,
Hearts v St Johnstone, Rangers v Motherwell, Dunfermline v Dundee, Hamilton v
Dundee United, Celtic v Hibernian. Ties to be played by December 10.
</TEXT>
