AUSTRALIAN MASTERS
BRITAIN'S Laura Davies made a disastrous start to her campaign to win a third
successive Alpine Australian Ladies Masters title at the Royal Pines on the
Gold Coast yesterday.
Davies twice found herself in water off the tee and was unhappy with her
opening round score of 72 in the #150,000 event, which left her six shots
adrift off the pace.
Swedish pair Annika Sorenstam and Liselotte Neumann shot seven-under-par rounds
of 66 to share the first-round lead after they both hit eight birdies.
They hold a one-shot advantage over Australian duo Karen Lunn and Jennifer
Sevil while English pair Alison Nicholas and Caroline Hall were among a large
group one shot further back.
Davies admitted: ``It was not a fun day. It's hard to give players like Annika
six shots. I'll have to shoot three rounds in the low 60s to have a shot at it.
I'm not packing my bags, but I haven't made it easy for myself.''
Neumann predicted the British star could still make a challenge, insisting:
``She is such a great player she is capable of just about anything on this golf
course.
``The greens here are in superb condition - the best I've ever played on. If
you get your ball on line, it sticks on the line and goes in. I could have shot
four or five less. I had a lot of chances.'' Leading scores (Australian unless
