<HEADLINE>Socket shot forgotten Form man Lane finds sweet spot DUNLOP PHOENIX OPEN:</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET McMASTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339753</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND'S Barry Lane, in a late-season Indian summer vein of form, matched the
weather with a flawless seven under par 64 in the first round of the #1.3m
Dunlop Phoenix tournament, the richest in Japan, in Miyazaki yesterday.
Lane is something of a course specialist after finishing runner-up to Ernie Els
here two years ago and third behind Jumbo Ozaki last year - a double bogey 5 at
the seventeenth scuppered him then.
``There's a long way to go,'' the 35-year old cautioned, ``but I'm playing well
and it's about time I won again. I was second in the European Open, second in
the European Masters, and second in the Kapalua International the other week.
``I picked up a new Mizuno driver on Wednesday and I hit the ball well and
putted beautifully. I don't think I had to chip once.''
Lane thus avoided any shanking - he had the first socket of his career last
Sunday - and found himself leading a distinguished field by one shot. The
inevitable Ozaki, the defending champion, was second on 65 and is determined to
prevent the upstart Satoshi Higashi, currently leading the Japanese money list,
from finishing the season No.1. In these parts what Jumbo determines Jumbo
usually gets.
Five-times Open champion Tom Watson, winner here in 1980 and second last year,
shared third place after a five-birdie 66. ``I was happy,'' he professed. ``I
did everything all right and my putting, for the most part, was good. It was
the perfect day to score, with hardly any breeze, although there were certain
places you didn't want to be in the rough. I got two good lies and two awkward
ones, but no difficult ones.''
Els was leading the field after going out in 31, five under, but finished with
a 68 because of a fit of pique. After three-putting the fourteenth, the giant
Springbok, irritated, threw his putter at his bag. It broke in two and Els
opted to use his sand iron on the greens for the last four holes. As a result
he bogeyed the sixteenth and seventeenth, but two-wedged for a birdie 4 after
reaching the 534-yard eighteenth in two.
``I've won several tournaments, including the US Open and the World Matchplay
with that putter,'' Els said. ``It didn't deserve that.'' Leading scores
