<HEADLINE>Norman the decade's brightest star</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339754</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREG Norman has been by far the dominant figure in the Sony world rankings,
which has just completed its 500th week and is approaching the end of the tenth
year of its existence. Since 1986 the Australian has held the No.1 position for
231 of those weeks and is the only player never to have been lower than tenth
on the list.
Indeed, Norman, whose worst placing was seventh in 1992, has become the US
Tour's leading money-winner with $9.5m since he joined it in 1983, the year
after he had finished first on the European order of merit - the only golfer to
have completed that particular dual achievement.
In the past decade only six other professionals have occupied the pole position
and among them they have won 19 major championships and been No.1 on either the
European or US Tours. They are Nick Faldo, Severiano Ballesteros, Ian Woosnam,
Nick Price, Fred Couples, and Bernhard Langer.
Faldo is a long way behind Norman in the number of weeks he has led, but his
total of 97 includes the record of 81 in succession. The five others were first
among equals for 60, 50, 43, 16, and three weeks respectively. However, an
imminent change in the grading system may alter cases, if only slightly.
At the end of 1995 the three-year ``rolling period'' is to be changed to a
two-year system, placing more emphasis on the current 12-month period. It will
thereby come into line with the policy of the world's principal professional
tours and of the Royal and Ancient Club and the United States Golf Association
of granting championship and tournament exemptions and team invitations in
recognition of more up-to-date form.
