<HEADLINE>Bath's No.8 a victim again of stiff competition Back-row blues for Peters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975339755</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ERIC Peters will be sitting in front of his television set in Bath when his
erstwhile Scottish comrades-in-arms lock horns with the Western Samoans
tomorrow afternoon at Murrayfield.
Peters, the find of the last Five Nations' Championship campaign, is out of
favour and out the side. To add insult to injury he will have to wait until
close of business at Twickenham, where England entertain the Springboks, before
he can watch televised highlights of the Murrayfield game.
It's been a rough couple of weeks for the amiable Peters. First, he was dropped
by Scotland in favour of Stuart Reid, and then he played at blindside
wing-forward, as opposed to his favoured berth at No.8, as Scotland A succumbed
to the Samoans at Hawick on Sunday.
Reid, the Boroughmuir No.8, has undoubtedly been playing well and deserves his
international call-up. The problem facing the Scotland selectors was one of
blend in the back-row and they have gone for Gloucester's Ian Smith as a
genuine open-side replacement for the retired Iain Morrison.
There was a case to be made for playing Reid, Peters, and Rob Wainwright as an
admittedly one-paced back-row unit, but the selectors have dismissed it for the
time being, at least.
Peters, 26, a surveyor by profession, learned of his demotion in a phone call
from Murrayfield the night before the team details were announced. ``I was
surprised, but you have to take the knocks and use them as a spur to get back.
I was told that there wasn't a major problem with my form but they thought that
Stuart Reid deserved his chance and you can't really argue with that.''
The former Cambridge University captain, who was born in Glasgow from good
Dumbarton stock, was reluctant to be interviewed for fear that he could be
accused of upsetting the apple-cart.
``I don't want this to appear as if I'm moaning on the sidelines, because I'm
not,'' said Peters. ``I want to win back my place in the Scotland side and it's
up to me to prove that I can do it. That's why the Inter-district Championship
will be so important to the Exiles and to me personally.
``I knew that Stuart Reid had been getting rave reviews in the press. I knew
that Rob would be in the side and I suspected, too, that Ian Smith would be in.
Therefore I knew that if Stuart was pushing then he would be pushing against
me.''
But competition for a back-row slot is not new territory for Peters. It is
something that he experiences weekend in and weekend out at Bath. Thereby may
hang at least part of the answer to his exclusion.
The former Scotland coach, Dougie Morgan, who now manages the A side, dropped
the heaviest of hints at the team selection news conference that Peters would
benefit from regular first XV rugby and that he would, certainly, be guaranteed
that if he were to up sticks and move to Scotland.
Peters is aware of that school of thought but still relishes the challenge of
securing a regular first-team berth at the Recreation Ground. ``I had been with
Saracens, but after university I went to Bath and I did so because they are the
premier club in Europe with superb facilities and coaching set-up.
``I knew when I went that they had five internationalist back-row players all
battling each week for a regular position. With Dave Egerton, Jon Hall, Andy
Robinson, Ben Clarke and Steve Ojomoh all trying to get into the back-row I
knew that it wasn't going to be an easy ride, but I relished the challenge,''
said Peters. ``Dave and Jon have now retired, so it's getting easier.
``I've been getting games at No.6 in the first team. I would prefer No.8,
because it is a more constructive position in terms of attack but there are
quite a few similarities between blindside and No.8.''
So far as enlisting on the Scottish club scene is concerned, Peters cites again
the fact that he is happy to compete for a regular place at Bath and, again,
underlines that the English side is the foremost club in Europe.
``It may well be that I could get regular first-team rugby in Scotland, but I'm
sure that I can get it down here, too. That's the challenge I've set myself and
I aim to succeed.''
What will happen next season when English clubs - and presumably Bath will be
involved - are competing in the new European Cup alongside Scottish district
sides (if indeed Scotland follows the district route) is for the moment a
matter of conjecture. Would, for instance, Bath be happy to see their exiles
enrol with a Scottish district and compete against them in Europe?
``I just don't know what will happen. It hasn't been decided yet what the
structure is going to be and it certainly hasn't filtered down to the clubs yet
so, at the moment, it is a big grey area,'' said Peters.
</TEXT>
