<HEADLINE>Sloppy play, but South ease to a handsome victory</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339757</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PALTRY crowd of around 150 witnessed a convincing South victory at Netherdale
last night.
The home side registered a deluge of points, scoring six tries, but a plethera
of knock-ons, sloppy passes, and misplaced enthusiasm for the wrong option had
the brave spectators in the bitter weather checking their watches regularly and
clapping their hands in prayer for the final whistle.
Selkirk stand-off Scott Nichol impressed, scoring a hat trick of tries -
including the opener in five minutes - in a fine all-round display which showed
himself to be one of the most astute and accurate kickers in open play in
Scotland.
However, it was full back Graeme Aitchison who put the much needed points on
the board with a personal haul of 26 points with a try, three penalties, and
six conversion.
His touchdown and conversion just before the interval - closely following
another by winger Mark Moncrieff, who had waltzed round four visiting players -
made the game safe at 32-17.
Winger Keith Suddon also weighed in with a try and Kelso flanker Stewart Bennet
grabbed a well deserved touchdown.
The South African scorers were Marthinus, Fourie, Horn and captain Jaarsveld,
with a try apiece, while Markram slotted three conversions.
The brightest moment among periods of tedium came at the start of the second
half.
South African stand-off Markram received the ball while still putting on his
shirt. With it half on he took off from his twenty-two and sliced through the
South back division. He then kicked the ball over Aitchison, pulled his shirt
over his head, and joined the race for the ball, now bobbling near to the South
line.
Moncrieff won the race and to a great sigh of disappointment from the crowd the
entertaining South African was penalised for not allowing the South winger to
return to his feet.
