<HEADLINE>Lights shine on schools' team SCHOOLS RUGBY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339758</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Schools open their representative programme tonight at Meggetland,
where they face Scotland Under-18 in what has become an important fixture for
both sides. Important, certainly in the short term, for Scottish Schools, who
play their French counterparts next month at Goldenacre before facing Welsh
Schools at Bridgend on January 6.
This will be the first time that many of the schools' side will have
experienced playing under floodlights but Keith Yuille, the Scottish Schools
coach, thinks that this could be useful for his team. ``When we play Wales at
Bridgend it will be an evening match,'' he said.
This season's schools' team have a difficult act to follow, albeit that their
immediate predecessors achieved only one victory - the 20-18 win over Wales at
Goldenacre. But the narrow defeats by Australia (18-17) and England (19-14) and
a good showing against New Zealand all proved that Scottish Schools are now
able to compete against the best.
``We tried to play exciting rugby against these teams by attacking them and not
merely trying to contain them,'' said Yuille, whose side for the opening game
of this season has been picked ``to play an expansive game.''
He added: ``We have considerable pace in the back three, all of whom are
capable of scoring, and creativity in the centre. The difference this season is
that we do not have a big      physical presence in midfield.''
``It is a big bonus having Gordon Ross back at stand-off as well as Fergie
Gladstone and Jason White in the pack. The experience they picked up last
season from playing in six internationals will be vital for us.''
Selecting White, who was capped as a lock last season, at blindside flanker is
something of a gamble for the Schools but the George Watson's College forward
has had considerable back row experience having played No.8 while at Cults
Academy.
``It will give us another option in the lineout,'' said Yuille, who reckons
that the Schools this season will field a ``much more physical pack.''
One feature of the Schools side this season is that the squad of 22 represents
a wider geographical spread. ``We are simply looking for the best regardless of
what school they come from. The message must be to all districts is that if
they have good players then they will be selected,'' says Yuille.
Among the squad of 22 for the match tonight will be representatives from
Dunfermline High School, Queen Victoria High School, Eastwood High School and
Douglas Ewart High School. It is a welcome indication, perhaps, that schools
rugby, helped considerably by the SRU youth development programme, is again
beginning to flourish outside its more traditional boundaries.
q WORLD Cup winner Joel Stransky has had a memorable season - and that's the
way he wants it to stay against England at Twickenham tomorrow.
The Springboks have won 13 games on the spin, a run highlighted by their 15-12
triumph over New Zealand last summer when Stransky kicked the vital goal in
extra time to snatch the global crown.
``We have had a great season, but your last game is how they judge you. If we
lost against England at Twickenham it would be a big dampener for us,'' said
fly-half Stransky, who is looking forward to meeting opposite number Mike Catt.
Catt, who replaces Mr Golden Boot Rob Andrew, was rebuked by manager Jack
Rowell this week for labelling South Africa's captain Francois Pienaar ``an
average player''.
</TEXT>
