<HEADLINE>Not a level playing field ARENA ALAN R IRONS, PRESIDENT, CARETHA QUEEN'S PARK RFC AND ACTING CHAIRMAN, SCOTTISH RUGBY CLUBS' ASSOCIATION</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN R IRONS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339759</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WINNING the Player of the Month award for October, Graeme Beveridge, of
Boroughmuir, is hailed as one of a number of young players reaching the highest
levels of Scottish rugby, and thus a tribute to the Scottish Rugby Union's
youth development policy. Maybe - but no tribute to his club's youth policy.
Since primary school, Beveridge has been coached, transported, fed hot-dogs by
Peebles rugby club under their long-standing commitment to youth rugby. And
just as their investment was about to pay off Beveridge, at 19, moved on.
What return on their efforts can clubs have when this happens? What incentive
is there to bring on young players, to see them mature into good footballers
only to watch as they are snapped up by senior clubs, many without a youth
section.
But why should the clubs who devote enormous resources watch their efforts
being exploited by clubs who may not have made such a commitment?
The SRU youth development policy was an initiative. It was taken up by clubs
outwith the top flight to ensure a supply of players to enable clubs to improve
their standing. Such clubs are powerless to prevent the haemorrhage of their
best young players.
Control must be exercised over the movement of young players when avaricious
senior clubs are sweeping up all the available talent.
The Scottish Rugby Clubs Association, which represents the majority of national
league clubs, believes that a system of registration of players is essential.
Clubs should decide which players to register, from age 16 upwards, with a
limit on the number aged 18 or over. Only registered players would be eligible
for championship and cup matches. If a club wished to introduce a new player to
its squad, an existing member would be de-registered.
The effect of this would be three-fold: a club with a youth policy would hold
the registrations of its young players; it would prevent clubs from amassing
large numbers of players; and it would enable de-registered players to move to
another club where a first-team place was more certain.
Players would be registered and re-registered annually and no player could
register for another club without the agreement of the club holding his
registration. There would be criteria under which players could change clubs,
the most obvious being change of residence or on taking up tertiary education.
However, any young player, ie up to age 21, who no longer satisfied the
conditions for such a transfer, would automatically be re-registered with his
original club.
No club will stand in the way of talented players who wish to try their hand at
a higher level. A club would voluntarily allow a player to transfer his
registration but for players between 16 and 21 this should attract mandatory
compensation to the holding club for its investment in its youth. A fee might
be negotiated for older players.
There should be a qualifying period of, say, three or four months following
change of registration. There should be a fallow period from April to July,
during which no registrations would be permitted, and no part of this period
would count towards the qualifying period. If registration was effective on 1
October each year, it would enable club squads to settle at the start of each
season but would allow players to be released or to move early in the season.
Where do the SRU stand?
Accused. It is widespread practice for young players selected for
representative squads at age-group levels to find themselves being approached
by squad officials, often appointed by the SRU, to move to their (more senior)
club. For too long the SRU has turned a blind eye to this abuse of position and
the poaching of players more generally. It must act if youth development is not
to be blighted.
And condemned. The SRU has threatened to throw clubs who cannot fulfil fixtures
out of the championship and has questioned whether such clubs should
participate in the leagues. But loss of players to more senior clubs
contributes, or indeed may be the primary cause of, these clubs' problems.
It has been suggested that clubs in the championship should meet certain
criteria. One would be to require all such clubs to have established and
credible mini and midi rugby sections at all levels by 2000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
