<HEADLINE>Open  warfare</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GILLIAN DORRICOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339760</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BADMINTON
SCOTTISH Badminton Union chief executive Anne Smillie has hit out at what she
describes as a ``nonsense'' draw the International Federation has imposed upon
the Scottish Open.
``Players like former All-England Champion Ib Frediriksen have been asked to
pre-qualify for the men's singles,'' said Smillie. ``Meanwhile players who are
not up to his standard have been allowed into the main draw.''
The irrational state of affairs is a direct result of the IBF's new
computerised draw system, which only recognises players' current positions in
the world rankings, regardless of how many tournaments in which they have
played.
Former Scottish Open winners Maria and Catrine Bengtsson of Sweden have not
been seeded in the women's doubles, although they are the experts' tip to lift
the title at the Kelvin Hall next week.
Former national champion Jim Mailer of Stirling heads a section of the men's
singles dominated by fellow Scots. Five out of seven players in his section are
compatriots.
</TEXT>
