<HEADLINE>Scots stay in the hunt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339762</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND, despite wins in four of their six matches yesterday, still find
themselves trailing leaders England by nine points going into the penultimate
day of the European Indoor Team Championship in Jersey.
The Scots have a total of 33 points, with England leading on 42, followed by
Wales on 40.
Scotland faced Ireland in the men's and women's singles and fours yesterday and
won three of their four matches.
Graham Robertson led the way when he beat Jeremy Henry 7-6, 7-1, 1-7, 7-4 and
then both Scottish rinks added wins.
Angus Blair's men beat Noel Graham's side 21-12, thanks to a strong finishing
burst in which the Scots turned an 11-11 scoreline into a nine-shot win, while
Jeanette Conlan's women were never behind en route to a 19-13 victory over
Dessa Baird's side.
Ireland's consolation win came from world outdoor champion Margaret Johnston,
who won in four sets against Tweedbank's Joyce Lindores. Johnston took the
opener 7-0 in just three ends but Lindores battled to a 7-5 nine-end win in the
second. Johnston took the third set 7-5, and then dominated the next to win it
7-2.
East Lothian's Robertson got back on the winning way last night, and in some
style, when he picked up the three points on offer for a straight-sets singles
win, needing just 14 ends to beat Stephen Rees 7-2, 7-3, 7-0.
``I was playing well and Stephen was struggling a bit, but the way things are
going for Scotland we need all the points we can get, and winning this one in
straight sets was definitely a bonus,'' said Robertson.
However, his team-mates in the fours failed to capitalise when they went down
24-18 to the local Jersey side.
The Scots trailed 6-4 after six ends, and then dropped 11 shots while they
picked up just 2 as Jersey went on to a comfortable win.
England edged ahead of Wales at the top of the table for the first time since
the event began last Sunday when they notched up wins last night over Jersey in
the singles and Ireland in the fours.
World champion Andy Thomson, who had to come from two sets to one down earlier
in the day to beat Guernsey's John Queripel, completed the Channel Island
double when he beat Jersey's David Le Marquand 7-4, 4-7, 7-4, 7-2.
England added the points in the fours when David Holt, Gary Smith, Greg Harlow,
and Tony Allcock notched up their second win of the day.
Last night battled to a 22-17 win over Noel Graham's Irish rink. Earlier, they
had beaten Guernsey 27-12. Results:
Men. Singles - G Robertson (Scotland) beat J Henry (Ireland) 7-6, 7-1, 1-7,
7-4; A Thomson (England) beat J Queripel (Guernsey) 3-7, 7-4, 0-7, 7-4, 7-9; S
Rees (Wales) beat D Le Marquand (Jersey) 7-1, 7-4, 4-7, 7-3; Robertson beat
Rees 7-2, 7-3, 7-0; Henry beat Queripel 7-1, 7-2, 7-6; Thomson beat D Le
Marquand 7-4, 4-7, 7-4, 7-2.
Fours - Scotland 21, Ireland 12; England 27, Guernsey 12; Wales 17, Jersey 14;
Wales beat Guernsey 34-12; England beat Ireland 22-17; Jersey beat Scotland
24-18.
Women. Singles - M Johnston (Ireland) beat J Lindores (Scotland) 7-0, 5-7, 7-5,
7-2; A Simon (Guernsey) beat J Roylance (England) 7-3, 7-6, 7-5; V Stead
(Jersey) beat R Jones (Wales) 7-4, 1-7, 7-6, 1-7, 7-1. Fours - England 23,
Guernsey 17; Scotland 19, Ireland 13; Wales 18, Jersey 18.
BOWLING
</TEXT>
