<HEADLINE>Atherton bruised, battered, but not bewildered Ton-up Hick shows he's the master at Centurion</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339763</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRAEME Hick punched the air in jubilation last night after having scored a
superb hundred at Centurion Park, Pretoria. The Worcestershire batsman reached
the fourth century of his international career just before bad light halted
play five overs early in this first Test against the South Africans.
And when he left the field to a standing ovation, Hick had just about completed
a memorable England recovery.
His undefeated 105 - studded with 21 boundaries - helped the tourists to end
the first day on an encouraging 221 for four.
But he was by no means the only hero. Courageous captain Mike Atherton - who
shared a stand of 142 with Hick - had been the rock off which England's
fightback was launched.
Atherton gritted his teeth and withstood a near six-hour battering from South
Africa's six-pronged pace attack before falling for 78.
He had seen England slump to 64 for three but refused to budge until dismissed
two overs before the premature close of play.
Atherton was struck three times on his protective headgear, and once on the
shoulder, as Allan Donald and company tried to wear him down.
But the England skipper simply would not buckle in the face of South Africa's
pace attack after Alec Stewart, Mark Ramprakash and Graham Thorpe all had
fallen cheaply.
The early stages of this first Test between the two countries in South Africa
since 1965 had looked like turning into a nightmare for England.
But defiant opener Atherton worked his way past 50 and, with Hick's support,
led the team towards calmer waters.
England, having been put in, were facing a near non-stop diet of fast bowling,
and while South Africa could talk about the necessity of playing to their
strengths, it hardly made for easy watching.
A spinner - the very occasional Gary Kirsten - was finally introduced for the
seventy-seventh over of the day. But until then, the nearest the home team got
to some variety was when captain Hansie Cronje brought himself on as bowler No.
6 - and even he sends down medium pace.
At lunch, however, South Africa had been cock-a-hoop, though England's problems
at that stage were mostly of their own making.
Stewart, with 6, could consider himself a shade unlucky to fall in the tenth
over, pulling left-armer Brett Schultz towards backward square leg where Craig
Matthews, diving right, held an acrobatic one-handed catch.
But the shot was not properly controlled and South Africa are famous for their
fine fielding.
Ramprakash's exit for 9, which left England tottering on 36 for two, was even
more disappointing.
The Middlesex batsman had looked composed for half an hour. But, as too often
before, he let himself down - playing a loose shot outside off stump against
Donald to present keeper Dave Richardson with his one hundredth catch at this
level.
It comes as no surprise to learn that Richardson has never achieved a Test
stumping. Let's face it, he doesn't get much chance.
Thorpe, on 13, was the last of the morning victims, departing during the final
over of the session.
Shaun Pollock, the 22-year-old debut maker, produced a good delivery that left
Thorpe just enough to clip the outside edge and give Richardson victim No 101.
Atherton had made 34 by lunch and he went on to pass 50 for the thirty-fourth
time in his ninety-seventh Test innings.
Hick overtook him after tea but needed one slice of luck. On 67, the
Worcestershire batsman drove a gentle return catch to Matthews, but the
shin-high chance was spilled.
Despite that blemish, Hick's innings was full of confidence and his final
mission of the day was to help Atherton see off the second new ball.
If ever a man deserved to bat through the day, it was Atherton. But the third
over of the new ball finally brought his downfall.
Pollock banged in a short delivery, Atherton could only fend it off to gully
and Donald held a simple catch.
Atherton had been at the crease for 341 minutes while scoring 78 and leading
England to 206 for four.
It was vital the tourists did not waste his hard work - and Hick soon completed
an excellent century to underpin that effort. He reached his ton by cutting
Donald for his twentieth boundary. Scoreboard:
