<HEADLINE>Union delights</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339764</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW League cricket clubs were celebrating last night after Western Union
officials rubber-stamped a proposal to admit eight city sides, and Dumfries
from the Borders, into a second division from next season. The decision, taken
at the Union's AGM, wiped out more than 100 years of tradition.
Helensburgh secretary Barry Williams said: ``This is great news and a fantastic
incentive for the new second division clubs to improve their standards.'' GHK's
retiring skipper Jim Forrest added: ``Glasgow clubs have shown in cup
competitions that they can hold their own in one-off situations. But this is a
whole new challenge."
Union officials had hoped to have a 10-club lower division with promotion and
relegation from next season. But their plans were hit for six when Ayrshire
opted to join the new Scottish League. Last night's meeting agreed to put
promotion on hold.
</TEXT>
