<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kibreet one for Hobbs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WHITE and GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339765</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KIBREET can underline trainer Philip Hobbs's talents with victory in the
Manicou Chase at Ascot today. A move to the West Country has revitalised the
gelding who showed ability in his younger days and was once described as ``the
new Barnbrook Again'' by his first trainer, David Elsworth.
The eight-year-old served notice that he was about to start fulfilling his
promise when second to Big Matt on his debut for Hobbs last spring. And there
was no mistaking the quality of his reappearance in a competitive event at
Chepstow earlier this month.
Ridden from the front, he had the race won a long way out and strolled to a
12-length triumph.
Kibreet looks to have left his days as a modest performer behind and Hobbs has
clearly found the key to him. He can follow up this afternoon on a course where
front-runners are often very hard to catch.
Silver Groom can land another useful prize for trainer Reg Akehurst in the
closing hurdle. The five-year-old has been a money-spinner on the Flat, gaining
his biggest success in the William Hill Cup at Goodwood in July. There are big
races to be won with him over hurdles judged on the ease with which he landed
the odds at Sandown on his reappearance a fortnight ago.
Last season's jumping problems look to have been ironed out and he could well
develop into a leading contender for January's big race at Leopardstown for
which this is a trial.
Large Action is the clear choice on form in the Ascot Hurdle - he has been
placed in the last two Champion Hurdles yet carries bottom weight here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
