<HEADLINE>Pauline saves British blushes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339766</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOMEN'S HOCKEY:
PAULINE Robertson, the Scottish captain, yesterday helped salvage a point for
Great Britain in their opening match of the Olympic qualifying tournament
against Canada, who were expected to be one of the weaker sides in the Cape
Town event.
The Canadians, who were short of attacking ideas, spent most of the 70 minutes
directing their attentions towards erecting a defensive barrier, but while it
won them a point in a 1-1 draw, it did nothing to enhance the reputation of the
sport.
Despite their reluctance to attack Great Britain, it was Canada who opened the
scoring in 24 minutes when Tammy Holt could hardly believe her luck when a
clearance from the British keeper, Jo Thompson, went straight to her stick.
Holt was left with an easy task to score, but Canada's advantage was
short-lived.
Robertson, as usual a source of influence to the British side, forced the
equaliser five minutes later, and for the remainder of an easily forgotten game
were camped inside Canadian territory - but to no avail.
Britain, who started the match with three Scots in the side, Roberston, Susan
MacDonald, and Susan Fraser, and then introduced Rhona Simpson and Diane
Renilson as substitutes, will see this scoreline as a point dropped.
It was envisaged that Great Britain would struggle to finish among the five
qualifiers for Atlanta, but now the task facing them will be even more
formidable.
Argentina, World Cup finalists, are unlikely to encounter similar problems for
they are now the clear leaders, having beaten Korea 1-0 with a goal by Cecilia
Pagnoni, to become the first side to register a second successive victory.
Results:
Great Britain 1, Canada 1; Argentina 1, Korea 0.
Today's games - South Africa v Holland, China v Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
