<HEADLINE>'Hill rely on young brigade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Josephy Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339767</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEN'S HOCKEY
WHEN Jimmy Cox, Kevin Squire, Graham Wylie and Davy Stott left Menzieshill at
the start of the season, the future did not look bright for the Taysiders, but
they have responded to the challenge with the usual determination, writes
Joseph Dillon.
They go into the final series of games before the mid-season break tomorrow
against MIM just one point off the pace which has been set by defending
champions Grange. Indeed, it's not in the realms of fantasy to suggest that
when hostilities resume again in February, they will be top of the table.
The Menzieshill revival has taken the game by surprise - as well as the club
itself. Bruce Cuthill, their player coach, joked: ``It is because we got rid of
some dead wood.'' But in reality, he might not be too far off the mark.
The club has been forced to give youth its chance - like 17-year-old Neil
Devine, who has come into the side and established himself, while men on the
fringe, Chris Anderson and Ross Yule, now seem to accept greater responsibility.
Another explanation for the good run of Menzieshill is that on the opening day
of the season, they defeated arch- rivals MIM by 4-0.
Their confidence received a tremendous boost, and they have not looked back.
The teams meet for a second time tomorrow at Maryfield.
The remaining games should be clear cut, provided of course Grange don't allow
Insights Inverleith's reputation for producing the unexpected get to them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
