<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plea for patience</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339768</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORSPORT
NEW Ferrari team-mates Michael Schumacher and Eddie Irvine pleaded for patience
yesterday in their bid to put the Italian team back on top of Formula 1.
They have paid big money to lure world champion Schumacher from Benetton and
Ulsterman Irvine from Jordan in an attempt to bring back the glory days.
But Schumacher, winner of the world title for the last two years, was careful
to make no promises after his first appearance as a Ferrari driver.
``Expectations will certainly be high,'' he said after driving 20 laps in a car
powered by Ferrari's new V10 engine at their Maranello base. ``But like any
team, we will need time to work together and grow together. I'm sure the
potential is there for Ferrari to be world champions, but it will take a
while.''
His new team-mate Irvine was also cautious, saying: ``Do not expect miracles.''
Schumacher's signing was part of a costly shake-up by Ferrari, who have been
living in the shadow of Benetton and Williams over the last two seasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951117-000180</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951117-000180</DOCID>
<DATE>951117</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hendry's hopes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975339769</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNOOKER
WORLD champion Stephen Hendry must hope he is not 12 months too late with the
launch of his new coaching book - ``Snooker Masterclass'' - during the Royal
Liver Assurance UK Championship, which starts in Preston today.
In 1994, the 26-year-old Scot compiled seven century breaks in 12 frames
against Irish stablemate Ken Doherty. The previous year against John Parrott in
the semi-finals he chalked up five tons in seven frames.
Now he hopes to repeat those extraordinary feats and successfully defend the
title. Facing Hendry over the best of 17 frames when the #380,000 tournament
gets under way is young compatriot Jamie Burnett of Hamilton.
q ALAN Burnett's hopes of adding the Embassy IBSF World Amateur Championship to
the World Junior crown he collected earlier in the year stayed on course
yesterday when he won his latest group qualifying tie in Bristol. The Ayrshire
teenager made it six wins out of six with a 4-3 victory over Jonathan Nelson of
Northern Ireland.
</TEXT>
